1
00:00:22,607 --> 00:00:25,525
## [Jazz Band]

2
00:01:33,552 --> 00:01:36,554
## [Jazz Continues]

3
00:02:21,517 --> 00:02:23,476
Hi, Toivo.

4
00:02:27,231 --> 00:02:29,441
Hey. Your pal just drove into town,
Mr. McCarthy.

5
00:02:31,986 --> 00:02:35,322
I'll have one more, Toivo.

6
00:02:35,406 --> 00:02:38,158
I'm afraid I'll have to pay
my bar bill tomorrow.

7
00:02:38,242 --> 00:02:40,285
You're good with me, Mr. McCarthy.

8
00:02:40,369 --> 00:02:42,329
Thank you, Toivo.

9
00:02:47,668 --> 00:02:50,670
- Good night, Toivo.
- Good night, Mr. McCarthy.

10
00:04:54,837 --> 00:04:56,629
[Woman] Operator.

11
00:04:57,423 --> 00:05:02,302
Operator, I want, uh, 489, Thunder Bay.

12
00:05:02,386 --> 00:05:04,429
I want to speak to Mrs. Manion.

13
00:05:04,513 --> 00:05:07,015
M-A-N-I-O-N.

14
00:05:07,099 --> 00:05:11,019
This is Paul Biegler speaking.
Iron City, 700.

15
00:05:11,103 --> 00:05:13,605
[Train Bell Clanging]

16
00:05:23,115 --> 00:05:26,242
- Well, do they know when she'll be there?
- No, they don't.

17
00:05:26,327 --> 00:05:30,121
I see. Well, just leave a message,
and tell her to call this number.

18
00:05:30,206 --> 00:05:32,165
Thank you.

19
00:05:33,584 --> 00:05:36,294
All right.
What do you say there, counselor?

20
00:05:36,378 --> 00:05:38,338
Save your money.

21
00:05:40,674 --> 00:05:42,592
What's in the brown paper bag?

22
00:05:42,676 --> 00:05:45,887
- [Faucet Running]
- It might be a cabbage head.

23
00:05:45,971 --> 00:05:47,889
But it wouldn't be.

24
00:05:47,973 --> 00:05:50,683
You're a very suspicious man.

25
00:05:52,686 --> 00:05:56,940
True. I'm everlastingly suspicious of...

26
00:05:57,024 --> 00:06:00,443
and/or fascinated by...

27
00:06:00,528 --> 00:06:03,446
the contents of brown paper bags.

28
00:06:03,531 --> 00:06:07,033
- Shall I sneak a peek?
- You do that, counselor.

29
00:06:09,370 --> 00:06:11,663
You do that, and...

30
00:06:11,747 --> 00:06:15,458
after you sneak a peek, why, you uncork...

31
00:06:15,543 --> 00:06:17,585
whatever you find.

32
00:06:23,092 --> 00:06:25,009
- Shall I pour?
- Your privilege.

33
00:06:25,094 --> 00:06:27,053
My pleasure, sir.

34
00:06:33,018 --> 00:06:35,687
## [Jazz]

35
00:06:37,398 --> 00:06:39,774
You fought this soldier by yourself.

36
00:06:40,859 --> 00:06:42,902
You've been drinkin' alone, Polly.

37
00:06:42,987 --> 00:06:44,904
I don't like that.

38
00:06:44,989 --> 00:06:48,324
Ah, drop the stone, counselor.
You live in a glass house.

39
00:06:48,409 --> 00:06:53,162
My windows have been busted
a long time ago, so I can say as I please.

40
00:06:55,374 --> 00:06:57,292
Have an Italian cigar?

41
00:06:57,376 --> 00:06:58,876
No, thanks.

42
00:06:59,920 --> 00:07:02,755
Those stinkweeds are another sign
of your decadence.

43
00:07:02,840 --> 00:07:04,465
[Match Strikes]

44
00:07:07,386 --> 00:07:09,053
Polly, it's a fact.

45
00:07:09,138 --> 00:07:12,599
Since Mitch Lodwick beat you
out of the office of public prosecutor...

46
00:07:12,683 --> 00:07:15,184
you haven't been worth salt for peanuts.

47
00:07:15,269 --> 00:07:17,937
Not that I don't understand how you feel.

48
00:07:19,607 --> 00:07:22,942
When a man gets beat out of
an office he's held for a long time...

49
00:07:23,944 --> 00:07:26,571
he feels his community has deserted him...

50
00:07:26,655 --> 00:07:28,906
the finger of scorn is pointed at him.

51
00:07:28,991 --> 00:07:32,285
None but the lonely heart
shall know my anguish.

52
00:07:32,369 --> 00:07:34,996
Polly, you're a good lawyer.
You ought to make like one.

53
00:07:35,080 --> 00:07:39,792
Be here, ready for clients, not out fishin'
and playin' that rooty-tooty jazz.

54
00:07:39,877 --> 00:07:42,128
- ## [Continues]
- Oh, I'm making a living.

55
00:07:42,212 --> 00:07:47,133
I run a few abstracts and divorce Jane Doe
from John Doe every once in a while.

56
00:07:47,217 --> 00:07:49,802
Threaten a few deadbeats.

57
00:07:49,887 --> 00:07:52,555
And in the evening I sit around
and drink bourbon whiskey...

58
00:07:52,640 --> 00:07:56,726
and read law
with Parnell Emmett McCarthy...

59
00:07:56,810 --> 00:07:59,187
one of the world's great men.

60
00:07:59,271 --> 00:08:01,981
That was a kind word, Polly.

61
00:08:02,066 --> 00:08:05,234
You know, I might have been.

62
00:08:05,903 --> 00:08:10,239
That's one of the reasons I hate to see
your talent pushed aside by lesser men.

63
00:08:10,324 --> 00:08:12,700
I look at you and I see myself years ago...

64
00:08:12,785 --> 00:08:18,164
with the same love for the smell of the
old brown books and the dusty office.

65
00:08:20,084 --> 00:08:23,169
Here's a rose, a lily...

66
00:08:24,213 --> 00:08:26,172
a sweet lupine.

67
00:08:26,256 --> 00:08:29,801
The United States Supreme Court Reports.

68
00:08:30,469 --> 00:08:34,764
Well, what shall we read
this evening, counselor?

69
00:08:34,848 --> 00:08:37,767
How about a little, uh,
Chief Justice Holmes?

70
00:08:37,851 --> 00:08:39,894
[Phone Ringing]

71
00:08:41,522 --> 00:08:44,649
Restrain Chief Justice Holmes for a minute.
I might have a client.

72
00:08:44,733 --> 00:08:46,901
Been waiting for a call. Hello?

73
00:08:46,985 --> 00:08:49,362
- [Operator] Mr. Biegler?
- This is Paul Biegler speaking.

74
00:08:49,446 --> 00:08:52,031
- Here's your party.
- Hello? Mrs. Manion?

75
00:08:52,116 --> 00:08:54,033
- What?
- [Woman] Mr. Biegler?

76
00:08:54,118 --> 00:08:56,744
I'm sorry I missed you a while ago.
Did you get my message?

77
00:08:56,829 --> 00:08:59,122
- Who is that? What is that name?
- Just a minute, please.

78
00:08:59,206 --> 00:09:01,958
We seem to have a bad connection.
Just hold on.

79
00:09:02,042 --> 00:09:05,169
It's a woman name of Manion.
Maida took a message from her.

80
00:09:05,254 --> 00:09:07,171
- In Thunder Bay?
- Uh-huh.

81
00:09:07,256 --> 00:09:09,298
If she wants you to represent
her husband, say yes.

82
00:09:09,383 --> 00:09:12,468
- I don't know what it's all about.
- Pretend you do and say yes.

83
00:09:12,553 --> 00:09:14,220
- Hello?
- Mr. Biegler?

84
00:09:14,304 --> 00:09:17,432
Oh, yes. It's much better now.
Yes, I can hear you fine.

85
00:09:17,516 --> 00:09:20,518
- ## [Speakers: Jazz]
- I've waited for your call all afternoon.

86
00:09:20,602 --> 00:09:23,312
Yes, well, I just got in a few moments ago.

87
00:09:23,397 --> 00:09:25,815
You've read about my husband?
Muffy, please.

88
00:09:25,899 --> 00:09:27,609
Yes.

89
00:09:27,610 --> 00:09:29,318
Mr. Biegler, have you
read about my husband?

90
00:09:29,403 --> 00:09:30,903
Muffy, please.

91
00:09:32,114 --> 00:09:35,408
Well, yes, I have. A little.

92
00:09:35,492 --> 00:09:37,619
Will you defend him?

93
00:09:37,620 --> 00:09:39,746
I don't know.
I'd have to know more about it.

94
00:09:39,830 --> 00:09:42,832
Will you talk to him?
Mr. Biegler, he's in the county jail.

95
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:46,294
Will you see him in the morning?
He's-He's very anxious to see you.

96
00:09:46,378 --> 00:09:49,881
- You've been so highly recommended.
- I have?

97
00:09:49,965 --> 00:09:53,134
Yeah. Someone told him about you.
Will you see him?

98
00:09:53,218 --> 00:09:55,887
Well, I suppose I could.
I'll see him tomorrow morning.

99
00:09:57,222 --> 00:09:59,182
Would you want me there too, Mr. Biegler?

100
00:09:59,266 --> 00:10:02,852
I think that'd be fine.
Let's make it about 10:00, huh?

101
00:10:02,936 --> 00:10:05,521
Thank you. Thank you so much.

102
00:10:05,606 --> 00:10:07,607
Yes, you're quite welcome. Bye.

103
00:10:07,691 --> 00:10:09,609
Now, what's this all about?

104
00:10:09,693 --> 00:10:12,570
A man named Barney Quill raped Mrs. Manion.

105
00:10:12,654 --> 00:10:14,864
Her husband, he's a lieutenant in the army.

106
00:10:14,948 --> 00:10:17,867
There's a temporary base in Thunder Bay.
Gunnery or something.

107
00:10:17,951 --> 00:10:22,872
The lieutenant goes to Quill's place
and plugs Mr. Quill about five times...

108
00:10:22,956 --> 00:10:25,374
which causes Mr. Quill
to promptly die of lead poisoning.

109
00:10:25,459 --> 00:10:27,460
- When did all this happen?
- A couple of nights ago.

110
00:10:27,544 --> 00:10:30,129
If you hadn't been out fishing in a rowboat
in some godforsaken backwater...

111
00:10:30,214 --> 00:10:32,465
you'd have known about it.

112
00:11:02,538 --> 00:11:04,497
## [Whistling]

113
00:11:12,965 --> 00:11:14,966
[Snoring Softly]

114
00:11:47,541 --> 00:11:49,792
- Morning, Maida.
- Oh, there it is.

115
00:11:49,877 --> 00:11:51,794
- What?
- The newspaper.

116
00:11:51,879 --> 00:11:55,131
I thought maybe they didn't bring it.
We haven't paid the bill.

117
00:11:55,215 --> 00:11:58,050
- Did you get my note?
- Uh-huh. We may be in the case.

118
00:11:58,135 --> 00:12:01,304
I'm just reading up on it
now before talking to Lieutenant Manion.

119
00:12:01,388 --> 00:12:04,515
- Doesn't he ever go home?
- You mean Parnell?

120
00:12:04,600 --> 00:12:07,852
- We were up late last night.
- Is that a fact?

121
00:12:07,936 --> 00:12:11,564
Yeah. I think maybe you'd better cancel
all my appointments for today.

122
00:12:11,648 --> 00:12:15,902
What appointments?
People think you migrated into the woods.

123
00:12:16,987 --> 00:12:19,322
If this refrigerator gets
any more fish in it...

124
00:12:19,406 --> 00:12:21,324
it'll swim upstream and
spawn, all by itself.

125
00:12:21,325 --> 00:12:23,242
[Muttering]

126
00:12:24,453 --> 00:12:27,413
May I have your attention
for a moment, please?

127
00:12:28,957 --> 00:12:30,396
Yeah.

128
00:12:30,397 --> 00:12:31,834
I was going over your
checkbook yesterday.

129
00:12:31,919 --> 00:12:34,211
- I can't pay me my salary.
- [Mutters]

130
00:12:34,296 --> 00:12:36,672
What did you do with the fee
for the Walkers' divorce?

131
00:12:36,757 --> 00:12:38,966
Help salt a uranium mine or something?

132
00:12:39,051 --> 00:12:43,846
- Uh, I bought a few bare necessities.
- Like a new outboard motor.

133
00:12:43,931 --> 00:12:47,058
I wish I could be classed as a necessity.

134
00:12:47,142 --> 00:12:49,060
- Aren't you gonna have your toast?
- No, no.

135
00:12:49,144 --> 00:12:52,146
I'll, uh... I'll, uh...

136
00:12:52,230 --> 00:12:54,398
call you and let you know
how things are going.

137
00:12:54,483 --> 00:12:56,734
Now don't let him pay you off
in purple hearts.

138
00:12:56,818 --> 00:12:59,570
Those professional soldiers
never have a dime.

139
00:12:59,655 --> 00:13:02,323
I ought to know. I was married to one.

140
00:13:23,136 --> 00:13:25,137
I beg your pardon. Are you Mrs. Manion?

141
00:13:25,222 --> 00:13:27,473
- Hi.
- I'm Paul Biegler.

142
00:13:27,557 --> 00:13:29,475
- I'm Laura.
- How do you do?

143
00:13:30,936 --> 00:13:34,438
- This is Muff.
- Hello, Muff. The jail's right here.

144
00:13:38,151 --> 00:13:40,111
You're tall.

145
00:13:42,781 --> 00:13:45,741
- [Man] Hello, Polly.
- Hi, Sulo.

146
00:13:45,826 --> 00:13:47,743
You wait here, Muffy.

147
00:13:52,833 --> 00:13:54,750
- Good to see you, Polly.
- How ya feelin'?

148
00:13:54,835 --> 00:13:57,253
Fine. I guess you come for the soldier boy.

149
00:13:57,337 --> 00:14:00,548
Yeah. Sulo, do you think it'd be all right
if we talked in the sheriff's office?

150
00:14:00,632 --> 00:14:02,758
Oh, sure, Polly. I'll bring him down.

151
00:14:13,895 --> 00:14:17,106
Would you mind taking your glasses off,
Mrs. Manion?

152
00:14:19,276 --> 00:14:21,610
Gee whiz. Barney Quill do that to you?

153
00:14:21,695 --> 00:14:23,738
Mm-hmm. More than that.

154
00:14:23,822 --> 00:14:25,865
You should see. All over.

155
00:14:27,909 --> 00:14:30,911
Well, you can put them back on
if it's more comfortable for ya.

156
00:14:39,796 --> 00:14:42,256
This is Polly Biegler.
This is the bucko, Polly.

157
00:14:42,340 --> 00:14:44,258
- Lieutenant Manion.
- Hello there.

158
00:14:44,342 --> 00:14:46,260
- Hi, Manny.
- Hello, Laura.

159
00:14:48,555 --> 00:14:51,391
Uh, Mrs. Manion, I wonder
if you could meet me

160
00:14:51,392 --> 00:14:54,226
down at my office about
2:00 this afternoon.

161
00:14:54,311 --> 00:14:56,312
It's 305 West Barnham.

162
00:14:56,396 --> 00:14:58,355
- Of course.
- Fine.

163
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:02,735
- Is there anything I can get you, hon?
- I'm all right, hon.

164
00:15:04,404 --> 00:15:06,322
Right in here.

165
00:15:18,710 --> 00:15:21,629
"Wanted." The big ten.

166
00:15:21,713 --> 00:15:24,632
[Chuckles]
They got the ten best-dressed dames...

167
00:15:24,716 --> 00:15:28,010
the ten top teams, the ten top tunes...

168
00:15:28,095 --> 00:15:30,012
and now, the ten most wanted.

169
00:15:30,097 --> 00:15:32,244
Well, don't knock it.
That's the American dream.

170
00:15:32,245 --> 00:15:34,391
Those boys made the grade.

171
00:15:34,935 --> 00:15:39,647
You were the... district attorney
around here, weren't you?

172
00:15:39,731 --> 00:15:41,649
Mm-hmm. Ten years.

173
00:15:42,234 --> 00:15:44,193
What's your experience as a defense lawyer?

174
00:15:44,277 --> 00:15:46,153
Not very much.

175
00:15:46,238 --> 00:15:48,155
How do I know you can handle my case?

176
00:15:48,740 --> 00:15:51,200
Well, I guess you don't know.

177
00:15:51,284 --> 00:15:53,202
Shall we talk about it?

178
00:15:54,871 --> 00:15:56,789
I suppose so.

179
00:15:56,873 --> 00:15:59,500
Well, now, come on, Lieutenant.
Don't be so bored.

180
00:15:59,584 --> 00:16:03,212
You know, it might very well be
that no lawyer can handle your case...

181
00:16:03,296 --> 00:16:05,214
if you mean getting off scot-free.

182
00:16:05,298 --> 00:16:08,759
You seem to be forgetting
Barney Quill raped my wife.

183
00:16:08,844 --> 00:16:10,719
I have the unwritten law on my side.

184
00:16:10,804 --> 00:16:13,722
The unwritten law is a myth, Lieutenant.

185
00:16:13,807 --> 00:16:16,600
There is no such thing
as the unwritten law...

186
00:16:16,685 --> 00:16:19,728
and anyone who commits a murder
on the theory that it does exist...

187
00:16:19,813 --> 00:16:23,065
has just bought himself
room and board in the state penitentiary.

188
00:16:23,150 --> 00:16:24,900
Maybe for life.

189
00:16:26,069 --> 00:16:27,778
Now, with that in mind...

190
00:16:27,863 --> 00:16:33,325
perhaps we can proceed with a few questions
and answers that... that, uh...

191
00:16:33,410 --> 00:16:35,536
Can I borrow your lighter?

192
00:16:38,373 --> 00:16:40,771
We can proceed with a few
questions and answers

193
00:16:40,772 --> 00:16:43,169
that might be of some
help in your defense.

194
00:16:45,964 --> 00:16:47,882
But probably won't be.

195
00:16:49,759 --> 00:16:51,927
Yeah. Nice lighter.

196
00:16:54,431 --> 00:16:57,892
- Okay.
- Well, how old are you?

197
00:16:57,976 --> 00:17:00,269
- Twenty-eight.
- How long have you been in the service?

198
00:17:00,353 --> 00:17:02,730
Since '50.

199
00:17:02,814 --> 00:17:05,107
- You seen any action?
- Korea.

200
00:17:05,192 --> 00:17:07,568
- Have any decorations?
- Plenty.

201
00:17:07,652 --> 00:17:09,570
Is this your first marriage?

202
00:17:09,654 --> 00:17:11,238
No.

203
00:17:11,323 --> 00:17:14,408
You're not on the witness stand.
You don't have to answer yes or no.

204
00:17:14,492 --> 00:17:17,411
Just give me the matrimonial rundown.

205
00:17:17,495 --> 00:17:21,123
- Is this necessary?
- I'll be the judge of that.

206
00:17:23,210 --> 00:17:25,211
My first wife divorced me.

207
00:17:25,295 --> 00:17:28,130
Charged cruelty. [Chuckles]

208
00:17:28,215 --> 00:17:31,133
Eating crackers in bed.
You know, the usual stuff.

209
00:17:31,885 --> 00:17:36,388
Truth was, she found another guy
when I was in Korea.

210
00:17:38,516 --> 00:17:41,852
I met Laura four years ago in Georgia.

211
00:17:41,937 --> 00:17:44,647
We were married right after her divorce.

212
00:17:44,731 --> 00:17:46,774
Did you know the husband?

213
00:17:47,359 --> 00:17:50,694
- He was in my outfit down there.
- You mean you were buddies?

214
00:17:51,363 --> 00:17:54,823
I'll withdraw the question.
That's a little old-fashioned.

215
00:17:54,908 --> 00:17:58,410
Have there been any children by or from
any of these marriages?

216
00:17:58,995 --> 00:18:01,914
- No.
- Any present prospects?

217
00:18:01,998 --> 00:18:04,083
Not unless Barney Quill started something.

218
00:18:04,167 --> 00:18:06,335
What kind of a gun did you use on Quill?

219
00:18:06,419 --> 00:18:09,797
War souvenir. Luger.
The police have it now.

220
00:18:09,881 --> 00:18:13,342
I suppose you've read the newspapers,
the stories about your case?

221
00:18:13,426 --> 00:18:15,928
- Some of them.
- Are they substantially correct?

222
00:18:16,012 --> 00:18:17,137
Yes.

223
00:18:17,222 --> 00:18:20,015
And you didn't see Quill
rape and beat your wife?

224
00:18:20,892 --> 00:18:22,142
No. No.

225
00:18:22,227 --> 00:18:26,689
When she got back, uh, to the trailer,
she told me what had happened.

226
00:18:26,773 --> 00:18:29,566
Then how long was it before you went
over to Quill's and killed him?

227
00:18:29,651 --> 00:18:31,527
I don't know exactly. Maybe an hour.

228
00:18:31,611 --> 00:18:33,988
That long, huh?

229
00:18:34,072 --> 00:18:37,283
Now, the newspapers say that your wife
volunteered to take a lie detector test.

230
00:18:37,367 --> 00:18:39,034
You know anything about this?

231
00:18:39,119 --> 00:18:41,370
Only what I read and what she told me.

232
00:18:41,454 --> 00:18:43,872
Do you know how
the lie detector test turned out?

233
00:18:43,957 --> 00:18:46,375
- They didn't tell her.
- Yes, Sulo?

234
00:18:46,459 --> 00:18:50,087
Polly, we got lunch served for the jail.
You want to eat with us?

235
00:18:51,298 --> 00:18:53,215
Does your sister still cook for the jail?

236
00:18:53,300 --> 00:18:56,093
- Oh, sure. She cooks.
- Uh-huh.

237
00:18:56,177 --> 00:18:59,513
Well, you give her my compliments, Sulo.

238
00:18:59,597 --> 00:19:02,558
- I've got a luncheon date downtown.
- Nice going, Mr. Biegler.

239
