and did what he wanted.

475
00:32:00,920 --> 00:32:03,379
Now, the newspapers said
that a doctor examined you...

476
00:32:03,464 --> 00:32:05,507
and said that he didn't
think you'd been raped.

477
00:32:05,591 --> 00:32:09,344
I don't care what the doctor thought.
A woman doesn't mistake these things.

478
00:32:09,428 --> 00:32:12,472
All right. All right. Now go ahead.

479
00:32:12,556 --> 00:32:14,140
Well, I...

480
00:32:15,851 --> 00:32:18,144
I don't know exactly what happened then.
I must've fainted.

481
00:32:18,229 --> 00:32:21,356
But the next thing I remember,
the car was moving.

482
00:32:21,440 --> 00:32:25,610
Barney was driving very fast,
and... and he was breathing hard.

483
00:32:25,694 --> 00:32:29,030
An ugly, gasping sound.

484
00:32:30,241 --> 00:32:32,742
We were on the main road
to the trailer park...

485
00:32:32,827 --> 00:32:35,578
and he swung in by the gate and stopped.

486
00:32:35,663 --> 00:32:37,769
I opened the door to get out.
Muffy jumped out

487
00:32:37,770 --> 00:32:39,874
first, with a lighted
flashlight in his mouth.

488
00:32:39,959 --> 00:32:42,043
Well, now, wait a minute.
I thought you said...

489
00:32:42,128 --> 00:32:44,546
he'd thrown Muff out of the car
back in the woods.

490
00:32:44,630 --> 00:32:47,257
Well, he did, but Muff was
in the car when we got back.

491
00:32:47,341 --> 00:32:49,217
He must've let him back in.
I don't remember.

492
00:32:49,301 --> 00:32:52,846
All right. All right. Now, you opened the
door, and Muff got out first. All right.

493
00:32:52,930 --> 00:32:55,557
Before I could get out,
Barney grabbed me...

494
00:32:55,641 --> 00:32:58,893
and said he was gonna tear all my
clothes off and attack me again.

495
00:32:58,978 --> 00:33:00,688
I got away and ran.

496
00:33:00,689 --> 00:33:02,397
I could see Muff at an
opening in the fence.

497
00:33:02,481 --> 00:33:05,900
He was scooting back and forth
with the flashlight.

498
00:33:05,985 --> 00:33:09,946
Barney caught me from behind,
and I fell to the ground.

499
00:33:10,030 --> 00:33:12,866
He fell on top of me and began
to beat me again with his fists.

500
00:33:12,950 --> 00:33:14,868
I thought he was gonna kill me.

501
00:33:14,952 --> 00:33:19,581
I screamed, and somehow or other
I got to my feet again and ran.

502
00:33:19,665 --> 00:33:22,250
I went through the opening
in the fence and followed Muffy.

503
00:33:22,334 --> 00:33:24,544
He was running along ahead
with the flashlight.

504
00:33:24,628 --> 00:33:27,589
And I kept following the light
until he led me to our trailer.

505
00:33:27,673 --> 00:33:29,883
And you didn't see Barney again?

506
00:33:29,967 --> 00:33:32,719
Never laid eyes on him
again, dead or alive.

507
00:33:33,804 --> 00:33:35,722
Well, I...

508
00:33:35,806 --> 00:33:37,682
I think that's enough for now.

509
00:33:38,267 --> 00:33:40,977
I've got lots of time. All you want.

510
00:33:42,438 --> 00:33:44,355
Where can I reach you?

511
00:33:44,440 --> 00:33:47,192
I'm still in Thunder Bay,
but I can drive down again in the morning.

512
00:33:51,030 --> 00:33:53,781
- Was there something else?
- No.

513
00:34:06,462 --> 00:34:08,463
Thanks for letting me play the records.

514
00:34:08,547 --> 00:34:11,549
- Oh, you're very welcome.
- Thanks a lot. Bye.

515
00:34:14,720 --> 00:34:17,931
- Who's that?
- The lady in the case.

516
00:34:18,015 --> 00:34:19,307
Oh.

517
00:34:20,976 --> 00:34:22,810
And you're not gonna take the case, huh?

518
00:34:22,895 --> 00:34:27,148
Well, I don't know. That depends on
what Manion has to tell me tomorrow.

519
00:34:27,233 --> 00:34:29,776
He's thinking things out.

520
00:34:29,860 --> 00:34:31,903
Oh, well, that's more like it.

521
00:34:31,987 --> 00:34:35,073
Now, if I take the case, I want you in it.

522
00:34:36,116 --> 00:34:39,077
Me? In a big murder case?

523
00:34:39,703 --> 00:34:41,872
Why, Polly, the sight of
this whiskey-drinking

524
00:34:41,873 --> 00:34:44,040
old man at the counsel
table would ruin you.

525
00:34:44,959 --> 00:34:46,709
I need you.

526
00:34:47,253 --> 00:34:48,836
Do you mean that?

527
00:34:48,921 --> 00:34:51,506
Why else would he say it?

528
00:34:52,424 --> 00:34:55,093
Well, I'd be glad to work with you
outside of the courtroom...

529
00:34:55,177 --> 00:34:57,095
but not in the courtroom.

530
00:34:57,179 --> 00:35:01,432
Well, suit yourself about that. Either way,
I'm gonna have to be able to depend on you.

531
00:35:03,769 --> 00:35:05,687
Will you lay off the booze?

532
00:35:11,277 --> 00:35:15,571
I don't know.
I don't know about that, Polly.

533
00:35:15,656 --> 00:35:17,615
Why don't you know?

534
00:35:20,035 --> 00:35:22,495
Do you think I could lay off the booze?

535
00:35:23,163 --> 00:35:25,498
[Maida] Ever tried it?

536
00:35:27,710 --> 00:35:29,419
Try it.

537
00:35:33,716 --> 00:35:36,134
I've never been on a big murder case.

538
00:35:36,927 --> 00:35:39,470
Not once in all my life.

539
00:35:39,555 --> 00:35:41,472
It's up to you, Parn.

540
00:35:48,689 --> 00:35:50,773
Will you be around tonight?

541
00:35:51,275 --> 00:35:54,360
Yeah. Yeah. I'll be around.

542
00:36:03,537 --> 00:36:06,247
You know, Maida, darlin'...

543
00:36:06,332 --> 00:36:09,250
I might manage it.

544
00:36:09,335 --> 00:36:12,378
I might manage to be a real lawyer again.

545
00:36:13,672 --> 00:36:15,673
For a little while anyway.

546
00:36:19,011 --> 00:36:21,262
I tried remembering.

547
00:36:21,347 --> 00:36:23,723
There were still some pieces missing.

548
00:36:25,309 --> 00:36:27,226
I remember...

549
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:31,939
going to Quill's bar with a gun...

550
00:36:32,024 --> 00:36:35,651
and I remember Quill's face behind the bar.

551
00:36:36,320 --> 00:36:39,947
But I don't remember anything else,
not even going home.

552
00:36:40,032 --> 00:36:42,033
Don't you remember firing the gun?

553
00:36:42,117 --> 00:36:44,452
Five shots.
That's a lot of noise to forget.

554
00:36:44,536 --> 00:36:48,498
Yeah, I remember hearing shots, but they
don't seem to be connected with me.

555
00:36:48,582 --> 00:36:50,541
They seemed far away...

556
00:36:50,626 --> 00:36:53,920
like somebody else was doing the shooting.

557
00:36:58,217 --> 00:37:01,886
Lieutenant Manion, I'll, uh...
I'll take your case.

558
00:37:02,554 --> 00:37:04,722
Why, thanks. Thanks, Mr. Biegler.

559
00:37:04,807 --> 00:37:07,975
All right. Now, there's
the little matter of the fee.

560
00:37:08,060 --> 00:37:09,977
Three thousand dollars.
That's reasonable enough, isn't it?

561
00:37:10,062 --> 00:37:11,979
Oh, sure, sure. More than reasonable.

562
00:37:12,064 --> 00:37:14,065
I'll have to pay you later.
Right now I'm broke.

563
00:37:14,149 --> 00:37:16,526
- You're what?
- I'm broke. I'm flat busted.

564
00:37:16,610 --> 00:37:18,986
I don't have three dollars,
much less 3,000.

565
00:37:19,071 --> 00:37:22,990
- Well, can you raise it?
- Oh, yeah, as soon as I get outta jail.

566
00:37:23,075 --> 00:37:26,077
But, uh, next week's payday.

567
00:37:26,161 --> 00:37:29,080
I'll, uh...
I'll be able to give you $150.

568
00:37:29,164 --> 00:37:32,375
And if you get me off, I'll give you
a promissory note for the rest.

569
00:37:32,459 --> 00:37:36,129
All right. Now, suppose I don't go along
with you unless you pay me half the fee?

570
00:37:37,381 --> 00:37:40,216
Well, I'll have to take
the lawyer the court appoints.

571
00:37:40,300 --> 00:37:43,928
- I got my defense now. Right? Insanity.
- Yeah.

572
00:37:44,012 --> 00:37:46,848
I think I'll stick around
and make damn sure you get off.

573
00:37:46,932 --> 00:37:51,144
- Where do we start?
- We're gonna need a psychiatrist.

574
00:37:51,228 --> 00:37:53,313
As much as neither one
of us has any money,

575
00:37:53,314 --> 00:37:55,398
do you think the army'll
stir one up for you?

576
00:37:55,482 --> 00:37:57,400
Well, I know a colonel in the Pentagon.

577
00:37:57,484 --> 00:37:59,610
- I'll write a letter.
- Good. Do that. Sulo.

578
00:38:05,367 --> 00:38:07,285
Where are you going now?

579
00:38:07,369 --> 00:38:09,662
I'm going to see your wife, for one thing.

580
00:38:09,746 --> 00:38:12,206
Why? Didn't you see her yesterday?

581
00:38:12,291 --> 00:38:14,333
That's right. I did.

582
00:38:14,418 --> 00:38:16,627
She's a very pretty woman, your wife.

583
00:38:17,504 --> 00:38:19,339
A man gets used to the
way his wife looks.

584
00:38:19,340 --> 00:38:21,174
Yeah. I can see that.

585
00:38:21,258 --> 00:38:23,176
I'll see ya.

586
00:38:39,485 --> 00:38:42,278
Come on in, Polly. Come on in.

587
00:38:42,362 --> 00:38:44,989
You haven't been in here since you vacated,
have you, Polly?

588
00:38:45,073 --> 00:38:47,492
- No.
- Hardly recognize the old place, huh?

589
00:38:47,576 --> 00:38:50,077
Mary did it for me.
She just finished a decorator's course.

590
00:38:50,162 --> 00:38:52,580
Smart girl.
Very smart girl. Look at this.

591
00:38:52,664 --> 00:38:55,416
- A real, genuine Picasso print.
- It's very nice.

592
00:38:55,501 --> 00:38:58,586
And here, try this chair.
It sort of does things for you.

593
00:38:58,670 --> 00:39:00,755
- Huh?
- Yeah. Sit right down.

594
00:39:00,839 --> 00:39:02,549
[Mechanical Rattling]

595
00:39:02,550 --> 00:39:04,258
Great, isn't it?
Good for the nerves, they say.

596
00:39:04,343 --> 00:39:07,929
- Yeah. How do you shut it off?
- There. Here we are.

597
00:39:08,013 --> 00:39:10,681
- Feel better?
- I feel all shook up.

598
00:39:10,766 --> 00:39:12,141
Whew!

599
00:39:12,226 --> 00:39:17,355
Uh, Mitch, I just dropped by to tell you
I've got both feet in the Manion case.

600
00:39:17,439 --> 00:39:19,398
- You're going to cop out, aren't you?
- No.

601
00:39:19,483 --> 00:39:21,276
That's a mistake, Polly.
It's open and shut.

602
00:39:21,277 --> 00:39:23,069
Well, maybe. We'll see.

603
00:39:23,153 --> 00:39:25,071
Judge Maitland is still in the hospital.

604
00:39:25,155 --> 00:39:27,615
Maybe you'd like to agree
to a continuance until he gets back.

605
00:39:27,699 --> 00:39:29,909
If we go with the case now,
we'll have to try...

606
00:39:29,993 --> 00:39:32,203
before some grab-bag judge they'll send in.

607
00:39:32,287 --> 00:39:34,872
- Me, I'd rather have Maitland.
- Yeah. So would I.

608
00:39:34,957 --> 00:39:38,042
But of course that'd also mean my client
would lie around in jail...

609
00:39:38,126 --> 00:39:40,503
for another two, three months
before the trial.

610
00:39:40,587 --> 00:39:44,298
Now, if you'll drop the charge
down to manslaughter...

611
00:39:44,383 --> 00:39:47,218
so I can get him out on bail,
we'll agree to a continuance.

612
00:39:47,302 --> 00:39:49,637
You wouldn't do that if you were still D.A.

613
00:39:49,721 --> 00:39:52,139
Oh, I don't know. I might.

614
00:39:52,224 --> 00:39:55,142
I might, since a great big fat
lie detector test on his wife...

615
00:39:55,227 --> 00:39:57,562
has given proof to the rape story.

616
00:39:57,646 --> 00:40:01,023
- He'd have the jury with him.
- How did you know what the lie...

617
00:40:01,108 --> 00:40:03,025
- Bit, didn't I?
- Yeah. You did.

618
00:40:03,110 --> 00:40:05,653
Anyway, the result of a lie detector test
isn't admissible evidence.

619
00:40:05,737 --> 00:40:09,490
- You can't use it.
- No, but it carries moral weight.

620
00:40:09,575 --> 00:40:12,952
[Mutters] Mitch, I wouldn't
sit in that chair too much.

621
00:40:13,036 --> 00:40:15,454
It could shake a fellow's brains loose.

622
00:40:15,539 --> 00:40:17,456
I'll see you later.

623
00:40:22,838 --> 00:40:24,755
[Muff Barks]

624
00:40:26,508 --> 00:40:28,426
He remembers you, Paul. He likes you.

625
00:40:28,510 --> 00:40:30,428
- He likes the beer in my icebox.
- [Laughs]

626
00:40:30,512 --> 00:40:32,805
Well, what's the occasion today?
A buffalo hunt?

627
00:40:32,889 --> 00:40:35,933
I bought these in Arizona
when we were stationed there.

628
00:40:36,018 --> 00:40:37,978
Aren't they smart?
I think they're very smart.

629
00:40:37,979 --> 00:40:39,937
Here. We can sit in my car.

630
00:40:47,154 --> 00:40:48,696
Here you are.

631
00:40:49,865 --> 00:40:51,782
Here you go, Muffy.

632
00:40:51,867 --> 00:40:54,118
Several things have occurred to me.

633
00:40:54,202 --> 00:40:56,162
The, uh...

634
00:40:56,246 --> 00:40:59,874
The undergarments
that Barney Quill tore off.

635
00:40:59,958 --> 00:41:02,376
Who has them now? The police?

636
00:41:02,461 --> 00:41:04,545
You mean my panties?

637
00:41:04,630 --> 00:41:06,547
All right. Your panties.

638
00:41:06,632 --> 00:41:08,549
I haven't seen them since.

639
00:41:08,634 --> 00:41:10,551
I gave the torn skirt
and sweater to the police...

640
00:41:10,636 --> 00:41:14,221
and then I went with them up that lane
into the woods to look for the panties.

641
00:41:14,306 --> 00:41:16,329
But we couldn't find
anything but my glasses.

642
00:41:16,330 --> 00:41:18,351
Your glasses?

643
00:41:18,435 --> 00:41:20,394
You mean you were wearing glasses
through all that?

644
00:41:20,479 --> 00:41:23,314
No. I had them in a case in my hand.

645
00:41:23,398 --> 00:41:26,233
I wear them for reading, playing pinball.
Things like that.

646
00:41:26,318 --> 00:41:28,736
I must've tried to get
out of the car and dropped them.

647
00:41:28,820 --> 00:41:30,696
Uh-huh.

648
00:41:30,781 --> 00:41:34,367
You, uh, might be interested to know
that your lie detector test...

649
00:41:34,451 --> 00:41:36,577
turned out in your favor.

650
00:41:36,662 --> 00:41:39,497
Of course it did.
I could've told you it would.

651
00:41:39,581 --> 00:41:44,168
- You weren't worried about it?
- No. Why should I be?

652
00:41:44,753 --> 00:41:47,838
Would you like to have
something to worry about?

653
00:41:47,923 --> 00:41:49,548
[Chuckles] Silly.

654
00:41:49,633 --> 00:41:51,926
Like your husband watching us
from his cell window?

655
00:41:56,014 --> 00:41:59,058
All right. All right. Let's have it.

656
00:42:00,811 --> 00:42:03,771
- Did he say something to you?
- Just enough.

657
00:42:03,855 --> 00:42:05,898
Are you afraid of him?

658
00:42:06,608 --> 00:42:08,442
Yes.

659
00:42:08,527 --> 00:42:11,612
Is that why you volunteered
for a lie detector test? For him?

660
00:42:11,697 --> 00:42:15,533
- Yeah.
- Mmm. Does he have reason to be jealous?

661
00:42:16,952 --> 00:42:18,953
He was jealous even before we were married.

662
00:42:19,037 --> 00:42:21,122
I should have known how it would be.

663
00:42:21,790 --> 00:42:24,709
It's funny though. He...
He likes to show me off.

664
00:42:24,793 --> 00:42:26,961
He likes me to dress the way I do.

665
00:42:27,045 --> 00:42:30,005
And then he gets furious
if a man pays any attention to me.

666
00:42:30,716 --> 00:42:33,092
I've tried to leave him, but I can't.

667
00:42:33,176 --> 00:42:35,177
He begs. I give in.

668
00:42:36,179 --> 00:42:39,849
Now, if you think I've forgotten
my question, I haven't.

669
00:42:40,892 --> 00:42:42,977
- I have.
- All right.

670
00:42:43,061 --> 00:42:45,438
All right. Then I'll ask it again.

671
00:42:45,522 --> 00:42:48,566
Does your husband
have any reason to be jealous?

672
00:42:50,068 --> 00:42:51,652
No.

673
00:42:51,737 --> 00:42:54,155
Not once. Not ever.

674
00:45:01,825 --> 00:45:03,742
[Door Opens]

675
00:45:12,711 --> 00:45:14,670
All right? You like the place all right?

676
00:45:14,754 --> 00:45:17,131
I was just lookin' at these pictures.

677
00:45:17,215 --> 00:45:20,801
- That was Barney Quill, wasn't it?
- That's right. Barney Quill.

678
00:45:20,886 --> 00:45:23,262
- I'm Paul Biegler...
- I know who you are.

679
00:45:23,346 --> 00:45:25,598
Seen you around Iron City.

680
00:45:25,682 --> 00:45:29,894
- You didn't tell me your name.
- Paquette. We don't open till 5:00.

681
00:45:29,978 --> 00:45:33,564
That's all right. I can wait.
I don't have the shakes yet. [Chuckles]

682
00:45:34,399 --> 00:45:36,775
You were on the job that
night, weren't you?

683
00:45:36,860 --> 00:45:39,069
The night Barney Quill was killed.

684
00:45:39,154 --> 00:45:41,488
Like the newspaper said, I was present.

685
00:45:41,573 --> 00:45:45,117
You were the fellow that stopped
Lieutenant Manion outside.

686
00:45:45,201 --> 00:45:48,662
That's right. He, uh...
He pointed the gun at me and said...

687
00:45:48,747 --> 00:45:50,497
"You want some too, buster?"

688
00:45:50,582 --> 00:45:53,167
And you said no,
because your name isn't buster.

689
00:45:53,835 --> 00:45:55,753
There wasn't anything funny
about it, Mr. Biegler.

690
00:45:55,837 --> 00:45:58,464
No. There wasn't. I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

691
00:45:58,548 --> 00:46:02,176
Where were you when Barney Quill
was killed, Mr. Paquette?

692
00:46:02,802 --> 00:46:05,012
[Sighs]

693
00:46:05,096 --> 00:46:07,640
I gather you don't want to
talk about that night, huh?

694
00:46:07,724 --> 00:46:10,184
That's right.
I don't want to talk about it.

695
00:46:10,268 --> 00:46:13,228
Have to talk to me about it in court.
Why not now?

696
00:46:13,772 --> 00:46:16,565
Because I don't have to now.
Reason enough, okay?

697
00:46:16,650 --> 00:46:17,858
Okay.

698
00:46:18,777 --> 00:46:23,697
Okay. Boy, old Barney, he was kind of
a rugged character, wasn't he?

699
00:46:23,782 --> 00:46:27,868
Ex-prize fighter, muscle man.
Fancy with guns.

700
00:46:27,953 --> 00:46:30,371
He paid his debts, ran a clean place.

701
00:46:30,455 --> 00:46:33,415
- Me, I liked him.
- You run the place now?

702
00:46:33,500 --> 00:46:37,044
No, I just work here.
Mary's running things.

703
00:46:37,128 --> 00:46:39,296
Mary. Was that Barney's wife?

704
00:46:39,381 --> 00:46:42,591
No. He wasn't... He didn't have a wife.
Mary was his manager.

705
00:46:42,676 --> 00:46:46,553
Oh. Gee, I wonder
who's gonna inherit the place.

706
00:46:46,638 --> 00:46:50,015
- Mary, I guess.
- Hmm, Mary again?

707
00:46:50,100 --> 00:46:52,017
What's the matter with that?

708
00:46:52,102 --> 00:46:55,187
You mean what's the matter with Mary?
I don't know what's the matter with Mary.

709
00:46:55,271 --> 00:46:57,147
Mary what?

710
00:46:57,232 --> 00:46:59,066
Pilant. Mary Pilant.

711
00:46:59,150 --> 00:47:01,068
She's in the back booth.

712
00:47:01,152 --> 00:47:04,405
We don't talk about our customers here,
but if we did...

713
00:47:04,489 --> 00:47:07,533
- Which we don't...
- Thank you.

714
00:47:07,617 --> 00:47:10,202
[Whispers]
That's her. That's Mary Pilant.

715
00:47:19,337 --> 00:47:21,296
Do you know Lieutenant Manion's wife?

716
00:47:21,381 --> 00:47:23,674
Sure. I know the lieutenant too.

717
00:47:23,758 --> 00:47:26,593
He's a good officer. She's all right too.

718
00:47:26,678 --> 00:47:29,054
- Friendly. Good kid.
- [Laughs]

719
00:47:29,139 --> 00:47:31,056
What do you know about it?
Knock it off.

720
00:47:31,141 --> 00:47:33,934
I didn't mean anything.
She's a dish. What's the matter with that?

721
00:47:34,019 --> 00:47:36,562
You want this lawyer to get wrong ideas?

722
00:47:37,188 --> 00:47:39,857
What chances has the lieutenant got,
Mr. McCarthy?

723
00:47:39,941 --> 00:47:43,694
Pretty good, I'd say, with a couple
of character witnesses like you.

724
00:47:45,030 --> 00:47:50,409
I'd like to help him out. I sure would, but
we're moving out. The whole outfit. Berlin.

725
00:47:50,493 --> 00:47:52,911
Oh. Uh, tell me...

726
00:47:52,996 --> 00:47:55,831
who is this babe at the hotel?

727
00:47:55,915 --> 00:48:00,502
Name's Mary Pilant.
She was Quill's private property.

728
00:48:13,725 --> 00:48:16,060
- Would you like a table, sir?
- Yes, please.

729
00:48:22,317 --> 00:48:25,736
- Will you be alone?
- I'll be joined by two others.

730
00:48:25,820 --> 00:48:29,406
- May I take your hat?
- Well, thank you. Thank you very much.

731
00:48:36,372 --> 00:48:38,290
How was the manicure?

732
00:48:38,374 --> 00:48:41,502
Just ask me any questions about anybody.
I've got all the dope.

733
00:48:41,586 --> 00:48:44,588
Well, can you tell me about a woman
by the name of Mary Pilant?

734
00:48:44,672 --> 00:48:46,340
Easy.

735
00:48:46,424 --> 00:48:50,594
Mary Pilant may or may not have been
the mistress of the late B. Quill.

736
00:48:50,678 --> 00:48:52,179
Oh?

737
00:48:52,180 --> 00:48:53,680
The manicurist is in favor
of the mistress theory...

738
00:48:53,765 --> 00:48:55,682
but the hairdresser is agin it.

739
00:48:55,767 --> 00:49:00,521
However, they both agree that some sort of
hanky-panky must've been going on.

740
00:49:00,605 --> 00:49:02,689
- To be continued.
- Menu?

741
00:49:02,774 --> 00:49:04,691
Thank you.

742
00:49:06,236 --> 00:49:08,654
- Pretty, huh?
- Yes, she's very pretty.

743
00:49:08,738 --> 00:49:10,531
Well, go on. Go on.

744
00:49:10,615 --> 00:49:12,825
Well, anyway, there's
one story that says

745
00:49:12,826 --> 00:49:15,035
that Barney's wild night
with Mrs. Manion...

746
00:49:15,120 --> 00:49:18,205
was somehow triggered by Mary Pilant.

747
00:49:18,289 --> 00:49:22,209
Seemed she'd been running around with
some soldier, and Barney blew his stack.

748
00:49:22,293 --> 00:49:25,712
- He got tanked up and exploded.
- Is Mary Pilant local?

749
00:49:25,797 --> 00:49:29,842
No, she's a Canadian. Barney brought her
in here to sort of dress up the place...

750
00:49:29,926 --> 00:49:31,927
and she stayed on to manage it for him.

751
00:49:32,011 --> 00:49:34,117
Looks like she's
done all right.

752
00:49:34,118 --> 00:49:36,223
Better than all right.
She's in for the estate.

753
00:49:36,307 --> 00:49:39,977
Oh? She doesn't look like
a bad sort, does she?

754
00:49:40,061 --> 00:49:43,730
- Hmm? Where?
- What do you mean, where?

755
00:49:43,815 --> 00:49:47,109
- The pretty one with the menus.
- This girl right here?

756
00:49:52,615 --> 00:49:55,450
Uh, Miss Pilant, may I introduce myself?

757
00:49:55,535 --> 00:49:57,911
I'm Paul Biegler,
attorney for Lieutenant Manion.

758
00:49:57,996 --> 00:50:00,080
This is Mrs. Rutledge
and Mr. McCarthy, my associates.

759
00:50:00,165 --> 00:50:01,666
How do you do?

760
00:50:01,667 --> 00:50:03,167
I wonder if you could
sit with us for a minute?

761
00:50:03,251 --> 00:50:05,752
- Yes, I can take a minute.
- Thank you.

762
00:50:07,547 --> 00:50:10,674
I'd like to ask you a few things,
if you don't mind.

763
00:50:10,758 --> 00:50:13,093
What sort of things, Mr. Biegler?

764
00:50:13,178 --> 00:50:16,722
Well, like what kind of a man
your employer was, Mr. Quill.

765
00:50:16,806 --> 00:50:18,348
A very nice man.

766
00:50:18,433 --> 00:50:22,186
If that's true, how do you explain what
happened with Lieutenant Manion's wife?

767
00:50:22,770 --> 00:50:25,272
I don't know what happened
with Lieutenant Manion's wife...

768
00:50:25,356 --> 00:50:27,983
so there really isn't anything
for me to explain, is there?

769
00:50:28,067 --> 00:50:31,278
Your loyalty to the dead Mr. Quill
is very touching, Miss Pilant.

770
00:50:31,362 --> 00:50:33,947
Barney was well liked here
by everyone, Mr. Biegler.

771
00:50:34,032 --> 00:50:36,284
It was very generous of
everyone to overlook his

772
00:50:36,285 --> 00:50:38,535
little faults, like
raping other men's wives.

773
00:50:39,913 --> 00:50:41,830
If you'll pardon me...

774
00:50:41,915 --> 00:50:44,625
the waitress will take your order
when you're ready.

775
00:50:44,709 --> 00:50:49,254
Nice to have met you, Mr. Biegler,
Mr. McCarthy, Mrs. Rutledge.

776
00:50:51,424 --> 00:50:54,218
You've just been ginned, Lieutenant.

777
00:50:55,845 --> 00:50:58,388
- Ten, twenty...
- [Sulo] Manion.

778
00:51:02,602 --> 00:51:04,645
- Any word, Lieutenant?
- Yeah.

779
00:51:04,729 --> 00:51:07,606
Uh, this. From Washington.

780
00:51:07,690 --> 00:51:10,609
They'll let a doctor come to testify,
but there's a string on it.

781
00:51:10,693 --> 00:51:14,446
They want me to go to an army hospital
in Detroit for an examination.

782
00:51:14,530 --> 00:51:18,492
Doesn't the army understand you're in jail
on a non-bailable offense?

783
00:51:18,576 --> 00:51:20,494
That's it, as far as the army's concerned.

784
00:51:20,578 --> 00:51:23,580
I don't know how I can get around this.
I'll try and think of something.

785
00:51:23,665 --> 00:51:25,312
Look. My wife hasn't
been here for two days.

786
00:51:25,313 --> 00:51:26,959
Have you seen her?

787
00:51:27,043 --> 00:51:29,753
- No, not for a while.
- Where the hell is she?

788
00:51:29,837 --> 00:51:32,047
You've got other things
to worry about, Lieutenant.

789
00:51:32,131 --> 00:51:35,050
Now, I'll get in touch with your wife.
I'll tell her you miss her.

790
00:51:35,134 --> 00:51:37,094
Yeah. You tell her that.

791
00:51:38,304 --> 00:51:40,889
- Thanks, Sulo.
- Okay, Polly.

792
00:51:44,894 --> 00:51:47,187
I know just how you feel, Lieutenant.

793
00:51:47,272 --> 00:51:51,191
I'd be tearin' my hair out too
if I had something like that outside.

794
00:51:52,277 --> 00:51:56,863
- Something like what outside?
- Man, you know what I mean.

795
00:51:56,948 --> 00:52:00,242
Something like that,
running around on the loose.

796
00:52:01,494 --> 00:52:03,704
[Shouts, Groans]

797
00:52:05,873 --> 00:52:08,125
Now, what's the big noise, buckoes?

798
00:52:09,460 --> 00:52:13,171
It's me, dummy.
I hit my elbow on this lousy iron bar.

799
00:52:13,256 --> 00:52:16,383
Oh. You want some rubbing alcohol, maybe?

800
00:52:16,467 --> 00:52:19,136
Nah. But a little bourbon might help.

801
00:52:19,220 --> 00:52:23,557
- [Men Laugh]
- Knock it off. Knock it off, buckoes.

802
00:52:23,641 --> 00:52:25,642
Let's finish the game, Lieutenant.

803
00:52:27,228 --> 00:52:30,147
## [Jazz]

804
00:52:47,498 --> 00:52:50,459
## [Continues]

805
00:52:55,381 --> 00:52:58,842
Oh! Hey!
What a crazy lawyer we've got.

806
00:52:58,926 --> 00:53:02,220
Hiya, Polly.
That's what they call you, isn't it? Polly?

807
00:53:02,305 --> 00:53:05,474
That's a crazy name for a crazy lawyer!

808
00:53:13,858 --> 00:53:15,776
Thanks for letting me sit in, Pie-Eye.

809
00:53:15,860 --> 00:53:18,278
- Hey, you're not splittin' the scene, man?
- Huh?

810
00:53:18,363 --> 00:53:21,156
- I mean, you're not cuttin' out?
- No, I'll be back.

811
00:53:40,885 --> 00:53:42,345
Well, hi, Polly.
Fellas, this is Manny's lawyer.

812
00:53:42,346 --> 00:53:43,804
Hi.

813
00:53:43,888 --> 00:53:45,597
- How are ya?
- Sit down, won't you?

814
00:53:45,681 --> 00:53:50,310
Sorry, I can't right now. Mrs. Manion,
may I talk to you for a moment, outside?

815
00:53:50,395 --> 00:53:53,980
"Mrs. Manion"? I thought
we dropped the formalities a long time ago.

816
00:53:54,065 --> 00:53:55,441
I think maybe we'd better
pick them up again.

817
00:53:55,442 --> 00:53:56,817
This is important.

818
00:53:56,901 --> 00:53:59,403
- All right. I'll go with you.
- All right, come on.

819
00:53:59,487 --> 00:54:03,198
- Hey! You're coming back, aren't you?
- Sure. What do you think?

820
00:54:13,251 --> 00:54:16,711
- See ya later, Pie-Eye.
- Okay.

821
00:54:24,303 --> 00:54:27,806
- Did you get my phone message?
- Yeah, but I got busy.

822
00:54:27,890 --> 00:54:29,808
Why haven't you been to see your husband?

823
00:54:29,892 --> 00:54:32,060
I don't see why I have
to see him every day.

824
00:54:32,145 --> 00:54:34,396
I think it'd be a very
good idea if you did.

825
00:54:34,480 --> 00:54:36,731
All right. I'll see him every day. Okay?

826
00:54:36,816 --> 00:54:38,942
No, not okay. Now, where's your car?

827
00:54:39,026 --> 00:54:40,298
I came with them.

828
00:54:40,299 --> 00:54:41,570
All right.
Mine's right over here. Come on.

829
00:54:41,654 --> 00:54:43,572
Hey, wait a second!
I've got friends inside.

830
00:54:43,656 --> 00:54:46,491
- Friends or no friends, you're goin' home.
- Who do you think you are?

831
00:54:46,576 --> 00:54:49,369
I'm the lawyer trying to beat a rap
for your husband! Do you remember?

832
00:54:49,454 --> 00:54:52,456
- What's that got to do with...
- Wait. Now, you listen. You listen.

833
00:54:52,540 --> 00:54:55,459
Now, until this trial is over, you're
gonna be a meek little housewife...

834
00:54:55,543 --> 00:55:00,130
with horn-rimmed spectacles, and you're
gonna stay away from men and juke joints...

835
00:55:00,214 --> 00:55:02,549
and booze and pinball machines...

836
00:55:02,633 --> 00:55:05,260
and you're gonna wear
a skirt and low-heeled shoes...

837
00:55:05,344 --> 00:55:08,180
and you're gonna wear a girdle...
and especially a girdle.

838
00:55:08,264 --> 00:55:10,579
Look, Laura, believe
me, I don't usually

839
00:55:10,580 --> 00:55:12,893
complain of an attractive
jiggle, but just...

840
00:55:12,977 --> 00:55:16,855
You save that jiggle for your husband to
look at, if and when I get him out of jail.

841
00:55:16,939 --> 00:55:18,857
Now come on. Let's go.

842
00:55:20,318 --> 00:55:22,277
I'm sorry. I really am.

843
00:55:22,361 --> 00:55:24,529
I wouldn't hurt Manny's
chances for anything.

844
00:55:24,614 --> 00:55:26,531
Come on. Come on.

845
00:56:04,779 --> 00:56:06,947
Is this about where
Barney knocked you down?

846
00:56:07,031 --> 00:56:09,241
Yeah. Right over here.

847
00:56:09,325 --> 00:56:11,243
Over there is the opening in the fence...

848
00:56:11,327 --> 00:56:13,787
where Muffy was running
back and forth with the flashlight.

849
00:56:16,624 --> 00:56:18,542
Where's your trailer?

850
00:56:19,043 --> 00:56:21,086
Up there on the hill.

851
00:56:26,717 --> 00:56:28,843
This is my favorite place.

852
00:56:33,558 --> 00:56:37,769
Sometimes when Manny was sleeping,
I'd come out here and just sit.

853
00:56:37,853 --> 00:56:39,730
I had to get out
of that trailer.

854
00:56:39,731 --> 00:56:41,606
I couldn't stand being
cooped up all the time.

855
00:56:44,360 --> 00:56:46,987
I'm... I'm lonely, Paul.

856
00:56:47,071 --> 00:56:49,114
I'm awful lonely.

857
00:56:49,198 --> 00:56:52,867
I wouldn't have gone to that roadhouse
if it weren't for that, you know.

858
00:56:52,952 --> 00:56:56,246
Maybe you're getting in
some good practice being lonely.

859
00:56:57,081 --> 00:56:59,249
You mean you think
maybe Manny won't get off?

860
00:56:59,333 --> 00:57:02,544
That'll be up to the jury,
and you can never tell about them.

861
00:57:02,628 --> 00:57:05,171
If he didn't, it'd be one way to end it.

862
00:57:05,881 --> 00:57:09,092
No. I don't mean that.
I... I may think it sometimes...

863
00:57:09,176 --> 00:57:11,553
but I don't really want it.

864
00:57:23,190 --> 00:57:25,108
[Muff Barks]

865
00:57:25,192 --> 00:57:28,403
Hello, sweetie. Did ya miss me?

866
00:57:28,487 --> 00:57:30,447
Of course you missed me.

867
00:57:32,950 --> 00:57:35,201
You wanna come in, Paul?

868
00:57:35,286 --> 00:57:37,621
You can if you want to, you know.

869
00:57:38,956 --> 00:57:41,291
No, thank you, Laura.

870
00:57:41,375 --> 00:57:45,337
I'm sorry I had to spoil
your fun over at that place. I...

871
00:57:46,714 --> 00:57:50,300
- Good night, Laura.
- Good night.

872
00:58:17,870 --> 00:58:20,121
Hear ye, hear ye, hear ye.

873
00:58:20,206 --> 00:58:25,126
The Circuit Court for the County
of Iron Cliffs is now in session.

874
00:58:25,211 --> 00:58:27,170
You can be seated.

875
00:58:32,635 --> 00:58:36,513
For those of you I haven't met,
my name is Weaver.

876
00:58:36,597 --> 00:58:38,932
I'm from downstate,
and I'm sitting

877
00:58:38,933 --> 00:58:41,267
temporarily while your
good Judge Maitland...

878
00:58:41,352 --> 00:58:43,937
is recovering from a severe illness.

879
00:58:44,021 --> 00:58:47,315
There's no need, I think,
to dwell at length upon my methods.

880
00:58:47,400 --> 00:58:50,026
One judge is quite like another.

881
00:58:50,111 --> 00:58:53,947
The only differences may be in the state
of their digestions...

882
00:58:54,031 --> 00:58:57,409
or their proclivities
for sleeping on the bench.

883
00:58:57,493 --> 00:59:00,870
For myself, I can digest pig iron.

884
00:59:00,955 --> 00:59:03,415
And while I might appear
to doze occasionally,

885
00:59:03,416 --> 00:59:05,875
you'll find that I'm
easily awakened...

886
00:59:05,960 --> 00:59:11,256
particularly if shaken gently
by a good lawyer with a nice point of law.

887
00:59:12,883 --> 00:59:16,761
We will now take up the criminal docket.
Case number one.

888
00:59:16,846 --> 00:59:19,931
The People versus Clarence Madigan.

889
00:59:20,015 --> 00:59:22,809
Breaking and entering in the nighttime.

890
00:59:22,893 --> 00:59:25,979
Will the defendant rise and come forward?

891
00:59:26,063 --> 00:59:28,022
That's me, Your Honor.

892
00:59:36,240 --> 00:59:38,366
"State of Michigan, Court of Iron Cliffs.

893
00:59:38,451 --> 00:59:40,493
I, Mitchell Lodwick,
prosecuting attorney...

894
00:59:40,578 --> 00:59:43,538
come into said county of Iron Cliffs
and give the court to understand...

895
00:59:43,622 --> 00:59:45,540
that one Clarence Madigan...

896
00:59:45,624 --> 00:59:49,169
alias 'One-Shot' Madigan,
alias 'Smoky' Madigan...

897
00:59:49,253 --> 00:59:51,337
did break and enter
the dwelling house of Casper Katz...

898
00:59:51,422 --> 00:59:54,340
and did there commit the felony
of larceny on said premises."

899
00:59:55,426 --> 00:59:58,428
Does Mr. Madigan have an attorney?

900
00:59:58,512 --> 01:00:02,307
Oh, no. A man's gotta have money
to ask them fellas the time of day.

901
01:00:02,391 --> 01:00:04,934
Mr. Madigan, if you're impoverished,
it's my duty...

902
01:00:05,019 --> 01:00:07,520
to appoint an attorney on your behalf.

903
01:00:07,605 --> 01:00:11,191
Oh, I wouldn't bother, Your Honor.
I stole the whiskey.

904
01:00:11,275 --> 01:00:13,151
I'm guilty as hell.

905
01:00:13,235 --> 01:00:15,528
It was a full case of expensive bourbon,
Your Honor.

906
01:00:15,613 --> 01:00:18,865
- Did you sell this whiskey?
- Oh, no. I drank it.

907
01:00:18,949 --> 01:00:20,742
- All of it?
- You bet, Judge.

908
01:00:20,826 --> 01:00:24,162
Are you aware that it will be necessary
to punish you for this crime?

909
01:00:24,246 --> 01:00:26,206
It was worth it, Your Honor.

910
01:00:26,290 --> 01:00:28,375
Well, I'll accept your plea
of guilty, Mr. Madigan.

911
01:00:28,376 --> 01:00:30,460
You'll be sentenced later.

912
01:00:30,544 --> 01:00:33,838
- You may now return to your place.
- Thanks, Your Honor.

913
01:00:35,883 --> 01:00:40,720
Case number two.
The People versus Frederick Manion.

914
01:00:40,805 --> 01:00:42,972
The charge: murder.

915
01:00:43,057 --> 01:00:47,685
Paul Biegler for the defendant.
My formal appearance is already on file.

916
01:00:47,770 --> 01:00:50,563
Which of these men is your client,
Mr. Biegler?

917
01:00:50,648 --> 01:00:52,982
- None of them, Your Honor.
- Mr. Sheriff...

918
01:00:53,067 --> 01:00:55,443
will you produce the prisoner?

919
01:00:55,528 --> 01:00:59,072
Well, I... I'm afraid I can't do that,
Your Honor.

920
01:00:59,156 --> 01:01:02,492
Perhaps someone should explain.
I'm not clairvoyant.

921
01:01:02,576 --> 01:01:06,830
The defendant is in Detroit being examined
by a psychiatrist, Your Honor.

922
01:01:06,914 --> 01:01:08,873
Shouldn't the court have been consulted...

923
01:01:08,958 --> 01:01:11,918
before the defendant
was allowed to leave its jurisdiction?

924
01:01:12,002 --> 01:01:14,879
Well, Your Honor, we're dealing
with the army in this matter...

925
01:01:14,964 --> 01:01:18,258
and this was the only crack the army would
give us at one of their psychiatrists.

926
01:01:18,342 --> 01:01:20,426
The court was not present,
and it was very urgent...

927
01:01:20,511 --> 01:01:23,096
that we get the defendant
to the psychiatrist.

928
01:01:23,180 --> 01:01:25,515
What does the attorney
for the People say to this?

929
01:01:25,599 --> 01:01:27,350
It was done with my knowledge, Your Honor.

930
01:01:27,434 --> 01:01:32,438
I've always heard that this Upper Peninsula
of our fair state was a queer place.

931
01:01:32,523 --> 01:01:34,983
If it's customary here to
allow a man charged with

932
01:01:34,984 --> 01:01:37,443
first-degree murder to
wander about at will...

933
01:01:37,528 --> 01:01:41,197
I don't suppose it behooves
an outsider to point out...

934
01:01:41,282 --> 01:01:45,326
that the law makes no provision
for such quaint liberalism.

935
01:01:45,411 --> 01:01:47,809
Your Honor, the defendant
is in the care of a

936
01:01:47,810 --> 01:01:50,206
deputy and will be
returned this afternoon.

937
01:01:50,291 --> 01:01:53,960
We'll formally arraign
the defendant on his return.

938
01:01:54,044 --> 01:01:57,463
For the sake of the docket,
can you give me a clue as to his plea?

939
01:01:57,548 --> 01:02:00,758
The defendant will waive reading
of the information and stand mute.

940
01:02:00,843 --> 01:02:03,303
A plea of not guilty will be entered.

941
01:02:03,387 --> 01:02:08,141
The case of Frederick Manion
will be placed first on the trial docket.

942
01:02:18,861 --> 01:02:21,029
Can you hurry it up, Polly?
Somebody tells that judge...

943
01:02:21,113 --> 01:02:22,969
the prisoner was
lounging around the rail

944
01:02:22,970 --> 01:02:24,824
road station, he'll
really give me the works.

945
01:02:24,909 --> 01:02:26,701
- Just take a minute, Sheriff.
- Okay.

946
01:02:26,785 --> 01:02:29,037
Thank you. Come on over here.

947
01:02:31,999 --> 01:02:34,709
Well, Lieutenant, how'd things turn out?

948
01:02:34,793 --> 01:02:37,170
- I was temporarily insane.
- Did he tell you that?

949
01:02:37,254 --> 01:02:40,465
Yeah. Said he's gonna write you a letter...

950
01:02:40,549 --> 01:02:43,343
but, uh, I took some notes on my own.

951
01:02:43,427 --> 01:02:45,803
- Doctor's name is Smith.
- Smith.

952
01:02:45,888 --> 01:02:50,183
Anatole Ludwig Smith
or, uh, Ludwig von Smith, I hope.

953
01:02:50,267 --> 01:02:53,436
- A name like that would impress the jury.
- No, just plain Matthew Smith.

954
01:02:53,520 --> 01:02:58,441
He said that when I shot Quill, I was
suffering from "dissociative reaction."

955
01:02:58,525 --> 01:03:02,445
Dissociative reaction.
Sounds pretty good, doesn't it, Parn?

956
01:03:02,529 --> 01:03:05,323
- Yeah. What does it mean in plain English?
- Well, it means I had...

957
01:03:05,407 --> 01:03:08,576
"an irresistible impulse to shoot Quill."

958
01:03:11,288 --> 01:03:12,956
That's okay, isn't it?

959
01:03:13,040 --> 01:03:15,375
Yeah, but what did he say
about your knowing the difference...

960
01:03:15,459 --> 01:03:17,543
between right and wrong
when you shot Quill?

961
01:03:17,628 --> 01:03:20,421
I don't think he said anything.
Why? Is that important?

962
01:03:21,548 --> 01:03:24,133
We better not keep the sheriff waiting.
You better go.

963
01:03:30,516 --> 01:03:32,475
[McCarthy] Thank you, Sheriff.

964
01:03:43,570 --> 01:03:47,907
You ever heard of a Michigan court
accepting irresistible impulse as insanity?

965
01:03:47,992 --> 01:03:51,244
No. Maybe we better switch to self-defense.

966
01:03:51,328 --> 01:03:53,663
Even Mitch Lodwick would make
a monkey out of us on that.

967
01:03:53,747 --> 01:03:56,416
[Belches] Damn strawberry soda.

968
01:03:56,500 --> 01:03:58,835
- Here. Want a peanut?
- No, thanks.

969
01:03:59,503 --> 01:04:01,796
Well, tomorrow's Saturday.

970
01:04:01,880 --> 01:04:04,382
We just have the weekend before the trial.

971
01:04:04,466 --> 01:04:08,678
- When do you want to start working?
- Tomorrow morning, early.

972
01:04:12,266 --> 01:04:14,434
[Bell Tolling]

973
01:04:46,050 --> 01:04:47,967
[Clatter]

974
01:05:03,984 --> 01:05:06,402
- Polly!
- Hey, listen to this, Parn.

975
01:05:06,487 --> 01:05:09,238
Never mind that. Just find...

976
01:05:09,865 --> 01:05:15,161
People versus Durfee,
62 Michigan, 486. Year 1886.

977
01:05:15,245 --> 01:05:17,497
Yeah, that's it.
I have it right here in the A.L.R.

978
01:05:17,581 --> 01:05:21,584
Listen. "The right-and-wrong test,
though condemned as being unscientific...

979
01:05:21,668 --> 01:05:23,628
is adhered to by most
of the states, but"...

980
01:05:23,712 --> 01:05:28,007
Listen to this "but." "But the fact
that one accused of committing a crime...

981
01:05:28,092 --> 01:05:33,012
may have been able to comprehend the
nature and the consequences of this act...

982
01:05:33,097 --> 01:05:36,390
and to know that it was
wrong, nevertheless"...

983
01:05:36,475 --> 01:05:39,352
Dear, sweet, endearing
word, "nevertheless"!

984
01:05:39,436 --> 01:05:44,857
"Nevertheless, if he was forced
to its execution by an impulse...

985
01:05:44,942 --> 01:05:47,985
by an impulse which he was
powerless to control...

986
01:05:48,070 --> 01:05:50,696
he will be excused from punishment."

987
01:05:50,781 --> 01:05:54,408
Why, the Michigan Supreme Court
did accept irresistible impulse, Parn.

988
01:05:54,493 --> 01:05:56,516
This is precedent.

989
01:05:56,517 --> 01:05:58,538
Boy, I think we got ahold
of something here.

990
01:05:58,622 --> 01:06:01,207
Good old Durfee, 1886.

991
01:06:01,291 --> 01:06:03,417
How about that? Give me a pad.

992
01:06:04,002 --> 01:06:05,941
By the saints, this
strawberry soda pop is

993
01:06:05,942 --> 01:06:07,880
beginning to taste like
real bourbon whiskey.

994
01:06:07,965 --> 01:06:11,551
Well, don't get drunk yet.
You know, we've got to convince a jury...

995
01:06:11,635 --> 01:06:14,637
that our client was irresistibly impulsed.

996
01:06:14,721 --> 01:06:16,305
Remember that.

997
01:06:17,349 --> 01:06:19,934
Ladies and gentlemen of the jury...

998
01:06:20,018 --> 01:06:23,729
before we proceed further, it will be
necessary for me to examine you...

999
01:06:23,814 --> 01:06:27,650
on your qualifications to sit as jurors.

1000
01:06:27,734 --> 01:06:30,319
Will you please remember
that you are under oath?

1001
01:06:30,404 --> 01:06:32,947
Are all of you citizens?

1002
01:06:33,031 --> 01:06:35,700
Will you please raise
your hand if you are not.

1003
01:06:48,589 --> 01:06:53,551
Are there any justices of the peace
or law enforcement officers among you?

1004
01:06:53,635 --> 01:06:55,803
[Jury] No.

1005
01:06:55,888 --> 01:07:00,808
Are any of you related by blood or marriage
to any law enforcement officer?

1006
01:07:00,893 --> 01:07:03,769
- [Jury] No.
- So much for qualifications.

1007
01:07:03,854 --> 01:07:06,606
I will now examine for cause.

1008
01:07:06,690 --> 01:07:08,817
Do any of you have any
business pending with

1009
01:07:08,818 --> 01:07:10,943
the prosecuting attorney,
Mitchell Lodwick?

1010
01:07:11,028 --> 01:07:12,904
[Jury] No.

1011
01:07:12,988 --> 01:07:15,615
Do any of you have any
business pending with

1012
01:07:15,616 --> 01:07:18,242
Paul Biegler, attorney
for the defense?

1013
01:07:18,327 --> 01:07:19,619
No.

1014
01:07:19,703 --> 01:07:22,079
Are any of you acquainted
with the defendant...

1015
01:07:22,164 --> 01:07:24,749
sitting there on Mr. Biegler's left?

1016
01:07:24,833 --> 01:07:27,627
- [Jury] No.
- Will Mrs. Laura Manion...

1017
01:07:27,711 --> 01:07:29,921
the defendant's wife please stand?

1018
01:07:31,340 --> 01:07:34,467
- Do any of you know Mrs. Manion?
- No.

1019
01:07:34,551 --> 01:07:37,261
Thank you, Mrs. Manion.
You may be seated.

1020
01:07:38,305 --> 01:07:40,640
Counsel may challenge the jury for cause.

1021
01:07:40,724 --> 01:07:46,270
Your Honor, before counsel's challenge, may
I introduce Mr. Claude Dancer to the court?

1022
01:07:46,355 --> 01:07:49,440
Mr. Dancer is an assistant attorney general
from Lansing.

1023
01:07:49,524 --> 01:07:51,609
Because of the peculiar
nature of this case,

1024
01:07:51,610 --> 01:07:53,694
I have requested the
attorney general...

1025
01:07:53,779 --> 01:07:56,239
to allow Mr. Dancer to sit in
with the prosecution.

1026
01:07:56,323 --> 01:07:58,950
Your reputation precedes you, Mr. Dancer.

1027
01:07:59,034 --> 01:08:01,327
It's a privilege to have you in my court.

1028
01:08:01,411 --> 01:08:04,330
Thank you, Your Honor.
I'm sure it will be instructive.

1029
01:08:04,414 --> 01:08:07,083
Do any of you jurors
have any business pending...

1030
01:08:07,167 --> 01:08:09,168
before the attorney general's office?

1031
01:08:09,253 --> 01:08:10,753
No.

1032
01:08:11,838 --> 01:08:14,757
I must apologize for my
disparaging remarks...

1033
01:08:14,841 --> 01:08:17,635
about the Upper Peninsula and its customs.

1034
01:08:17,719 --> 01:08:22,890
I've seldom seen a murder jury
selected and sworn in less than half a day.

1035
01:08:22,975 --> 01:08:26,185
You have won my heart
completely, gentlemen.

1036
01:08:26,270 --> 01:08:29,689
Now, Mr. Dancer, you asked for the recess.
What's your problem?

1037
01:08:29,773 --> 01:08:32,608
There was a little suggestion
I wanted to make, Your Honor.

1038
01:08:32,693 --> 01:08:36,362
- By all means.
- Since the defense plea is insanity...

1039
01:08:36,446 --> 01:08:38,698
the prosecution has
retained a psychiatrist.

1040
01:08:38,782 --> 01:08:41,659
Under the statute, we have the right
to petition for a mental examination...

1041
01:08:41,743 --> 01:08:43,828
of the defendant by our own doctor.

1042
01:08:43,912 --> 01:08:45,955
Are you familiar with that statute,
Mr. Biegler?

1043
01:08:46,039 --> 01:08:48,207
Uh-huh. Moderately.

1044
01:08:48,292 --> 01:08:50,793
I think it would only
delay things to file a formal petition...

1045
01:08:50,877 --> 01:08:53,212
so why don't we just, uh,
get together and sort of...

1046
01:08:53,297 --> 01:08:55,298
informally agree to ask His Honor
for an adjournment?

1047
01:08:55,382 --> 01:08:58,259
Only a day or so, and our doctor
can visit with the defendant.

1048
01:08:58,343 --> 01:08:59,844
I think it would save everyone
a great deal of time.

1049
01:08:59,845 --> 01:09:01,345
Don't you, Mr. Biegler?

1050
01:09:01,430 --> 01:09:03,389
- Yes, I'm sure it will.
- Good.

1051
01:09:03,473 --> 01:09:08,227
But suppose you just go ahead
and file that formal petition anyway.

1052
01:09:08,312 --> 01:09:10,313
Of course, you're a little late, aren't ya?

1053
01:09:10,397 --> 01:09:12,315
Well, maybe His Honor will overlook that.

1054
01:09:12,399 --> 01:09:14,483
And then, I'd sort of
like the jury to see...

1055
01:09:14,568 --> 01:09:17,194
that you think our insanity plea
has some merit.

1056
01:09:17,279 --> 01:09:19,739
There really won't be any need for
our doctor to examine your client.

1057
01:09:19,823 --> 01:09:21,741
Naturally, I was only following
the usual procedure.

1058
01:09:21,825 --> 01:09:23,743
- Well, naturally, I'm all for it.
- Uh-huh.

1059
01:09:23,827 --> 01:09:26,370
Do you wish to file the petition or not,
Mr. Dancer?

1060
01:09:26,455 --> 01:09:28,205
- Yes, Your Honor...
- It won't be necessary.

1061
01:09:28,290 --> 01:09:29,999
That's right. It won't be necessary at all.

1062
01:09:30,083 --> 01:09:33,878
Skirmish over.
Shall we join now on the field of battle?

1063
01:09:37,758 --> 01:09:42,011
The body of Quill had sustained
five gunshot wounds.

1064
01:09:42,095 --> 01:09:45,014
One of the bullets
had passed through the heart.

1065
01:09:45,098 --> 01:09:48,768
Death, in my opinion,
was almost instantaneous...

1066
01:09:48,852 --> 01:09:50,770
and was directly caused by this wound.

1067
01:09:50,854 --> 01:09:52,877
Dr. Raschid, may I have
your detailed report?

1068
01:09:52,878 --> 01:09:54,899
Certainly.

1069
01:09:54,983 --> 01:09:59,028
I ask that this report be marked
People's Exhibit One for identification.

1070
01:09:59,112 --> 01:10:01,322
So received and marked.

1071
01:10:01,406 --> 01:10:04,033
The People hand the defense
a copy of the report.

1072
01:10:04,576 --> 01:10:06,619
Counsel may cross-examine.

1073
01:10:06,703 --> 01:10:11,624
Dr. Raschid, your primary purpose was to
ascertain the cause of death, was it not?

1074
01:10:11,708 --> 01:10:12,833
Yes.

1075
01:10:12,918 --> 01:10:15,961
And yet, I read in your report here,
that you checked...

1076
01:10:16,046 --> 01:10:18,506
to determine whether
spermatogenesis was occurring...

1077
01:10:18,590 --> 01:10:20,966
in the body of the deceased
at the time of death.

1078
01:10:21,051 --> 01:10:25,888
Objection, Your Honor. The People call this
witness only to show the cause of death.

1079
01:10:25,972 --> 01:10:28,599
Your Honor, the entire report
was offered as evidence...

1080
01:10:28,683 --> 01:10:31,727
and the report contains this information
about spermatogenesis.

1081
01:10:31,812 --> 01:10:35,022
Overruled, Mr. Lodwick.
The witness may answer.

1082
01:10:35,649 --> 01:10:38,651
Yes, I made that examination
on the deceased.

1083
01:10:38,735 --> 01:10:41,737
Now, would you tell the
court your findings?

1084
01:10:41,822 --> 01:10:44,782
Spermatogenesis was occurring
at the time of death.

1085
01:10:44,866 --> 01:10:49,370
In other words, the deceased, in life,
was not sterile. He could produce children.

1086
01:10:49,454 --> 01:10:51,414
- That is correct.
- Now, Doctor...

1087
01:10:51,498 --> 01:10:55,835
if a woman says that she has had
intercourse with a certain man...

1088
01:10:55,919 --> 01:11:00,005
and the man is proved fertile, even though
no evidence is found in the woman's body...

1089
01:11:00,090 --> 01:11:02,383
could a lawyer...
say a prosecuting attorney...

1090
01:11:02,467 --> 01:11:06,011
could he use this as evidence
that the woman is lying?

1091
01:11:06,096 --> 01:11:10,766
Your Honor.
I, uh, object to this line of questioning.

1092
01:11:10,851 --> 01:11:12,935
We're not concerned here
with whether or not...

1093
01:11:13,019 --> 01:11:15,438
there have been relations
between a man and a woman.

1094
01:11:15,522 --> 01:11:18,858
Your Honor, as long as an examination
for spermatogenesis has been made...

1095
01:11:18,942 --> 01:11:20,693
at least we're entitled to know why.

1096
01:11:20,777 --> 01:11:22,528
Overruled. You may answer.

1097
01:11:22,612 --> 01:11:25,573
Yes. Prosecution could use that...

1098
01:11:25,657 --> 01:11:29,201
though it certainly
would not be conclusive that she was lying.

1099
01:11:29,286 --> 01:11:31,954
- Why not?
- There could be several reasons...

1100
01:11:32,038 --> 01:11:33,956
why the test on her was negative.

1101
01:11:34,040 --> 01:11:37,084
The, uh, use of a contraceptive...

1102
01:11:37,169 --> 01:11:40,963
or... or possibly there was no completion
on the part of the man.

1103
01:11:41,047 --> 01:11:43,883
Now, on this postmortem were you also asked
to determine whether or not...

1104
01:11:43,967 --> 01:11:48,137
the deceased had reached
a sexual climax shortly before his death?

1105
01:11:48,221 --> 01:11:50,764
- No, sir.
- Could you have made such a determination?

1106
01:11:50,849 --> 01:11:52,349
Oh, yes.

1107
01:11:52,434 --> 01:11:55,144
So you were only asked
to make such examination...

1108
01:11:55,228 --> 01:11:58,230
as might be useful to the prosecution,
none that might help the defense?

1109
01:11:58,315 --> 01:12:02,359
I object, Your Honor.
The question is argumentative.

1110
01:12:02,444 --> 01:12:04,987
Counsel for the defense
is trying to impugn the intent...

1111
01:12:05,071 --> 01:12:06,989
of the representatives of the People.

1112
01:12:07,073 --> 01:12:10,242
Mr. Biegler, you must be aware
that the question is improper.

1113
01:12:10,327 --> 01:12:12,912
I withdraw the question, Your Honor,
and apologize.

1114
01:12:12,996 --> 01:12:15,414
The question and answer will be stricken...

1115
01:12:15,499 --> 01:12:19,084
and the jury will disregard
both the question and the answer.

1116
01:12:20,045 --> 01:12:22,755
- That's all the questions I had.
- No redirect.

1117
01:12:22,839 --> 01:12:26,091
The People now call Lloyd Burke.

1118
01:12:26,176 --> 01:12:28,802
[Bailiff]
Will the witness step forward, please.

1119
01:12:32,349 --> 01:12:36,185
[Whispering] How can a jury disregard
what it's already heard?

1120
01:12:36,770 --> 01:12:40,773
They can't, Lieutenant. They can't.

1121
01:12:40,857 --> 01:12:44,276
...The whole truth,
and nothing but the truth, so help you God?

1122
01:12:44,361 --> 01:12:46,445
- I do.
- Sit down, please.

1123
01:12:47,280 --> 01:12:49,615
Will you state your profession,
please, Mr. Burke?

1124
01:12:49,699 --> 01:12:53,869
- I'm a commercial photographer.
- Were you called upon by the police...

1125
01:12:53,954 --> 01:12:57,790
to take photographs of the body
of the deceased Bernard Quill...

1126
01:12:57,874 --> 01:13:00,751
before and after he was removed
from the scene of death?

1127
01:13:00,835 --> 01:13:02,002
Yes, sir, I was.

1128
01:13:02,087 --> 01:13:04,838
Were these photographs
of the deceased made by you?

1129
01:13:09,386 --> 01:13:11,387
They were.

1130
01:13:11,471 --> 01:13:13,389
The reporter will please mark
these photographs...

1131
01:13:13,473 --> 01:13:16,392
People's Exhibit 2A to
2D for identification.

1132
01:13:16,476 --> 01:13:19,853
Photographs are tendered
to the defense for examination...

1133
01:13:19,938 --> 01:13:22,147
and the People move
their admission as evidence.

1134
01:13:22,232 --> 01:13:24,984
- Your witness.
- Uh, no questions. No objections.

1135
01:13:25,068 --> 01:13:27,444
Paul, he took pictures
of me that night too.

1136
01:13:27,529 --> 01:13:29,863
Just a minute, Mr. Burke.

1137
01:13:29,948 --> 01:13:33,075
Uh, Mr. Burke...

1138
01:13:33,159 --> 01:13:35,160
these photographs offered as evidence...

1139
01:13:35,245 --> 01:13:37,913
are they the only photographs
you took that night?

1140
01:13:37,998 --> 01:13:39,999
Why, uh, no.

1141
01:13:40,083 --> 01:13:42,251
I suppose the others didn't turn out.
ls that it?

1142
01:13:43,169 --> 01:13:45,087
All my pictures turn out!

1143
01:13:45,171 --> 01:13:48,048
- [Spectators Laugh]
- Oh, of course. I... I beg your pardon.

1144
01:13:48,133 --> 01:13:50,843
Did you give the other
pictures to the police?

1145
01:13:50,927 --> 01:13:53,846
- Yes, sir, I did.
- Well, Mr. Burke, what were they?

1146
01:13:53,930 --> 01:13:57,600
Were they side shots,
or a shot of the moon, perhaps?

1147
01:13:57,684 --> 01:13:59,164
Or a black bear scavenging
the Thunder Bay dump?

1148
01:13:59,165 --> 01:14:00,644
[Spectators Laugh]

1149
01:14:00,729 --> 01:14:02,647
Your Honor, I object!

1150
01:14:02,648 --> 01:14:04,565
I can't see how other
photographs are relevant.

1151
01:14:04,649 --> 01:14:06,567
The photographs in evidence
were introduced...

1152
01:14:06,651 --> 01:14:09,361
to show that the deceased
met with a violent death.

1153
01:14:09,446 --> 01:14:11,218
Well, Your Honor, I should
think any photograph

1154
01:14:11,219 --> 01:14:12,990
pertaining to the case
would be relevant.

1155
01:14:13,074 --> 01:14:15,951
The point is good, Mr. Biegler. Continue.

1156
01:14:16,036 --> 01:14:18,829
What were these other
photographs of, Mr. Burke?

1157
01:14:19,623 --> 01:14:21,332
Lieutenant Manion's wife.

1158
01:14:21,416 --> 01:14:23,397
You mean these photographs
showed how she looked

1159
01:14:23,398 --> 01:14:25,377
that night after Barney
Quill was killed?

1160
01:14:25,462 --> 01:14:28,547
- Yes.
- Your Honor, how she looked is irrelevant.

1161
01:14:28,632 --> 01:14:30,425
No evidence has been
introduced to connect Mrs.

1162
01:14:30,426 --> 01:14:32,217
Manion's appearance to
a charge of murder.

1163
01:14:32,302 --> 01:14:34,428
- [Judge Weaver] Sustained.
- I'm sorry, Your Honor.

1164
01:14:34,512 --> 01:14:37,765
I just wanted to make sure the prosecution
wasn't withholding evidence.

1165
01:14:37,849 --> 01:14:39,767
Now look here!

1166
01:14:39,851 --> 01:14:42,895
I protest to the defense attorney's
persistent attacks...

1167
01:14:42,979 --> 01:14:45,397
on the motives of the prosecution.

1168
01:14:45,482 --> 01:14:50,152
The jury will disregard the remark
made by the attorney for the defense.

1169
01:14:50,236 --> 01:14:54,573
There's no reason to believe that the
prosecution has not acted in good faith.

1170
01:14:54,658 --> 01:14:57,701
My apologies to the prosecution,
and to the court.

1171
01:14:57,786 --> 01:15:01,497
But, Your Honor,
as long as protests are being made...

1172
01:15:01,581 --> 01:15:03,749
I'd like to make a protest myself.

1173
01:15:03,833 --> 01:15:09,088
Now, I'm perfectly willing to take on
these two legal giants anytime, anyplace...

1174
01:15:09,172 --> 01:15:12,049
but in all fairness,
it ought to be one at a time.

1175
01:15:12,133 --> 01:15:15,761
I don't want these two fellows pitching
knuckleballs at me at the same time.

1176
01:15:15,845 --> 01:15:19,098
It seems to me you're batting
close to a thousand, Mr. Biegler...

1177
01:15:19,182 --> 01:15:21,809
but your point is well taken.

1178
01:15:21,893 --> 01:15:24,436
Whichever attorney opens
with the witness...

1179
01:15:24,521 --> 01:15:29,191
he alone shall continue with that witness
until the witness is excused.

1180
01:15:29,275 --> 01:15:31,402
Thank you, Your Honor. No more questions.

1181
01:15:31,486 --> 01:15:33,404
No questions.

1182
01:15:44,207 --> 01:15:46,959
- My, we're drawing well, aren't we?
- Where's Parnell?

1183
01:15:47,043 --> 01:15:49,086
Parnell? Why? Isn't he here?

1184
01:15:49,170 --> 01:15:52,297
No, he's not here. He's not in his rooming
house, and he hasn't been there all night.

1185
01:15:52,382 --> 01:15:54,299
You were the last to see him. Where is he?

1186
01:15:54,384 --> 01:15:56,301
I promised not to tell, so don't ask me.

1187
01:15:56,386 --> 01:16:00,055
- Aw, he hasn't fallen off the wagon?
- No. He was sober.

1188
01:16:00,140 --> 01:16:02,058
Has he gone somewhere?

1189
01:16:02,059 --> 01:16:03,976
He did borrow my car
for something or other.

1190
01:16:04,060 --> 01:16:07,062
Your car? That was smart.
He hasn't driven a car in 20 years.

1191
01:16:07,147 --> 01:16:09,189
He'll kill himself. Now where's he gone?

1192
01:16:09,274 --> 01:16:11,316
My word is my bond.

1193
01:16:18,742 --> 01:16:21,201
## [Humming]

1194
01:16:36,634 --> 01:16:38,552
Good morning, ladies and gentlemen.

1195
01:16:38,636 --> 01:16:40,512
- [Jury] Good morning.
- You may proceed.

1196
01:16:40,597 --> 01:16:43,182
Your Honor, the, uh...

1197
01:16:43,266 --> 01:16:47,019
the defense notices a third person
at the prosecution's table.

1198
01:16:47,103 --> 01:16:50,314
We were wondering if the court
shares our curiosity as to just who he is.

1199
01:16:50,398 --> 01:16:52,316
I was about to introduce him.

1200
01:16:52,400 --> 01:16:56,320
Your Honor, this gentleman
is Dr. W. Gregory Harcourt.

1201
01:16:56,404 --> 01:17:00,365
Dr. Harcourt is the People's psychiatrist
in this case.

1202
01:17:00,450 --> 01:17:05,037
We ask that Dr. Harcourt be allowed
to sit at our table as an observer.

1203
01:17:05,121 --> 01:17:07,831
What are you gonna have him observe?
The constellation of Taurus...

1204
01:17:07,916 --> 01:17:10,292
- or the life and times of a bumblebee?
- [Laughter]

1205
01:17:10,376 --> 01:17:12,294
To observe the defendant, of course.

1206
01:17:12,378 --> 01:17:14,630
Oh! Oh, well, that's fine. That's fine.

1207
01:17:14,714 --> 01:17:18,509
The defense has no objection, Your Honor.
I just wish to express my relief...

1208
01:17:18,593 --> 01:17:23,889
that the new recruit is not additional
legal reinforcements from Lansing.

1209
01:17:23,973 --> 01:17:26,308
- [Spectators Chuckle]
- [Lodwick] Call Alphonse Paquette.

1210
01:17:32,482 --> 01:17:34,441
Raise your right hand, please.

1211
01:17:34,526 --> 01:17:37,069
You do solemnly swear that the testimony
you shall give in this cause...

1212
01:17:37,153 --> 01:17:40,906
shall be the truth, the whole truth
and nothing but the truth, so help you God?

1213
01:17:40,990 --> 01:17:42,908
- [Paquette] I do.
- Take a seat, please.

1214
01:17:45,662 --> 01:17:49,164
- Will you state your name, please.
- Alphonse Paquette.

1215
01:17:49,249 --> 01:17:51,875
You work at the Thunder Bay Inn,
don't you, Mr. Paquette?

1216
01:17:51,960 --> 01:17:53,418
I'm bartender there.

1217
01:17:53,503 --> 01:17:56,797
Were you working on the night that Barney
Quill was shot by Frederick Manion?

1218
01:17:56,881 --> 01:17:59,258
- I was.
- Were you witness to the shooting?

1219
01:17:59,342 --> 01:18:00,467
I was.

1220
01:18:00,552 --> 01:18:03,512
Will you tell us in your own words,
please, what happened?

1221
01:18:04,514 --> 01:18:07,933
I was at a table by the door
when Lieutenant Manion came in.

1222
01:18:08,017 --> 01:18:10,310
Did you know Lieutenant Manion
by sight and by name?

1223
01:18:10,395 --> 01:18:12,855
- Yes, sir.
- Go ahead.

1224
01:18:12,939 --> 01:18:15,274
Well, he came in
and walked over to the bar...

1225
01:18:15,358 --> 01:18:17,693
and began to shoot.

1226
01:18:17,777 --> 01:18:21,029
He shot Barney when he came up to the bar,
and when Barney fell...

1227
01:18:21,114 --> 01:18:24,032
he kept on shooting down at Barney,
behind the bar.

1228
01:18:24,117 --> 01:18:26,034
Then he turned around and walked out.

1229
01:18:26,119 --> 01:18:30,414
When Lieutenant Manion entered the bar,
how did he appear to you?

1230
01:18:30,498 --> 01:18:33,000
Well, he walked slow.

1231
01:18:33,084 --> 01:18:35,335
Kind of deliberate, I guess you could say.

1232
01:18:35,420 --> 01:18:38,797
- Did he speak to Barney Quill?
- Not a word.

1233
01:18:38,882 --> 01:18:42,384
Just walked over and pulled out
his gun, and bang.

1234
01:18:42,468 --> 01:18:45,637
- And then he walked out.
- Yes.

1235
01:18:45,722 --> 01:18:48,932
When he walked out, how
did he appear to you?

1236
01:18:49,017 --> 01:18:51,518
He seemed just like he
did when he walked in.

1237
01:18:51,603 --> 01:18:53,812
Like he was the mailman
delivering the mail.

1238
01:18:53,897 --> 01:18:57,399
[Lodwick] When Lieutenant Manion
walked out of the bar, what did you do?

1239
01:18:57,483 --> 01:19:00,652
[Paquette] Well, it happened so fast,
I guess I was stunned.

1240
01:19:00,737 --> 01:19:03,655
- But then I ran out after him.
- Did you find him outside?

1241
01:19:03,740 --> 01:19:06,491
- Yes, sir. He was walking away.
- Did you speak to him?

1242
01:19:06,576 --> 01:19:10,829
Yes, sir. I said, uh, "Lieutenant,
you'd better not run away from this."

1243
01:19:10,914 --> 01:19:13,332
Did he reply to you?

1244
01:19:13,416 --> 01:19:16,877
He said, "Do you want some too, buster?"

1245
01:19:16,961 --> 01:19:19,004
Was he pointing the gun at you?

1246
01:19:19,088 --> 01:19:22,841
Well, he was holding the gun in my
direction, but the muzzle was low.

1247
01:19:22,926 --> 01:19:26,762
When he said,
"Do you want some too, buster?"

1248
01:19:26,846 --> 01:19:28,764
how was that expressed?

1249
01:19:28,848 --> 01:19:31,934
Did he shout it? Was it hysterical?

1250
01:19:32,018 --> 01:19:35,854
- Was he hoarse? Did his voice tremble?
- No, sir.

1251
01:19:35,939 --> 01:19:39,191
He just said it cool and hard
and looked right at me.

1252
01:19:39,275 --> 01:19:42,361
Did he appear to you,
as far as you could tell...

1253
01:19:42,445 --> 01:19:45,614
to be in complete possession
of his faculties?

1254
01:19:45,698 --> 01:19:49,159
- Yes, sir, far as I could tell.
- Your witness.

1255
01:19:49,243 --> 01:19:51,536
Mr. Paquette, did you see Laura Manion...

1256
01:19:51,621 --> 01:19:53,872
the wife of Lieutenant Manion,
in the bar that night?

1257
01:19:53,957 --> 01:19:57,209
Your Honor, there he goes again.
This is immaterial and irrelevant.

1258
01:19:57,293 --> 01:19:59,253
Your Honor, I don't see
what the prosecution's

1259
01:19:59,254 --> 01:20:01,213
so jumpy about.
I haven't gone anyplace yet.

1260
01:20:01,297 --> 01:20:05,008
Well, let's see where he's going
before we start objecting, Mr. Lodwick.

1261
01:20:05,093 --> 01:20:07,219
You may proceed, Mr. Biegler.

1262
01:20:07,303 --> 01:20:10,055
Well, did you see Mrs. Manion
in the bar that night?

1263
01:20:10,139 --> 01:20:12,099
She was there.

1264
01:20:12,100 --> 01:20:14,059
Did Barney Quill leave
the bar that night?

1265
01:20:14,143 --> 01:20:16,561
- Yes.
- Do you remember when he returned?

1266
01:20:16,646 --> 01:20:18,563
I think he came back around midnight.

1267
01:20:18,648 --> 01:20:22,109
From which entrance did he come?
Did he come from the lobby entrance...

1268
01:20:22,193 --> 01:20:24,945
or come from that...
that, uh, outside entrance?

1269
01:20:25,029 --> 01:20:27,155
- It was from the lobby.
- Mm-hmm.

1270
01:20:27,240 --> 01:20:28,699
And how did he appear
to you at that time?

1271
01:20:28,700 --> 01:20:30,158
How do you mean?

1272
01:20:30,243 --> 01:20:31,890
You understood the
prosecuting attorney very

1273
01:20:31,891 --> 01:20:33,537
well when he asked
you that question...

1274
01:20:33,621 --> 01:20:35,539
about Lieutenant Manion's appearance.

1275
01:20:35,623 --> 01:20:38,875
Oh, well, he was just
old Barney, like usual.

1276
01:20:38,960 --> 01:20:43,213
You mean he was just
good old sober, reliable...

1277
01:20:43,297 --> 01:20:45,195
gentle, salt-of-the-earth,
friend-to-man Barney?

1278
01:20:45,196 --> 01:20:47,092
Your Honor! Your Honor!

1279
01:20:47,176 --> 01:20:49,094
Your Honor, what kind
of a question is that?

1280
01:20:49,178 --> 01:20:51,263
I withdraw the question, Your Honor.

1281
01:20:53,099 --> 01:20:55,017
Mr. Paquette...

1282
01:20:55,101 --> 01:20:58,770
had Barney changed his clothes
since he left the bar?

1283
01:20:58,855 --> 01:21:00,063
I don't remember.

1284
01:21:00,148 --> 01:21:03,025
Might his clothing have been different
when he returned?

1285
01:21:03,109 --> 01:21:05,861
That is, might he have changed his clothes?

1286
01:21:05,945 --> 01:21:07,863
I couldn't say. I didn't notice.

1287
01:21:07,947 --> 01:21:10,115
Was Barney drinking that night?

1288
01:21:10,199 --> 01:21:14,619
Well, he... he always had a few shots
while he was talking to the customers.

1289
01:21:14,704 --> 01:21:18,081
- He was friendly.
- Oh, sure he was. Sure. Good old Barney.

1290
01:21:18,166 --> 01:21:21,918
Well, now, how many shots would you say
good old Barney usually had?

1291
01:21:22,003 --> 01:21:23,295
I don't know exactly.

1292
01:21:23,379 --> 01:21:26,214
Wasn't he, in fact,
pretty loaded that night, Mr. Paquette?

1293
01:21:26,299 --> 01:21:27,799
Objection, Your Honor.

1294
01:21:27,884 --> 01:21:31,553
Even if the deceased was dead drunk,
it's no defense to this charge.

1295
01:21:31,637 --> 01:21:34,931
Sustained.
I suggest you get off this, Mr. Biegler.

1296
01:21:35,016 --> 01:21:40,604
Mr. Paquette, what would you call a man
with an insatiable penchant for women?

1297
01:21:41,397 --> 01:21:43,523
- A what?
- A penchant.

1298
01:21:43,608 --> 01:21:46,151
A desire, uh, taste, passion.

1299
01:21:46,235 --> 01:21:49,404
Well, a ladies' man, I guess.

1300
01:21:49,489 --> 01:21:52,074
- Or maybe just a damn fool.
- [Spectators Laugh]

1301
01:21:53,201 --> 01:21:56,286
Just answer the questions, Mr. Paquette.

1302
01:21:56,370 --> 01:21:58,914
The attorneys will provide the wisecracks.

1303
01:21:58,998 --> 01:22:02,918
Well... [Laughs] What else would you call
a man like that, Mr. Paquette?

1304
01:22:03,002 --> 01:22:05,170
We can't see the drift of this, Your Honor.

1305
01:22:05,254 --> 01:22:07,339
You mean you do see, Mr. Lodwick.

1306
01:22:07,423 --> 01:22:09,258
You may answer.

1307
01:22:09,259 --> 01:22:11,093
Can you think of another
name, Mr. Paquette?

1308
01:22:11,803 --> 01:22:13,929
- Woman chaser.
- Try again.

1309
01:22:14,597 --> 01:22:17,641
- Masher?
- Oh, now, come now, Mr. Paquette.

1310
01:22:17,725 --> 01:22:20,811
Mashers went out with
whalebone corsets and hairnets.

1311
01:22:20,895 --> 01:22:23,188
- [Spectators Laugh]
- Did you ever hear the expression "wolf"?

1312
01:22:23,272 --> 01:22:25,982
Well, sure, I heard that.
It just slipped my mind.

1313
01:22:26,067 --> 01:22:28,151
It slipped your mind.
Well, naturally it would.

1314
01:22:28,236 --> 01:22:29,737
Clanking around in there with
all those rusty old mashers.

1315
01:22:29,738 --> 01:22:31,238
[Laughing]

1316
01:22:31,364 --> 01:22:35,367
Have you ever known a man who you could
call a wolf, Mr. Paquette? - I'm not sure.

1317
01:22:35,451 --> 01:22:38,120
- Was Barney Quill a wolf, Mr. Paquette?
- I couldn't say.

1318
01:22:38,204 --> 01:22:40,038
- Or wouldn't?
- Objection.

1319
01:22:40,123 --> 01:22:44,292
Sustained. The question was answered.
He said he couldn't say.

1320
01:22:45,169 --> 01:22:50,215
Mr. Paquette, when Barney returned
from wherever he had gone...

1321
01:22:50,299 --> 01:22:52,551
- did he relieve you at the bar?
- Yes.

1322
01:22:52,635 --> 01:22:54,178
And what did he say to
you when he relieved you?

1323
01:22:54,179 --> 01:22:55,720
Said, "I'll take over."

1324
01:22:55,805 --> 01:22:58,265
When you came out from behind the bar,
where did you go?

1325
01:22:59,433 --> 01:23:02,144
I went over to the table
where the Pedersons were sitting.

1326
01:23:02,228 --> 01:23:06,064
Now, you testified that you were by the
door when Lieutenant Manion came in.

1327
01:23:06,149 --> 01:23:09,234
Is that the reason you were by the door,
because the Pedersons' table was there?

1328
01:23:09,318 --> 01:23:10,819
- Yes.
- Uh-huh.

1329
01:23:10,903 --> 01:23:13,822
And how long was it before
Lieutenant Manion came in?

1330
01:23:14,657 --> 01:23:17,826
I don't know exactly.
Uh, maybe 30 minutes.

1331
01:23:17,910 --> 01:23:20,453
And you remained
at the Pedersons' table all that time.

1332
01:23:20,538 --> 01:23:24,958
- Yes, they're friends of mine.
- Is there also a window beside that table?

1333
01:23:25,042 --> 01:23:26,960
- I think so.
- You think so.

1334
01:23:27,044 --> 01:23:30,338
How long have you worked
at the Thunder Bay Inn, Mr. Paquette?

1335
01:23:30,423 --> 01:23:32,383
About six or seven years.

1336
01:23:32,384 --> 01:23:34,342
Well, now, does this
window beside the table...

1337
01:23:34,427 --> 01:23:37,929
does it suddenly vanish
and then reappear...

1338
01:23:38,014 --> 01:23:39,931
and come and go in a ghostly fashion?

1339
01:23:40,016 --> 01:23:41,933
No, sir. It's there all the time.

1340
01:23:42,018 --> 01:23:43,894
And while you were talking
to your friends there,

1341
01:23:43,895 --> 01:23:45,770
did you happen to look
out of the window?

1342
01:23:45,855 --> 01:23:48,023
- I might have.
- And when you looked out of the window...

1343
01:23:48,107 --> 01:23:50,066
were you looking for something special?

1344
01:23:50,151 --> 01:23:52,110
No. No, I wasn't looking for anything.

1345
01:23:52,195 --> 01:23:54,446
Didn't Barney Quill tell you
to go over to that window...

1346
01:23:54,530 --> 01:23:56,656
and watch out for Lieutenant Manion?

1347
01:23:57,241 --> 01:23:59,993
[Sighs]

1348
01:24:00,077 --> 01:24:02,662
Did he tell you to look out
for Lieutenant Manion?

1349
01:24:03,206 --> 01:24:05,207
He did not.

1350
01:24:06,334 --> 01:24:09,586
Mr. Paquette,
Barney was quite a marksman, wasn't he?

1351
01:24:09,670 --> 01:24:12,547
With guns. He'd won a lot of prizes
for shooting, hadn't he?

1352
01:24:12,632 --> 01:24:16,134
- Yes.
- Did he keep any guns behind the bar?

1353
01:24:22,183 --> 01:24:24,100
Well, he might have.

1354
01:24:24,185 --> 01:24:26,145
Isn't it a fact that there
are three concealed

1355
01:24:26,146 --> 01:24:28,104
pistol racks behind the
bar, Mr. Paquette?

1356
01:24:28,189 --> 01:24:31,983
Your Honor, the defendant's plea
is one of insanity, not self-defense.

1357
01:24:32,068 --> 01:24:35,987
I'm sure Mr. Biegler
hasn't forgotten that fact, Mr. Lodwick.

1358
01:24:36,072 --> 01:24:38,115
You may answer.

1359
01:24:38,116 --> 01:24:40,158
Are there concealed gun
racks behind the bar?

1360
01:24:40,243 --> 01:24:41,243
Yes.

1361
01:24:41,327 --> 01:24:44,537
And how many people
know about these gun racks?

1362
01:24:44,622 --> 01:24:46,186
I couldn't say.

1363
01:24:46,187 --> 01:24:47,749
But isn't it a fact that
Barney, every once in a while...

1364
01:24:47,833 --> 01:24:50,669
he'd take the guns out of these racks,
and twirling them on his fingers...

1365
01:24:50,753 --> 01:24:53,672
he'd demonstrate his skill to the patrons?

1366
01:24:53,756 --> 01:24:55,632
- Isn't it?
- I don't remember.

1367
01:24:55,716 --> 01:24:57,968
Oh, now, come on. Try and remember.

1368
01:24:58,052 --> 01:25:01,805
- Did you ever see him do that yourself?
- Once or twice he did.

1369
01:25:01,889 --> 01:25:05,392
- That's all, Mr. Paquette.
- [Lodwick] No further questions.

1370
01:25:05,476 --> 01:25:09,104
- [Judge Weaver] The witness may step down.
- Call George Lemon.

1371
01:25:14,944 --> 01:25:17,612
[Whispering]
Biegler's going off in all directions.

1372
01:25:17,697 --> 01:25:19,614
What's he getting at?

1373
01:25:20,783 --> 01:25:22,575
[Bailiff]
Raise your right hand, please.

1374
01:25:22,660 --> 01:25:24,578
I have a feeling he's
afraid of what we'll get at.

1375
01:25:24,579 --> 01:25:26,496
[Bailiff] ...shall
be the truth...

1376
01:25:26,580 --> 01:25:29,457
Mr. Biegler's putting up
a smoke screen for some reason.

1377
01:25:29,542 --> 01:25:31,793
- I do.
- Take a seat, please.

1378
01:25:33,796 --> 01:25:37,257
- Will you state your name, please?
- George Lemon.

1379
01:25:37,341 --> 01:25:39,217
What kind of work do you do, Mr. Lemon?

1380
01:25:39,302 --> 01:25:42,554
I'm caretaker of the tourist park
in Thunder Bay.

1381
01:25:42,638 --> 01:25:44,556
I see the place is clean and orderly.

1382
01:25:44,640 --> 01:25:47,142
I check people in,
check 'em out and lock the gate at night.

1383
01:25:47,226 --> 01:25:50,520
And what is your authority
for these duties?

1384
01:25:50,604 --> 01:25:55,900
I'm paid by Mastodon township, and I'm also
a deputy sheriff... just courtesy, sort of.

1385
01:25:56,569 --> 01:25:59,404
Did you see Lieutenant Manion
on the night of the 15th?

1386
01:25:59,488 --> 01:26:02,407
- The night Barney Quill was killed?
- Yes, sir.

1387
01:26:03,284 --> 01:26:05,285
Will you tell the court...

1388
01:26:05,369 --> 01:26:10,415
about how and-and when
you saw Lieutenant Manion?

1389
01:26:10,499 --> 01:26:13,543
About 1:00 a.m.,
a knock on my door waked me up.

1390
01:26:13,627 --> 01:26:16,254
I went to the door,
and Lieutenant Manion was standing there.

1391
01:26:16,339 --> 01:26:21,176
He said, "You better take me, Mr. Lemon,
because I just shot Barney Quill."

1392
01:26:21,260 --> 01:26:24,512
I told him to go back to his trailer
and that I would call the state police.

1393
01:26:24,597 --> 01:26:28,433
How did Lieutenant Manion appear to
you when he asked you to take him?

1394
01:26:28,517 --> 01:26:30,352
He said what he had to say
and did what I told him.

1395
01:26:30,353 --> 01:26:32,187
There wasn't any fuss.

1396
01:26:32,271 --> 01:26:35,357
Did he appear to you to be,
as far as you could tell...

1397
01:26:35,441 --> 01:26:38,109
in complete possession of his faculties?

1398
01:26:38,194 --> 01:26:40,362
As far as I could tell, yes, sir.

1399
01:26:42,031 --> 01:26:43,948
Take the witness.

1400
01:26:44,033 --> 01:26:47,452
Mr. Lemon,
did you go to the Manions' trailer?

1401
01:26:47,536 --> 01:26:48,578
Yes, sir.

1402
01:26:48,662 --> 01:26:50,580
Did you see Mrs. Manion at the trailer?

1403
01:26:50,664 --> 01:26:53,625
- Yes, sir.
- What was her appearance?

1404
01:26:54,210 --> 01:26:56,836
- She was a mess.
- [Spectators Laugh]

1405
01:26:56,921 --> 01:26:59,130
Objection.
No evidence has been introduced...

1406
01:26:59,215 --> 01:27:02,133
to make Mrs. Manion's appearance
relevant to this case.

1407
01:27:02,218 --> 01:27:05,762
Well, no evidence has been introduced to
make Barney Quill's appearance relevant...

1408
01:27:05,846 --> 01:27:07,931
but you didn't object to the question then.

1409
01:27:08,015 --> 01:27:11,768
Is that because you know that Barney Quill
bathed and changed and cooled off...

1410
01:27:11,852 --> 01:27:14,396
after he raped and beat hell
out of this poor woman?

1411
01:27:14,480 --> 01:27:17,857
Your Honor, everybody in this court
is being tried except Frederick Manion!

1412
01:27:17,983 --> 01:27:19,568
I must protest...

1413
01:27:19,569 --> 01:27:21,152
Now listen! This is a
cross-examination in a murder case!

1414
01:27:21,237 --> 01:27:24,239
It's not a high school debate!
What are you and Dancer trying to do?

1415
01:27:24,323 --> 01:27:26,658
Railroad this soldier into the clink?

1416
01:27:26,742 --> 01:27:29,411
Mr. Biegler,
you are an experienced attorney...

1417
01:27:29,495 --> 01:27:32,247
and you know better
than to make such an outburst.

1418
01:27:32,331 --> 01:27:35,208
I will not tolerate
intemperance of this sort.

1419
01:27:35,292 --> 01:27:38,545
If you once again try
the patience of this court...

1420
01:27:38,629 --> 01:27:41,047
I shall hold you in contempt.

1421
01:27:42,258 --> 01:27:43,675
Sorry.

1422
01:27:44,468 --> 01:27:46,344
Your Honor...

1423
01:27:46,429 --> 01:27:50,014
I apologize,
and it won't happen again.

1424
01:27:50,099 --> 01:27:54,811
The witness's answer will be stricken,
and the jury will disregard the answer.

1425
01:27:55,354 --> 01:27:59,107
- Now you may proceed, Mr. Biegler.
- Yes, sir.

1426
01:27:59,984 --> 01:28:01,943
Mr. Lemon...

1427
01:28:02,027 --> 01:28:05,280
on the night when Lieutenant Manion
awakened you and turned himself in...

1428
01:28:05,364 --> 01:28:07,282
had you been awakened before?

1429
01:28:07,366 --> 01:28:08,867
Had anything else
disturbed your slumbers?

1430
01:28:08,868 --> 01:28:10,368
No, sir.

1431
01:28:10,453 --> 01:28:14,873
- There were no soldiers singing?
- No, sir. Not in my park after 10:00.

1432
01:28:14,957 --> 01:28:17,042
There were no women screaming?

1433
01:28:17,043 --> 01:28:19,127
Well, those screams
were down by the gate.

1434
01:28:19,211 --> 01:28:20,837
Objection! Objection!

1435
01:28:20,921 --> 01:28:23,923
I see no reason for objecting yet,
Mr. Lodwick.

1436
01:28:24,008 --> 01:28:27,177
Tell us about those screams, Mr. Lemon.

1437
01:28:27,261 --> 01:28:28,992
I didn't hear 'em myself.

1438
01:28:28,993 --> 01:28:30,722
There were some tourists
from Ohio in the park...

1439
01:28:30,806 --> 01:28:33,141
and they heard 'em
and told me about it the next day.

1440
01:28:33,225 --> 01:28:37,270
- Now, Mr. Lodwick.
- This testimony is incompetent, hearsay...

1441
01:28:37,354 --> 01:28:40,315
irrelevant, immaterial, inconclusive...

1442
01:28:40,399 --> 01:28:42,817
- Yeah, well, that's too much for me.
- [Spectators Chuckle]

1443
01:28:42,902 --> 01:28:45,320
- The witness is yours, Mr. Lodwick.
- Huh?

1444
01:28:45,404 --> 01:28:48,156
Oh, uh, uh, no questions.

1445
01:28:48,782 --> 01:28:50,867
The witness may step down.

1446
01:28:50,951 --> 01:28:53,661
- Call your next witness.
- Um...

1447
01:28:54,830 --> 01:28:57,081
Detective Sergeant James Durgo.

1448
01:28:58,918 --> 01:29:01,169
- Hi, Polly.
- [Whispering] Hi, Jim. Come here.

1449
01:29:03,214 --> 01:29:06,007
As soon as we break,
you'd better phone that army psychiatrist.

1450
01:29:06,091 --> 01:29:08,927
- Tell him to be here day after tomorrow.
- Will do.

1451
01:29:09,011 --> 01:29:12,263
Will you please tell me
where Parnell has gone?

1452
01:29:12,348 --> 01:29:14,265
Won't do.

1453
01:29:14,350 --> 01:29:15,975
You're fired.

1454
01:29:17,019 --> 01:29:19,395
You can't fire me till you pay me.

1455
01:29:19,480 --> 01:29:21,773
[Durgo] Detective Sergeant
James Durgo, state police.

1456
01:29:21,857 --> 01:29:24,776
[Lodwick] Were you called to Thunder Bay
by Deputy Sheriff Lemon of Thunder Bay...

1457
01:29:24,860 --> 01:29:27,195
on the night that Barney Quill
was shot and killed?

1458
01:29:27,279 --> 01:29:31,282
Yes, sir, I was. My companion officer and I
were the first to be called in on the case.

1459
01:29:31,367 --> 01:29:34,953
Sergeant Durgo, when you arrived
at the Manion trailer, who was there?

1460
01:29:35,037 --> 01:29:37,372
Lieutenant Manion and his wife were there.

1461
01:29:37,456 --> 01:29:39,707
What did Lieutenant Manion say to you?

1462
01:29:40,793 --> 01:29:44,128
He said that his wife
had had some trouble with Barney Quill...

1463
01:29:44,213 --> 01:29:46,923
that he had gone to the tavern
and shot Quill.

1464
01:29:47,007 --> 01:29:50,343
He asked us whether Quill was dead or not.
We told him he was.

1465
01:29:50,427 --> 01:29:53,429
How did Lieutenant Manion
take this information?

1466
01:29:53,514 --> 01:29:57,183
- He didn't seem surprised.
- What did you do then, Sergeant Durgo?

1467
01:29:57,268 --> 01:29:59,185
I asked for the gun he'd used.

1468
01:29:59,270 --> 01:30:01,334
Did you take Lieutenant
Manion to the county

1469
01:30:01,335 --> 01:30:03,398
jail here in Iron City
on that same night?

1470
01:30:03,482 --> 01:30:06,276
Yes, sir. We drove the lieutenant
down with his wife.

1471
01:30:06,360 --> 01:30:11,322
On the drive to Iron City, did the
lieutenant talk further about the shooting?

1472
01:30:11,407 --> 01:30:15,159
He remarked that if he had the whole thing
to do over again, he'd still do it.

1473
01:30:15,244 --> 01:30:18,997
[Lodwick] During all this...
at the trailer, the drive to Iron City...

1474
01:30:19,081 --> 01:30:20,957
how did Lieutenant Manion appear to you?

1475
01:30:22,209 --> 01:30:25,587
He was very quiet most of the time.
Seemed clearheaded.

1476
01:30:25,671 --> 01:30:27,819
As far as you could tell,
would you say that he

1477
01:30:27,820 --> 01:30:29,966
was in complete possession
of his faculties?

1478
01:30:30,050 --> 01:30:32,760
- Seemed so to me.
- Your witness.

1479
01:30:32,845 --> 01:30:35,243
Sergeant Durgo, you
testified that Lieutenant

1480
01:30:35,244 --> 01:30:37,640
Manion told you that he
shot Barney Quill...

1481
01:30:37,725 --> 01:30:42,061
after he learned that his wife
had had some trouble with Quill.

1482
01:30:42,146 --> 01:30:45,607
Now, were these the words
Lieutenant Manion used? "Some trouble"?

1483
01:30:45,691 --> 01:30:48,026
No, sir. Those were my words, not his.

1484
01:30:48,110 --> 01:30:51,029
And was it your notion
to come here and use your own words?

1485
01:30:51,113 --> 01:30:53,031
No, sir. It was not.

1486
01:30:53,115 --> 01:30:55,742
And was the suggestion to
call it "some trouble"

1487
01:30:55,743 --> 01:30:58,369
made by somebody here
in this courtroom?

1488
01:31:00,080 --> 01:31:02,540
Yes, sir, it was.

1489
01:31:02,625 --> 01:31:04,876
All right, Sergeant.
Now, would you tell the court...

1490
01:31:04,960 --> 01:31:07,337
what words Lieutenant
Manion actually used...

1491
01:31:07,421 --> 01:31:09,631
to describe the trouble his wife had had?

1492
01:31:09,715 --> 01:31:12,383
Objection, Your Honor.
We've been over this before.

1493
01:31:12,468 --> 01:31:15,553
This information would not be relevant
to any issues before the court.

1494
01:31:15,638 --> 01:31:17,555
This statement concerning some trouble...

1495
01:31:17,640 --> 01:31:21,351
was brought out during
the direct examination of Sergeant Durgo.

1496
01:31:21,435 --> 01:31:24,083
Up to now you've
adroitly restricted all

1497
01:31:24,084 --> 01:31:26,731
testimony as far as Laura
Manion's concerned.

1498
01:31:26,815 --> 01:31:30,318
All right. The cat's out of the bag.
It's fair game for me to chase it.

1499
01:31:30,402 --> 01:31:33,488
This is a sore point, Mr. Biegler,
and it's getting sorer.

1500
01:31:33,572 --> 01:31:35,490
I'd like to hear from the prosecution.

1501
01:31:35,574 --> 01:31:38,055
The burden is on the
defense to prove temporary

1502
01:31:38,056 --> 01:31:40,536
insanity at the time
of the shooting.

1503
01:31:40,621 --> 01:31:44,791
Now, if the reason for the alleged insanity
is important to this case...

1504
01:31:44,875 --> 01:31:47,418
then that is a matter
for a competent witness...

1505
01:31:47,503 --> 01:31:50,296
an expert on the subject of the human mind.

1506
01:31:51,340 --> 01:31:53,841
What the defense is trying to do...

1507
01:31:53,926 --> 01:31:56,761
is introduce some sensational material...

1508
01:31:56,845 --> 01:31:59,514
for the purposes of
obscuring the real issues.

1509
01:32:00,974 --> 01:32:05,603
Your Honor, how can the jury accurately
estimate the testimony being given here...

1510
01:32:05,688 --> 01:32:09,148
unless they first know
the reason behind this whole trial...

1511
01:32:09,233 --> 01:32:12,110
why Lieutenant Manion shot Barney Quill.

1512
01:32:12,194 --> 01:32:16,280
Now, the prosecution would like to separate
the motive from the act.

1513
01:32:16,365 --> 01:32:21,285
Well, that's like trying to take the core
from an apple without breaking the skin.

1514
01:32:21,370 --> 01:32:26,290
The core of our defense is that the
defendant's temporary insanity...

1515
01:32:26,375 --> 01:32:29,669
was triggered by
this so-called trouble with Quill.

1516
01:32:29,753 --> 01:32:31,879
And I beg the court...

1517
01:32:31,964 --> 01:32:36,467
I beg the court
to let me cut into the apple.

1518
01:32:38,387 --> 01:32:40,763
Our objection still stands, Your Honor.

1519
01:32:55,279 --> 01:32:57,155
Objection overruled.

1520
01:32:57,239 --> 01:32:59,240
[Spectators Murmuring]

1521
01:33:03,704 --> 01:33:07,331
Sergeant Durgo, tell the court...

1522
01:33:07,416 --> 01:33:11,461
how Lieutenant Manion described
the trouble his wife had with Barney Quill.

1523
01:33:11,545 --> 01:33:14,964
He told us that Quill had raped his wife.

1524
01:33:15,048 --> 01:33:19,469
Now, can you recall generally what
Lieutenant Manion told you about this rape?

1525
01:33:20,053 --> 01:33:24,223
Yes, sir. He said he'd been asleep
since right after dinner.

1526
01:33:24,308 --> 01:33:28,394
That he was waked up by some noise.
Screams, he thought.

1527
01:33:28,479 --> 01:33:32,064
That he got up, opened the trailer door
and went outside.

1528
01:33:32,608 --> 01:33:35,693
His wife came running
out of the dark and fell into his arms.

1529
01:33:35,778 --> 01:33:39,030
You saw his wife in the trailer.
How'd she look?

1530
01:33:39,114 --> 01:33:42,200
She was a little hysterical.
She'd been pretty badly beaten up.

1531
01:33:42,284 --> 01:33:45,077
She had big black bruises
over her face and her arms.

1532
01:33:45,162 --> 01:33:47,080
Did Mrs. Manion tell you
about this rape and beating?

1533
01:33:47,081 --> 01:33:48,998
She did.

1534
01:33:49,124 --> 01:33:50,896
And did she take you to the
place where it had happened?

1535
01:33:50,897 --> 01:33:52,668
Yes, sir. The next morning.

1536
01:33:52,753 --> 01:33:54,484
And did you find anything there?

1537
01:33:54,485 --> 01:33:56,214
Any sort of evidence
pertaining to the story...

1538
01:33:56,298 --> 01:33:58,716
that Mrs. Manion had told you?

1539
01:33:58,801 --> 01:34:03,554
On the lane in the woods we found
some tire tracks and some dog tracks...

1540
01:34:03,639 --> 01:34:07,350
and a leather case with some
horn-rimmed glasses inside.

1541
01:34:08,310 --> 01:34:10,478
We also looked for...

1542
01:34:10,562 --> 01:34:14,190
a certain undergarment of Mrs. Manion's,
but we didn't find it.

1543
01:34:14,274 --> 01:34:17,068
Will the attorneys for both sides
approach the bench, please?

1544
01:34:21,114 --> 01:34:25,159
[Whispering] Mr. Biegler,
you finally got your rape into the case...

1545
01:34:25,244 --> 01:34:29,080
and I think all the details
should now be made clear to the jury.

1546
01:34:29,164 --> 01:34:33,084
- Do you agree, Mr. Lodwick?
- Absolutely.

1547
01:34:33,168 --> 01:34:36,546
What exactly was
the undergarment just referred to?

1548
01:34:36,630 --> 01:34:38,339
Panties, Your Honor.

1549
01:34:38,423 --> 01:34:40,279
Do you expect this
subject to come up again?

1550
01:34:40,280 --> 01:34:42,134
Yes, sir.

1551
01:34:42,219 --> 01:34:46,556
There's a certain light connotation
attached to the word "panties."

1552
01:34:46,640 --> 01:34:48,683
Can we find another name for them?

1553
01:34:48,767 --> 01:34:50,748
I never heard my wife
call 'em anything else.

1554
01:34:50,749 --> 01:34:52,728
Mr. Biegler?

1555
01:34:52,813 --> 01:34:57,608
- I'm a bachelor, Your Honor.
- That's a great help. Mr. Dancer?

1556
01:34:57,693 --> 01:35:02,530
When I was overseas during the war,
Your Honor, I... I learned a French word.

1557
01:35:02,614 --> 01:35:04,804
I'm afraid that it might
be slightly suggestive.

1558
01:35:04,805 --> 01:35:06,993
Most French words are.

1559
01:35:07,077 --> 01:35:10,121
All right, gentlemen. Back to your places.

1560
01:35:10,831 --> 01:35:15,501
For the benefit of the jury,
but more especially for the spectators...

1561
01:35:15,586 --> 01:35:19,380
the undergarment referred to
in the testimony was, to be exact...

1562
01:35:19,464 --> 01:35:21,382
Mrs. Manion's panties.

1563
01:35:21,466 --> 01:35:24,635
[Spectators Laughing]

1564
01:35:24,720 --> 01:35:29,307
I wanted you to get your snickering
over and done with.

1565
01:35:29,391 --> 01:35:33,644
This pair of panties will be mentioned
again in the course of this trial...

1566
01:35:33,729 --> 01:35:36,230
and when it happens,
there will not be one laugh...

1567
01:35:36,315 --> 01:35:38,232
one snicker, one giggle...

1568
01:35:38,317 --> 01:35:41,444
or even one smirk in my courtroom.

1569
01:35:41,528 --> 01:35:45,156
There isn't anything comic
about a pair of panties...

1570
01:35:45,240 --> 01:35:48,659
which figure in the violent death
of one man...

1571
01:35:48,744 --> 01:35:52,330
and the possible incarceration of another.

1572
01:35:52,873 --> 01:35:54,916
Proceed, Mr. Biegler.

1573
01:35:55,000 --> 01:35:56,334
Did you give Mrs. Manion
a lie detector test?

1574
01:35:56,335 --> 01:35:57,668
Objection.

1575
01:35:57,753 --> 01:36:00,546
A polygraph test is inadmissible evidence
in our courts.

1576
01:36:00,631 --> 01:36:04,050
I only asked if he gave the test.
I didn't ask the results.

1577
01:36:04,134 --> 01:36:06,135
[Judge Weaver]
He may answer that.

1578
01:36:06,219 --> 01:36:09,221
I gave her a lie detector
test at her request.

1579
01:36:09,306 --> 01:36:13,601
After all this investigation, did
you believe Mrs. Manion? - I did.

1580
01:36:13,685 --> 01:36:17,063
- Even after the lie detector test?
- Your Honor, I object to that question!

1581
01:36:17,147 --> 01:36:19,190
It constitutes flagrant,
sneaking subterfuge

1582
01:36:19,191 --> 01:36:21,233
on the part of the
defense counsel.

1583
01:36:21,318 --> 01:36:25,029
Objection sustained.
Ladies and gentlemen of the jury...

1584
01:36:25,113 --> 01:36:28,991
a polygraph or lie detector test
is not admissible in evidence...

1585
01:36:29,076 --> 01:36:31,452
because no one has ever been quite sure...

1586
01:36:31,536 --> 01:36:35,498
that some people couldn't lie
to a lie detector and get away with it.

1587
01:36:35,582 --> 01:36:37,626
Go ahead, Mr. Biegler.

1588
01:36:37,627 --> 01:36:39,669
In any case, Sergeant
Durgo, you, yourself...

1589
01:36:39,753 --> 01:36:44,090
in your own heart and mind are quite
convinced of Mrs. Manion's honesty.

1590
01:36:44,174 --> 01:36:46,592
- Yes, sir.
- That's all.

1591
01:36:48,095 --> 01:36:50,096
- Just a moment.
- [Whispering]

1592
01:36:50,180 --> 01:36:51,681
Yes, of course.

1593
01:36:53,350 --> 01:36:55,790
Sergeant Durgo, did you
look for the panties

1594
01:36:55,791 --> 01:36:58,229
elsewhere than the
lane in the woods?

1595
01:36:58,313 --> 01:37:01,148
We looked in Barney Quill's car
and his room in the hotel.

1596
01:37:01,233 --> 01:37:03,192
We didn't find the panties.

1597
01:37:03,276 --> 01:37:06,696
Do you know why Mrs. Manion
requested a lie detector test?

1598
01:37:06,780 --> 01:37:08,864
- I know what she said.
- What was that?

1599
01:37:08,949 --> 01:37:10,908
She said she wanted everybody
to believe her story...

1600
01:37:10,993 --> 01:37:12,910
because she knew it would
help her husband.

1601
01:37:12,995 --> 01:37:14,578
Was that the only reason she gave?

1602
01:37:14,663 --> 01:37:16,748
She said she'd already
sworn to her husband.

1603
01:37:16,749 --> 01:37:18,833
She wanted everybody
else to believe it too.

1604
01:37:18,917 --> 01:37:21,085
One moment, please, Your Honor.

1605
01:37:24,715 --> 01:37:27,341
Ask him in what manner she swore.

1606
01:37:27,426 --> 01:37:30,678
Did Mrs. Manion say how
she had sworn to her husband?

1607
01:37:30,762 --> 01:37:34,390
Yes, sir. She said she'd sworn on a rosary.

1608
01:37:35,100 --> 01:37:39,186
Sergeant, this lane in the woods...
What's it used for? Where does it go?

1609
01:37:39,730 --> 01:37:42,857
Used to be a logging road.
Doesn't go anyplace. Just stops.

1610
01:37:42,941 --> 01:37:44,859
Who uses it now?

1611
01:37:44,943 --> 01:37:46,861
