was your father.

1833
01:50:02,180 --> 01:50:05,015
- You didn't come here just to apologize.
- No. No.

1834
01:50:05,099 --> 01:50:07,017
But the apology was part of it.

1835
01:50:07,101 --> 01:50:11,104
To tell the truth, I sort of hoped
maybe it would thaw you out a bit.

1836
01:50:11,814 --> 01:50:15,650
All I want you to do is just listen to me.
Just for a few minutes.

1837
01:50:16,235 --> 01:50:20,906
Now, I need some strong evidence to back
up Laura Manion's story about the rape.

1838
01:50:20,990 --> 01:50:24,409
The prosecution's gonna
attack that story pretty hard.

1839
01:50:24,494 --> 01:50:27,120
And if... if the jury thinks she's lying...

1840
01:50:27,205 --> 01:50:30,290
well, that could turn the decision
against Manion, you see.

1841
01:50:30,374 --> 01:50:35,045
Well, isn't she lying? Barney didn't do
what she said he did. He couldn't have.

1842
01:50:35,671 --> 01:50:39,299
- What did you know about your father?
- All I needed to know.

1843
01:50:39,383 --> 01:50:43,386
He took care of me and of my mother
for as long as she lived.

1844
01:50:43,471 --> 01:50:46,723
He was always there when I needed him.

1845
01:50:46,808 --> 01:50:49,059
That's what I know
about my father, Mr. Biegler.

1846
01:50:49,143 --> 01:50:51,728
Will that back up Laura Manion's story?

1847
01:50:51,813 --> 01:50:54,898
Miss Pilant, I don't want to get at you.
I don't want to hurt you.

1848
01:50:54,982 --> 01:50:57,192
I appreciate your affection
for your father...

1849
01:50:57,276 --> 01:51:00,320
but... but as a lawyer I've had to learn...

1850
01:51:00,404 --> 01:51:03,156
that people aren't just good or just bad.

1851
01:51:03,241 --> 01:51:05,408
But people are many things.

1852
01:51:05,493 --> 01:51:08,703
And I kind of have a feeling
that Barney Quill was many things.

1853
01:51:08,788 --> 01:51:12,082
- I don't want to hear that.
- No, no, please. Please now, hear me out.

1854
01:51:12,166 --> 01:51:16,086
I believe that Barney told
Al Paquette what happened that night...

1855
01:51:16,170 --> 01:51:19,422
and he told him to go to this window
and wait for Manion.

1856
01:51:19,507 --> 01:51:24,177
Barney stayed behind the bar
next to a gun rack, just waiting.

1857
01:51:24,262 --> 01:51:27,556
Manion came in and fired
the minute he got inside that door...

1858
01:51:27,640 --> 01:51:30,433
and the first shot went
right through Barney's heart.

1859
01:51:30,518 --> 01:51:32,853
Now, here's what I want you to do.

1860
01:51:32,937 --> 01:51:37,399
I want you to try to persuade Al to come
to the court as a defense witness...

1861
01:51:37,483 --> 01:51:40,610
and tell the court exactly
what Barney told him that night.

1862
01:51:40,695 --> 01:51:43,613
That he'd raped and assaulted Mrs. Manion.

1863
01:51:43,698 --> 01:51:46,283
Al wouldn't conceal a thing like that.

1864
01:51:46,367 --> 01:51:48,410
Why wouldn't he tell it, if it were true?

1865
01:51:48,494 --> 01:51:51,746
I don't know. I don't know.
But I know this.

1866
01:51:51,831 --> 01:51:55,292
Everybody loves something or someone.

1867
01:51:55,376 --> 01:51:57,335
Me, I love fishing...

1868
01:51:57,420 --> 01:51:59,629
and an old guy by the name of Parnell.

1869
01:51:59,714 --> 01:52:03,258
Manion loves his freedom.
He'd like to have a little more of it.

1870
01:52:03,342 --> 01:52:06,970
Barney loved you. Maybe so does Al.

1871
01:52:07,638 --> 01:52:10,557
I wouldn't blame him.
But he doesn't want to hurt you.

1872
01:52:10,641 --> 01:52:13,435
He doesn't want you to know
the truth about Barney...

1873
01:52:13,519 --> 01:52:15,478
that he could be dangerous and brutal.

1874
01:52:15,563 --> 01:52:17,669
Now, if you'd just ask AI.

1875
01:52:17,670 --> 01:52:19,774
If you could just ask
him right straight out.

1876
01:52:20,484 --> 01:52:21,776
AI?

1877
01:52:30,119 --> 01:52:33,914
Al, Mr. Biegler knows
that Barney was my father.

1878
01:52:35,249 --> 01:52:38,335
He thinks you know something
about the night my father was killed...

1879
01:52:38,419 --> 01:52:40,837
something you won't tell.

1880
01:52:40,922 --> 01:52:43,548
Lawyer, I told you once,
and I'll tell you again.

1881
01:52:43,633 --> 01:52:46,426
- No questions, no answers.
- Wait, Al.

1882
01:52:49,096 --> 01:52:51,514
Did my father rape Mrs. Manion?

1883
01:52:52,600 --> 01:52:54,517
Barney wouldn't hurt a woman.

1884
01:52:56,395 --> 01:52:59,773
Is there any reason you wouldn't tell me
the truth about that, Al?

1885
01:53:00,942 --> 01:53:02,901
What reason?

1886
01:53:09,116 --> 01:53:11,660
- Anything else, Mr. Biegler?
- No.

1887
01:53:11,744 --> 01:53:14,621
I'm gonna leave a pass
for you and Al at the trial.

1888
01:53:14,705 --> 01:53:17,791
You might like to watch
Lieutenant Manion get convicted.

1889
01:53:18,376 --> 01:53:20,460
You gonna spread it around
about Mary being Barney's kid?

1890
01:53:20,544 --> 01:53:22,796
No, I'm not gonna spread it around, Al.

1891
01:53:22,880 --> 01:53:26,132
Thank you for the beer.
Good night, Miss Pilant.

1892
01:53:30,221 --> 01:53:32,973
All right,
now let's get at this rosary thing.

1893
01:53:33,057 --> 01:53:36,309
Now, it's been testified
that your wife swore to you on a rosary...

1894
01:53:36,394 --> 01:53:39,145
that she'd been raped by Barney Quill.

1895
01:53:39,230 --> 01:53:41,690
Did you ask your wife to swear on a rosary?

1896
01:53:42,733 --> 01:53:45,902
My wife was hysterical.
She wasn't making much sense.

1897
01:53:45,987 --> 01:53:49,155
I thought if I asked her
to take an oath on a rosary...

1898
01:53:49,240 --> 01:53:51,992
it might serve to calm her,
make her think more clearly.

1899
01:53:52,076 --> 01:53:53,994
Did the rosary help?

1900
01:53:54,078 --> 01:53:56,496
She was able to tell me
in detail what had happened.

1901
01:53:56,580 --> 01:53:58,498
All right. Go on from there now.

1902
01:53:58,582 --> 01:54:00,834
What did you do then, Lieutenant?

1903
01:54:00,918 --> 01:54:04,504
Well, I... I had her lie on the bed...

1904
01:54:04,588 --> 01:54:08,508
and I got some cold cloths for her head.

1905
01:54:08,592 --> 01:54:12,512
And, uh... Oh, yes.
I gave her a drink of brandy.

1906
01:54:14,765 --> 01:54:16,683
After a while she became calm...

1907
01:54:16,767 --> 01:54:19,352
seemed to go to sleep.

1908
01:54:19,437 --> 01:54:24,024
Then I went to the closet,
I got my gun, and I loaded it.

1909
01:54:24,108 --> 01:54:27,986
- Was it in your mind to kill Barney Quill?
- No.

1910
01:54:28,070 --> 01:54:31,448
Well, then why did you go to the closet
and get your gun and load it?

1911
01:54:31,532 --> 01:54:33,284
Well, I-I-I knew I had
to go to Quill's place.

1912
01:54:33,285 --> 01:54:35,035
I thought I might need it.

1913
01:54:35,119 --> 01:54:36,870
Why?

1914
01:54:36,954 --> 01:54:39,706
I knew Mr. Quill kept guns behind the bar.

1915
01:54:39,790 --> 01:54:41,708
I was afraid he might shoot me.

1916
01:54:41,792 --> 01:54:45,170
Might shoot you if you did what?
What were you gonna do?

1917
01:54:46,213 --> 01:54:48,631
I'm not sure.

1918
01:54:48,716 --> 01:54:51,551
I remember having some idea...

1919
01:54:51,635 --> 01:54:53,887
of finding him...

1920
01:54:53,971 --> 01:54:56,890
and holding him while I called the police.

1921
01:54:56,974 --> 01:54:58,975
Well, that Mr... what's his name...

1922
01:54:59,060 --> 01:55:01,936
Mr. Lemon, right at the tourist court
there, he was a deputy sheriff.

1923
01:55:02,021 --> 01:55:03,938
Why didn't you get him to go with you?

1924
01:55:04,774 --> 01:55:08,902
Maybe because he always seemed to be
just the old caretaker of the park.

1925
01:55:10,321 --> 01:55:14,032
Maybe because I wasn't
thinking about anything too clearly...

1926
01:55:14,116 --> 01:55:16,076
except finding Barney Quill.

1927
01:55:16,160 --> 01:55:19,829
Why didn't you go to a telephone, call the
state police before you went to the bar?

1928
01:55:19,914 --> 01:55:22,082
I don't know.

1929
01:55:22,166 --> 01:55:24,417
I was in sort of a daze.

1930
01:55:25,503 --> 01:55:28,463
It was a horrible thing
to see what had been done to my wife.

1931
01:55:28,547 --> 01:55:30,757
Now, you say you were in a sort of a daze.

1932
01:55:30,841 --> 01:55:34,260
When you got to the bar,
did you see that the bar was crowded?

1933
01:55:35,012 --> 01:55:36,930
I...

1934
01:55:37,014 --> 01:55:39,557
I didn't see anyone at the bar...

1935
01:55:40,351 --> 01:55:42,435
except Barney Quill.

1936
01:55:42,520 --> 01:55:44,437
He was the only person I saw.

1937
01:55:44,522 --> 01:55:46,523
What was he doing?

1938
01:55:47,191 --> 01:55:50,985
I think he was just
standing there behind the bar.

1939
01:55:51,070 --> 01:55:55,073
Well, now, did he make
a threatening move to get a gun?

1940
01:55:55,157 --> 01:55:56,699
I don't know.

1941
01:55:57,284 --> 01:55:58,910
He may have. I don't know.

1942
01:55:58,994 --> 01:56:01,454
All right.
Now, you say you went there to find him...

1943
01:56:01,539 --> 01:56:03,623
to hold him for the police.

1944
01:56:03,707 --> 01:56:05,625
Why did you shoot him?

1945
01:56:07,711 --> 01:56:10,046
I don't remember shooting him.

1946
01:56:10,631 --> 01:56:12,465
Now, when you left the bar...

1947
01:56:12,550 --> 01:56:15,301
do you remember Alphonse Paquette
coming up to you and stopping you...

1948
01:56:15,386 --> 01:56:17,470
and saying,
"You'd better not run away from this"...

1949
01:56:17,555 --> 01:56:21,224
and your reply,
"Do you want some too, buster?"

1950
01:56:21,308 --> 01:56:22,809
Remember that?

1951
01:56:23,519 --> 01:56:25,812
I-I seem to have a vague recollection...

1952
01:56:25,896 --> 01:56:27,814
of somebody speaking to me...

1953
01:56:29,400 --> 01:56:32,902
but I don't remember what I said
or what was said to me.

1954
01:56:32,987 --> 01:56:35,905
When did you realize
that you had shot Quill?

1955
01:56:38,576 --> 01:56:40,994
I was... I was getting a drink of water.

1956
01:56:41,078 --> 01:56:43,997
I remember my throat was so dry it hurt.

1957
01:56:45,583 --> 01:56:48,001
And when I put the glass down,
I saw the gun...

1958
01:56:48,085 --> 01:56:50,503
on the kitchen sink beside the tap.

1959
01:56:51,589 --> 01:56:53,590
I noticed the gun was empty.

1960
01:56:54,675 --> 01:56:57,343
Now I'd like you to show
the court and jury...

1961
01:56:57,428 --> 01:56:59,012
just, uh...

1962
01:56:59,972 --> 01:57:02,515
just how you knew this gun was empty.

1963
01:57:02,600 --> 01:57:05,018
Well, this gadget here...

1964
01:57:05,102 --> 01:57:08,396
when it sticks up,
you know the last round's been fired.

1965
01:57:09,106 --> 01:57:12,192
Lieutenant Manion,
on the night of the shooting...

1966
01:57:12,276 --> 01:57:14,194
did you love your wife?

1967
01:57:14,278 --> 01:57:17,655
- Yes, sir.
- Do you still love her?

1968
01:57:21,118 --> 01:57:22,952
Very much.

1969
01:57:23,704 --> 01:57:25,747
The witness is yours, Mr. Dancer.

1970
01:57:25,831 --> 01:57:27,707
Lieutenant Manion...

1971
01:57:28,959 --> 01:57:31,211
how many men have you killed?

1972
01:57:31,295 --> 01:57:33,213
Now wait a minute.

1973
01:57:33,881 --> 01:57:35,549
Your Honor, a man's
war record...

1974
01:57:35,550 --> 01:57:37,217
in Lieutenant Manion's
case, a great record...

1975
01:57:37,301 --> 01:57:39,219
certainly shouldn't be used against him.

1976
01:57:39,303 --> 01:57:42,222
Your Honor, I'm as patriotic
as the next man...

1977
01:57:42,306 --> 01:57:47,060
but the simple truth is, war can
condition a man to killing other men.

1978
01:57:47,144 --> 01:57:49,896
I simply want to determine
how conditioned the lieutenant may be...

1979
01:57:49,980 --> 01:57:53,483
to the use of firearms
on other human beings.

1980
01:57:53,567 --> 01:57:55,485
I don't quite like the
question, Mr. Biegler...

1981
01:57:55,569 --> 01:57:57,570
but I don't see how I can exclude it.

1982
01:57:57,655 --> 01:57:59,572
Let him answer.

1983
01:57:59,657 --> 01:58:02,909
I know I killed
at least four men in Korea...

1984
01:58:02,993 --> 01:58:04,911
three with a hand grenade...

1985
01:58:04,995 --> 01:58:07,247
and one with my service automatic.

1986
01:58:07,331 --> 01:58:11,084
I may have killed others.
A soldier doesn't always know.

1987
01:58:11,168 --> 01:58:13,419
Now, Lieutenant, in these
acts of killing...

1988
01:58:13,504 --> 01:58:15,421
did you ever have a lapse of memory...

1989
01:58:15,506 --> 01:58:16,799
such as you had when
you killed Barney Quill?

1990
01:58:16,800 --> 01:58:18,091
No, sir.

1991
01:58:18,175 --> 01:58:20,593
Did you ever have
a lapse of memory during battle?

1992
01:58:20,678 --> 01:58:21,887
No, sir.

1993
01:58:21,888 --> 01:58:23,096
Were you ever submitted
to a constant barrage...

1994
01:58:23,180 --> 01:58:25,098
constantly in a sweat for many hours...

1995
01:58:25,182 --> 01:58:27,267
- constantly under attack, or attacking?
- Many times.

1996
01:58:27,351 --> 01:58:29,269
Were you ever treated for shell shock,
battle fatigue...

1997
01:58:29,353 --> 01:58:31,437
- or any war neurosis or psychosis?
- No, sir.

1998
01:58:31,522 --> 01:58:35,775
Did you ever experience
any unusual mental state during the war?

1999
01:58:35,859 --> 01:58:37,235
Well, I do remember
having one great urge.

2000
01:58:37,236 --> 01:58:38,611
What was that?

2001
01:58:38,696 --> 01:58:42,115
- To get the hell out and go home.
- [Spectators Laughing]

2002
01:58:42,199 --> 01:58:46,452
You would do well to consider the
seriousness of the situation you are in.

2003
01:58:46,537 --> 01:58:49,622
- I'm sorry, Your Honor.
- I sympathize with the lieutenant.

2004
01:58:49,707 --> 01:58:53,626
I expect he has the same feeling
about getting out of jail.

2005
01:58:53,711 --> 01:58:56,796
But the main point here, Lieutenant, is
that at no time during your war service...

2006
01:58:56,880 --> 01:58:58,798
did you have a record
of mental disturbance.

2007
01:58:58,882 --> 01:59:00,967
You were always in complete possession
of your faculties.

2008
01:59:01,051 --> 01:59:03,636
Yes, sir, that's right.

2009
01:59:03,721 --> 01:59:06,306
- No more questions.
- [Biegler] No redirect, Your Honor.

2010
01:59:06,390 --> 01:59:08,975
[Judge Weaver]
Step down, please. Call your next witness.

2011
01:59:09,059 --> 01:59:11,644
We call Laura Manion to the stand.

2012
01:59:23,741 --> 01:59:26,659
- Up these stairs and to the right.
- Thank you.

2013
01:59:33,167 --> 01:59:35,626
Now, how long after you told your husband
what had happened...

2014
01:59:35,711 --> 01:59:37,962
did he leave the trailer?

2015
01:59:38,047 --> 01:59:40,131
I don't know exactly.

2016
01:59:40,215 --> 01:59:42,133
Everything was kind of fuzzy. I...

2017
01:59:42,217 --> 01:59:44,635
I was faint, and I lay down on the bed.

2018
01:59:44,720 --> 01:59:46,804
He sat beside me.

2019
01:59:46,889 --> 01:59:49,974
I vaguely remember
his getting up and going out.

2020
01:59:50,059 --> 01:59:52,643
I remember wondering
if he was going for a doctor.

2021
01:59:52,728 --> 01:59:54,896
And then he came back in.

2022
01:59:54,980 --> 01:59:57,482
It seemed like just a few seconds,
but it must have been longer.

2023
01:59:57,566 --> 01:59:59,776
I must have gone to sleep.

2024
02:00:00,527 --> 02:00:03,154
When he came back in,
he sat on the bed...

2025
02:00:03,238 --> 02:00:05,448
and he had a gun in his hand.

2026
02:00:05,532 --> 02:00:08,618
And I said, "What are you going to do?"

2027
02:00:08,702 --> 02:00:11,662
And he said, "I think I've already done it.

2028
02:00:11,747 --> 02:00:13,831
I think I've killed Barney Quill."

2029
02:00:13,916 --> 02:00:17,335
Are you sure he didn't say
"I've killed Barney Quill"?

2030
02:00:17,419 --> 02:00:20,004
No, I... I remember distinctly.

2031
02:00:20,089 --> 02:00:22,006
"I think I've killed Barney Quill."

2032
02:00:22,091 --> 02:00:24,175
Then what did you do?

2033
02:00:24,259 --> 02:00:28,679
I put my arms around him
and began to cry and...

2034
02:00:28,764 --> 02:00:31,516
and I said,
"You'd better go to Mr. Lemon."

2035
02:00:31,600 --> 02:00:33,518
And my husband said, "I forgot about that."

2036
02:00:33,602 --> 02:00:36,521
What did he mean? Forgot about what?

2037
02:00:36,605 --> 02:00:39,690
Well, he meant that he'd forgotten
Mr. Lemon was a deputy sheriff.

2038
02:00:39,775 --> 02:00:43,403
And he said,
"Yes, I'll go turn myself in to Mr. Lemon."

2039
02:00:43,487 --> 02:00:47,698
Yes, I see. Your Honor, I have no other
direct questions at this time...

2040
02:00:47,783 --> 02:00:50,368
but since I'm sure
it's difficult to visualize...

2041
02:00:50,452 --> 02:00:53,538
the part a little dog
played on this night...

2042
02:00:53,622 --> 02:00:57,542
I should like a few minutes to show the
court this remarkable little animal.

2043
02:00:57,626 --> 02:00:59,544
Do the People object?

2044
02:00:59,628 --> 02:01:01,546
I'm sure if we raise an objection,
Your Honor...

2045
02:01:01,630 --> 02:01:04,924
Mr. Biegler will declare that we're
haters of all small, furry animals.

2046
02:01:05,008 --> 02:01:06,947
[Spectators Chuckle]

2047
02:01:06,948 --> 02:01:08,886
A creature that cannot talk
will be a welcome relief.

2048
02:01:08,971 --> 02:01:11,222
- Bring in the dog.
- [Spectators Chuckling]

2049
02:01:11,306 --> 02:01:15,852
Thank you, sir. Will the, uh,
deputy bring in the dog, please.

2050
02:01:28,991 --> 02:01:31,284
Uh, you can put him right there.

2051
02:01:32,453 --> 02:01:34,370
Fine.
Here, Muff! Here, Muff! Come on!

2052
02:01:34,455 --> 02:01:36,372
Come on! Come on! Come on! Come on!

2053
02:01:36,457 --> 02:01:38,458
That's a boy.

2054
02:01:39,126 --> 02:01:42,795
And now I'll ask Mrs. Manion
to bring a flashlight for the dog.

2055
02:01:53,849 --> 02:01:58,311
Now, I ask the court to notice
that the dog turned on the light.

2056
02:02:00,481 --> 02:02:02,815
[Laughing]

2057
02:02:07,321 --> 02:02:10,072
Well, it's easy to see that Muff
doesn't know who his enemies are.

2058
02:02:10,157 --> 02:02:12,283
- [Laughing Continues]
- Remove the dog, please.

2059
02:02:12,367 --> 02:02:14,285
- Yes, sir.
- The witness will resume the stand.

2060
02:02:14,369 --> 02:02:17,497
Here we go, Muff. All right.

2061
02:02:18,874 --> 02:02:23,127
Mrs. Manion, may I congratulate you
on your well-trained pet.

2062
02:02:23,212 --> 02:02:25,129
May I also say that I'm pleased to see...

2063
02:02:25,214 --> 02:02:28,466
you are not today
hiding your lovely hair under a hat.

2064
02:02:28,550 --> 02:02:32,470
Your Honor, is the assistant attorney
general from Lansing pitching woo...

2065
02:02:32,554 --> 02:02:34,847
or is he going to cross-examine?

2066
02:02:34,932 --> 02:02:36,474
Let's get on with it.

2067
02:02:36,558 --> 02:02:38,809
Mrs. Manion, what was your occupation
before you were married?

2068
02:02:38,894 --> 02:02:41,896
- Housewife.
- Oh, then you've been married before?

2069
02:02:41,980 --> 02:02:44,295
Yes, once.

2070
02:02:44,296 --> 02:02:46,609
I suppose your first
husband, uh, died, hmm?

2071
02:02:46,693 --> 02:02:47,693
No.

2072
02:02:47,778 --> 02:02:50,321
Did you divorce your first husband
to marry Lieutenant Manion?

2073
02:02:50,405 --> 02:02:52,990
Your Honor, if counsel wants to know
the grounds for Mrs. Manion's divorce...

2074
02:02:53,075 --> 02:02:54,617
let him ask that question.

2075
02:02:54,701 --> 02:02:56,452
What were the grounds for divorce,
Mrs. Manion?

2076
02:02:56,537 --> 02:02:58,351
Mental cruelty.

2077
02:02:58,352 --> 02:03:00,164
Naturally.
And how long after your divorce...

2078
02:03:00,249 --> 02:03:02,458
was it that you married
Lieutenant Manion?

2079
02:03:02,543 --> 02:03:04,252
Uh, I'm not sure.

2080
02:03:04,336 --> 02:03:07,338
May I refresh the witness's memory
for Mr. Dancer?

2081
02:03:07,422 --> 02:03:09,340
- By all means.
- I believe she told me...

2082
02:03:09,424 --> 02:03:12,843
that they were married
three days after the divorce.

2083
02:03:12,928 --> 02:03:15,179
Thank you, Mr. Biegler.
ls that correct, Mrs. Manion?

2084
02:03:15,264 --> 02:03:16,722
Yes.

2085
02:03:16,807 --> 02:03:19,433
Then unless yours
was a whirlwind courtship...

2086
02:03:19,518 --> 02:03:21,644
you must have known Lieutenant Manion
before your divorce.

2087
02:03:21,728 --> 02:03:23,688
- Did you?
- Yes.

2088
02:03:24,648 --> 02:03:28,359
Mrs. Manion, what is your...
[Clears Throat] religious affiliation?

2089
02:03:28,443 --> 02:03:30,361
[Laura] I'm a Catholic.

2090
02:03:30,445 --> 02:03:33,739
- Catholic in good standing?
- Well, no. The divorce, you know.

2091
02:03:33,824 --> 02:03:36,701
You mean you were excommunicated
because of the divorce and remarriage?

2092
02:03:36,785 --> 02:03:37,910
Yes.

2093
02:03:38,495 --> 02:03:42,164
Mrs. Manion, wouldn't you say
that a Catholic who can blithely ignore...

2094
02:03:42,249 --> 02:03:44,709
one of the cardinal rules of her church...

2095
02:03:44,793 --> 02:03:48,045
could also easily ignore
an oath taken on one of its artifacts...

2096
02:03:48,130 --> 02:03:50,590
say, an oath taken on a rosary?

2097
02:03:51,800 --> 02:03:54,427
I-I-I don't think that's true.

2098
02:03:54,511 --> 02:03:56,200
But wouldn't you think
there'd be some doubt

2099
02:03:56,201 --> 02:03:57,888
about the integrity
of such a person?

2100
02:03:58,599 --> 02:04:00,600
I don't know. Uh...

2101
02:04:00,684 --> 02:04:03,227
All I know is the rosary
means something to me.

2102
02:04:03,770 --> 02:04:07,898
I see.
Well, I'll pass on to something else.

2103
02:04:07,983 --> 02:04:10,735
Mrs. Manion, you testified
that your husband came home late...

2104
02:04:10,819 --> 02:04:12,570
from his work
on the night of the shooting.

2105
02:04:12,654 --> 02:04:14,572
Were you a little angry
about his being late?

2106
02:04:14,656 --> 02:04:16,907
Well, I-I...
I guess I was a little put out.

2107
02:04:16,992 --> 02:04:19,910
- Did you have an argument?
- Not much. A little.

2108
02:04:19,995 --> 02:04:22,079
When you left the trailer
to go to the inn...

2109
02:04:22,164 --> 02:04:24,040
did your husband know you were going?

2110
02:04:24,124 --> 02:04:25,625
He was asleep.

2111
02:04:25,709 --> 02:04:27,752
Was part of your reason
for going without his knowledge...

2112
02:04:27,836 --> 02:04:30,129
because you were, uh, vexed?

2113
02:04:31,089 --> 02:04:34,258
Well, I-I'd been ironing all day and I...

2114
02:04:35,010 --> 02:04:36,553
Yes, I guess that's true.

2115
02:04:36,554 --> 02:04:38,095
Your Honor, the counsel
has deliberately...

2116
02:04:38,180 --> 02:04:39,805
cut off my view of the witness.

2117
02:04:39,890 --> 02:04:41,390
I'm sorry, Mr. Biegler.

2118
02:04:41,475 --> 02:04:43,684
I wouldn't want to interfere
with your signals to Mrs. Manion.

2119
02:04:43,769 --> 02:04:46,103
I object to the implication
I was signaling the witness.

2120
02:04:46,188 --> 02:04:49,106
This is the shabbiest
courtroom trick I've ever seen.

2121
02:04:49,191 --> 02:04:51,108
You haven't lived, Mr. Biegler.

2122
02:04:51,193 --> 02:04:53,569
Your Honor, I ask the court
to rule on my objection.

2123
02:04:53,654 --> 02:04:55,946
Mr. Dancer, will you be careful
not to place yourself...

2124
02:04:56,031 --> 02:04:58,324
between Mr. Biegler and his witness.

2125
02:04:58,408 --> 02:05:01,952
Of course, Your Honor.
Anything else, Mr. Biegler?

2126
02:05:02,037 --> 02:05:03,954
You do it once more, I'll punt you...

2127
02:05:04,039 --> 02:05:06,582
all the way out into
the middle of Lake Superior.

2128
02:05:06,667 --> 02:05:10,002
- [Spectators Laughing]
- [Judge Weaver] Gentlemen, gentlemen.

2129
02:05:10,087 --> 02:05:12,380
This rowing has got to stop.

2130
02:05:12,464 --> 02:05:16,467
The next one of you that speaks out of turn
will have me to deal with.

2131
02:05:16,551 --> 02:05:18,678
Now get on with your cross-examination.

2132
02:05:18,762 --> 02:05:22,014
Would you have gone to the inn
if your husband had, uh, been awake?

2133
02:05:22,099 --> 02:05:25,518
- He probably would have gone with me.
- But would you have gone alone?

2134
02:05:25,602 --> 02:05:29,188
- Not if he didn't want me to.
- Would he have not wanted you to?

2135
02:05:29,856 --> 02:05:32,566
I'm not sure.
I... I don't know how to answer that.

2136
02:05:32,651 --> 02:05:34,694
Well, had you ever gone
to the Thunder Bay Inn...

2137
02:05:34,778 --> 02:05:37,905
or elsewhere in Thunder Bay
alone at night?

2138
02:05:38,407 --> 02:05:41,617
- Yes, sometimes.
- Did your husband know you were going?

2139
02:05:42,494 --> 02:05:44,662
Not always. He goes to sleep early and...

2140
02:05:44,746 --> 02:05:47,623
and sometimes I'm restless.

2141
02:05:47,708 --> 02:05:49,834
Where did you go on these occasions?

2142
02:05:49,918 --> 02:05:53,713
Oh, I'd take a walk by the lake
or went to the bingo place.

2143
02:05:53,797 --> 02:05:57,216
- Maybe to the inn.
- You ever go to meet another man?

2144
02:05:57,759 --> 02:06:00,010
No, I didn't. I never did that.

2145
02:06:00,554 --> 02:06:04,348
You mean to say, Mrs. Manion, a lovely
woman like yourself, attractive to men...

2146
02:06:04,433 --> 02:06:06,475
lonely, restless, that you never once...

2147
02:06:06,560 --> 02:06:09,520
Objection, Your Honor! The witness
has answered the question about other men.

2148
02:06:09,604 --> 02:06:12,356
Counsel is now making
a veiled suggestion to the jury.

2149
02:06:12,441 --> 02:06:14,525
I withdraw the question.

2150
02:06:14,609 --> 02:06:19,071
Now, Mrs. Manion, on these
occasional excursions into the night...

2151
02:06:19,156 --> 02:06:21,657
did you always go and return home alone?

2152
02:06:21,742 --> 02:06:23,284
Of course.

2153
02:06:23,368 --> 02:06:26,871
Mrs. Manion, you testified that the reason
you got into Barney Quill's car...

2154
02:06:26,955 --> 02:06:29,206
was because you were afraid
to go home alone.

2155
02:06:29,291 --> 02:06:31,459
Why were you so frightened
on this particular night?

2156
02:06:32,419 --> 02:06:36,005
I said that it was because he told me
bears had been seen around.

2157
02:06:36,590 --> 02:06:38,717
Was this the first time
you'd heard that bears

2158
02:06:38,718 --> 02:06:40,843
came around Thunder Bay
to pick up scraps?

2159
02:06:40,927 --> 02:06:43,262
- No.
- Had you seen the bears before?

2160
02:06:43,346 --> 02:06:44,513
Yes.

2161
02:06:44,598 --> 02:06:47,057
Oh, this was just the first time
you were afraid of them?

2162
02:06:47,142 --> 02:06:49,268
No, I was always afraid of them.

2163
02:06:49,352 --> 02:06:51,604
Oh, this was just the first time
you were enough afraid...

2164
02:06:51,688 --> 02:06:54,732
to allow a man to take you home
from one of your evening prowls?

2165
02:06:54,816 --> 02:06:58,402
Objection! The use of the word "prowl"
is meant to mislead the jury.

2166
02:06:58,487 --> 02:07:00,571
- [Judge Weaver] Sustained.
- I apologize.

2167
02:07:00,655 --> 02:07:04,658
Mrs. Manion, I didn't mean to imply
that you were a huntress.

2168
02:07:04,743 --> 02:07:06,702
Was this the first time
that you were enough afraid...

2169
02:07:06,787 --> 02:07:10,122
to allow a man to take you home
from one of your evening walks?

2170
02:07:10,832 --> 02:07:13,667
Well, it... it wasn't just that.

2171
02:07:13,752 --> 02:07:15,628
- It was...
- Oh, come now, Mrs. Manion.

2172
02:07:15,712 --> 02:07:17,130
You should be able to
answer that straight off.

2173
02:07:17,131 --> 02:07:18,547
That's a simple enough question.

2174
02:07:18,632 --> 02:07:20,800
Your Honor,
how can the witness answer straight off...

2175
02:07:20,884 --> 02:07:23,219
when the counsel keeps
interrupting the answer?

2176
02:07:23,303 --> 02:07:26,430
The witness seemed a little slow to me,
Mr. Biegler.

2177
02:07:26,515 --> 02:07:29,433
However, let her complete her answers
before you interrupt.

2178
02:07:29,518 --> 02:07:32,269
Of course, Your Honor.
In any case, Mr. Biegler's objection...

2179
02:07:32,354 --> 02:07:35,231
has given Mrs. Manion sufficient time
to think of an answer to my question.

2180
02:07:35,315 --> 02:07:37,274
You've thought of one,
haven't you, Mrs. Manion?

2181
02:07:37,359 --> 02:07:40,611
What I was going to say was that I
didn't want to offend Mr. Quill...

2182
02:07:40,695 --> 02:07:43,948
by making him think that I was
afraid of him or didn't like him.

2183
02:07:44,032 --> 02:07:47,743
He'd been very pleasant to my husband
and me when we'd been in his bar.

2184
02:07:47,828 --> 02:07:49,642
That's very good, Mrs. Manion.
Very good indeed.

2185
02:07:49,643 --> 02:07:51,455
Your Honor, please.

2186
02:07:51,540 --> 02:07:55,960
The attorney for the People will reserve
his comments for the arguments.

2187
02:07:56,044 --> 02:07:58,504
I will ask you this question, Mrs. Manion.

2188
02:07:59,089 --> 02:08:04,218
Was this the first time you had been
in Barney Quill's car at night?

2189
02:08:07,180 --> 02:08:09,682
Mrs. Manion, did you hear the question?

2190
02:08:10,225 --> 02:08:11,809
Yes, I heard.

2191
02:08:12,561 --> 02:08:14,854
Yes, it was the first time.

2192
02:08:15,564 --> 02:08:18,399
Would you raise your voice a little,
Mrs. Manion?

2193
02:08:18,483 --> 02:08:21,193
[Laura]
I said it was the first time.

2194
02:08:22,279 --> 02:08:26,657
Now, Mrs. Manion,
I'm quite concerned about the lost panties.

2195
02:08:26,741 --> 02:08:29,535
Would you describe this article of clothing
to the court, please?

2196
02:08:31,329 --> 02:08:33,998
They were nylon
and had lace up the sides.

2197
02:08:34,082 --> 02:08:36,500
There was a label in them
of the place I got them...

2198
02:08:36,585 --> 02:08:38,502
the Smart Shop, in Phoenix, Arizona.

2199
02:08:38,587 --> 02:08:40,504
What was the color of the panties?

2200
02:08:40,589 --> 02:08:42,506
- I believe white.
- You believe?

2201
02:08:42,591 --> 02:08:44,050
I have white and pink.
They may have been pink.

2202
02:08:44,051 --> 02:08:45,509
You're not sure?

2203
02:08:45,594 --> 02:08:48,470
Haven't you checked your lingerie
to see which pair of panties is missing?

2204
02:08:48,555 --> 02:08:49,555
No.

2205
02:08:49,639 --> 02:08:51,473
When your husband came home
late from his work...

2206
02:08:51,558 --> 02:08:54,852
and you had this little spat,
were you already dressed to go out?

2207
02:08:54,936 --> 02:08:56,770
- No.
- When did you dress?

2208
02:08:56,855 --> 02:08:58,564
After dinner, when he was asleep.

2209
02:08:58,648 --> 02:09:01,734
It's been stated here that you were
bare legged in the bar. Is that true?

2210
02:09:01,818 --> 02:09:02,860
Yes.

2211
02:09:02,944 --> 02:09:05,696
In your anger at your husband
and your haste to get out of the trailer...

2212
02:09:05,780 --> 02:09:06,844
perhaps you didn't put
on any panties either?

2213
02:09:06,845 --> 02:09:07,907
Objection.

2214
02:09:07,991 --> 02:09:10,409
The witness has already testified
as to what she was wearing.

2215
02:09:10,493 --> 02:09:13,037
- [Judge Weaver] Sustained.
- Do you always wear panties, Mrs. Manion?

2216
02:09:13,121 --> 02:09:15,873
Now, Your Honor,
I object to this line of questioning.

2217
02:09:15,957 --> 02:09:18,834
It's immaterial what
Mrs. Manion does all the time.

2218
02:09:18,919 --> 02:09:21,128
On the night she was attacked,
she was wearing panties...

2219
02:09:21,212 --> 02:09:22,838
and that's all we're concerned with.

2220
02:09:22,923 --> 02:09:25,382
Your Honor, Mrs. Manion seems
a little bit uncertain...

2221
02:09:25,467 --> 02:09:27,593
about what kind of panties
she was wearing...

2222
02:09:27,677 --> 02:09:29,595
and since these panties
have not been found...

2223
02:09:29,679 --> 02:09:33,432
I submit that it's possible
she wasn't wearing any and has forgotten.

2224
02:09:33,516 --> 02:09:36,936
- That's all I'm trying to get at.
- You may answer, Mrs. Manion.

2225
02:09:38,021 --> 02:09:40,272
Do you always wear panties?

2226
02:09:41,358 --> 02:09:43,025
No.

2227
02:09:43,109 --> 02:09:46,111
On what occasions don't you wear them?
When you go out alone at night?

2228
02:09:46,196 --> 02:09:48,156
Oh, no, no. Objection.
He says he's going

2229
02:09:48,157 --> 02:09:50,115
after one thing, then
he goes after another.

2230
02:09:50,200 --> 02:09:52,076
I'll sustain the objection.

2231
02:09:52,160 --> 02:09:55,788
Strike out the last two questions
and Mrs. Manion's answer.

2232
02:09:55,872 --> 02:09:58,624
Now, Mr. Dancer, get off the panties.

2233
02:09:58,708 --> 02:10:02,294
- You've done enough damage.
- Yes, Your Honor.

2234
02:10:02,379 --> 02:10:06,298
Mrs. Manion, is your husband a jealous man?

2235
02:10:06,841 --> 02:10:08,405
He loves me.

2236
02:10:08,406 --> 02:10:09,969
I'm sure of that, but is
he excessively jealous?

2237
02:10:10,053 --> 02:10:12,805
Your Honor, how can the witness
answer that question?

2238
02:10:12,889 --> 02:10:14,974
What's the norm of jealousy?

2239
02:10:15,058 --> 02:10:18,060
Can you put your question a
little differently, Mr. Dancer?

2240
02:10:18,144 --> 02:10:20,187
Has your husband ever struck you
in a jealous rage?

2241
02:10:20,271 --> 02:10:22,315
No. Your Honor, I think
Mr. Dancer's fishing now.

2242
02:10:22,316 --> 02:10:24,358
What's the relevancy
of this question?

2243
02:10:24,442 --> 02:10:26,485
Your Honor,
the shoe is squeezing Mr. Biegler's foot.

2244
02:10:26,569 --> 02:10:28,779
In his own words,
this is not a high school debate...

2245
02:10:28,863 --> 02:10:30,823
this is a cross-examination
in a murder trial.

2246
02:10:30,907 --> 02:10:32,825
Proceed, Mr. Dancer.

2247
02:10:34,411 --> 02:10:36,161
Mrs. Manion...

2248
02:10:37,247 --> 02:10:40,332
did you ever go out socially
in Thunder Bay?

2249
02:10:40,417 --> 02:10:42,334
Yes, a few times.

2250
02:10:42,419 --> 02:10:44,503
When your husband's outfit
moved to Thunder Bay...

2251
02:10:44,587 --> 02:10:46,547
didn't Barney Quill throw
a cocktail party...

2252
02:10:46,631 --> 02:10:49,008
- for the officers and their wives?
- Yes.

2253
02:10:49,092 --> 02:10:52,344
Didn't your husband strike
a young second lieutenant at this party?

2254
02:10:54,097 --> 02:10:56,390
There was a little scuffle. It wasn't much.

2255
02:10:56,474 --> 02:10:59,476
- What was it about?
- I'm not sure I remember.

2256
02:10:59,561 --> 02:11:03,731
- Were you too drunk to remember?
- No, I was not.

2257
02:11:04,774 --> 02:11:07,651
I-I-I think it was because
the lieutenant...

2258
02:11:07,736 --> 02:11:10,821
was cutting in too much
when I was dancing with my husband.

2259
02:11:10,905 --> 02:11:13,073
And shortly afterwards,
on the veranda of the inn...

2260
02:11:13,158 --> 02:11:16,493
didn't your husband slap you hard enough
so that you fell against the wall?

2261
02:11:17,704 --> 02:11:21,665
- Well, h-he was drinking.
- [Dancer] Wasn't this a jealous rage?

2262
02:11:22,417 --> 02:11:25,169
- I don't know!
- Do you remember why he struck you?

2263
02:11:25,253 --> 02:11:27,171
- Yes.
- Wasn't he enraged at you...

2264
02:11:27,255 --> 02:11:29,673
because he thought you'd encouraged
this young lieutenant?

2265
02:11:29,758 --> 02:11:31,675
He might have thought so.

2266
02:11:31,760 --> 02:11:33,719
Mrs. Manion,
there are witnesses to this whole affair.

2267
02:11:33,803 --> 02:11:36,013
I'll ask you again.
Wasn't this a jealous rage?

2268
02:11:36,097 --> 02:11:38,557
I guess you could call it that.

2269
02:11:39,768 --> 02:11:41,727
Now I'll ask you...

2270
02:11:43,438 --> 02:11:47,691
on the night of the shooting,
what did you swear?

2271
02:11:47,776 --> 02:11:50,235
What oath did you take on the rosary?

2272
02:11:51,279 --> 02:11:53,864
It was about Barney Quill raping me.

2273
02:11:53,948 --> 02:11:56,992
Why did you swear on the rosary
that he raped you?

2274
02:11:57,535 --> 02:12:00,120
For the reason that my husband said...
because I was hysterical.

2275
02:12:00,205 --> 02:12:02,206
That was the reason he gave
for asking you to swear.

2276
02:12:02,290 --> 02:12:04,208
- What was your reason for swearing?
- So he'd believe me.

2277
02:12:04,292 --> 02:12:06,210
- Why shouldn't he believe you?
- Objection.

2278
02:12:06,294 --> 02:12:08,545
The reason for the use of the rosary
has been established.

2279
02:12:08,630 --> 02:12:11,216
These questions are immaterial.

2280
02:12:11,217 --> 02:12:13,801
No, I think I'll take
the answer, Mr. Biegler.

2281
02:12:13,885 --> 02:12:15,719
I'll ask you again, Mrs. Manion.

2282
02:12:15,804 --> 02:12:17,930
Why shouldn't he believe you?

2283
02:12:19,265 --> 02:12:21,225
Because I wasn't making much sense.

2284
02:12:21,309 --> 02:12:23,352
Did he think you'd lie
about a thing like that?

2285
02:12:23,436 --> 02:12:25,167
Objection, Your Honor!
Lieutenant Manion has

2286
02:12:25,168 --> 02:12:26,897
already testified as
to what he thought.

2287
02:12:26,981 --> 02:12:30,609
- Sustained.
- Did your husband strike you that night?

2288
02:12:31,277 --> 02:12:33,445
Did he hit you that night?

2289
02:12:35,698 --> 02:12:37,741
Well, he... he...

2290
02:12:37,826 --> 02:12:41,370
He may have slapped me
because I was hysterical.

2291
02:12:41,454 --> 02:12:44,081
And didn't you swear to a lie to keep him
from hitting you again?

2292
02:12:44,165 --> 02:12:45,791
No! No, I didn't. I did not.

2293
02:12:45,875 --> 02:12:48,127
Hadn't he already beaten you up
at the gate when he caught you...

2294
02:12:48,211 --> 02:12:49,399
coming home from lovers'
lane with Barney Quill?

2295
02:12:49,400 --> 02:12:50,587
Objection! Objection!

2296
02:12:50,672 --> 02:12:53,423
The witness has already testified
she was beaten by Barney Quill.

2297
02:12:53,508 --> 02:12:55,592
- [Spectators Murmuring]
- Quiet, quiet.

2298
02:12:55,677 --> 02:12:58,428
No more questions.

2299
02:12:58,513 --> 02:13:01,098
I think the witness has had enough,
Your Honor.

2300
02:13:01,182 --> 02:13:04,268
The witness may step down.
We'll recess for lunch.

2301
02:13:04,352 --> 02:13:06,436
[Gavel Raps]

2302
02:13:06,521 --> 02:13:08,772
[Bailiff] Recess until 1:00.

2303
02:13:08,857 --> 02:13:10,399
[Gavel Raps]

2304
02:13:11,484 --> 02:13:13,402
Sorry, baby. You were fine.

2305
02:13:13,486 --> 02:13:16,822
[Bell Clanging]

2306
02:13:46,895 --> 02:13:48,812
Dr. Smith?

2307
02:13:48,897 --> 02:13:50,814
I've come to meet you, sir.

2308
02:13:50,899 --> 02:13:53,317
- My name is...
- I'm sorry. You've made a mistake.

2309
02:13:53,401 --> 02:13:56,486
Maybe I'm the one you're looking for.
Are you Mr. Biegler?

2310
02:13:56,571 --> 02:13:58,906
No, I'm his associate in the case.

2311
02:13:59,449 --> 02:14:02,159
- Don't tell me you're Dr. Smith.
- That's me.

2312
02:14:02,243 --> 02:14:06,830
- The army psychiatrist?
- Maybe you expected me to be in uniform.

2313
02:14:06,915 --> 02:14:08,832
No. Well...

2314
02:14:08,917 --> 02:14:11,668
I didn't expect anybody so young.

2315
02:14:11,753 --> 02:14:13,670
I'm 40.

2316
02:14:13,755 --> 02:14:18,675
I sort of hoped you'd, uh, have a beard
and wear a monocle.

2317
02:14:18,760 --> 02:14:20,719
Oh, I see.

2318
02:14:21,346 --> 02:14:23,723
That better?

2319
02:14:23,724 --> 02:14:26,099
It helps.
You're on the stand this afternoon.

2320
02:14:28,603 --> 02:14:30,520
Doctor, have you formed an opinion...

2321
02:14:30,605 --> 02:14:32,522
as to Frederick Manion's
mental and emotional state...

2322
02:14:32,607 --> 02:14:34,524
at the time he killed Barney Quill?

2323
02:14:34,609 --> 02:14:36,526
- I have.
- And what is that opinion?

2324
02:14:36,611 --> 02:14:39,363
He was temporarily insane
at the time of the shooting.

2325
02:14:39,447 --> 02:14:41,365
At the time of the shooting,
do you believe...

2326
02:14:41,449 --> 02:14:43,867
he was able to distinguish
right from wrong?

2327
02:14:43,952 --> 02:14:46,870
He may or may not have been.
It doesn't make too much difference.

2328
02:14:46,955 --> 02:14:50,040
All right. Now, Doctor,
as clearly as you can...

2329
02:14:50,124 --> 02:14:54,002
will you explain Frederick Manion's
temporary insanity.

2330
02:14:54,087 --> 02:14:57,005
It is known as dissociative reaction...

2331
02:14:57,090 --> 02:15:01,718
a psychic shock which creates
an almost overwhelming tension...

2332
02:15:01,803 --> 02:15:05,055
which the person in shock must alleviate.

2333
02:15:05,139 --> 02:15:07,557
In Lieutenant Manion's case... a soldier...

2334
02:15:07,642 --> 02:15:10,394
it is only natural
that he would turn to action.

2335
02:15:10,478 --> 02:15:14,231
Only direct, simple action
against Barney Quill...

2336
02:15:14,315 --> 02:15:16,817
would relieve this unbearable tension.

2337
02:15:16,901 --> 02:15:20,028
This is not too uncommon.
For example, in combat...

2338
02:15:20,113 --> 02:15:23,490
some of the more remarkable heroics
take place in this state of mind.

2339
02:15:23,574 --> 02:15:25,639
Is there another name for
dissociative reaction,

2340
02:15:25,640 --> 02:15:27,703
one we might be more
likely to recognize?

2341
02:15:27,787 --> 02:15:31,123
Yes, it has been known
as "irresistible impulse."

2342
02:15:31,207 --> 02:15:34,251
Now, Doctor, a man in the grip
of irresistible impulse...

2343
02:15:34,335 --> 02:15:36,753
would he be likely
to go to his neighbor for advice...

2344
02:15:36,838 --> 02:15:39,715
or call up the police to come to his aid?

2345
02:15:39,799 --> 02:15:43,427
- Completely incompatible.
- Yes. But our man was able to think...

2346
02:15:43,511 --> 02:15:45,804
of going and taking out
a gun and loading it...

2347
02:15:45,888 --> 02:15:47,889
before setting out to find Quill.

2348
02:15:47,974 --> 02:15:49,808
Well, that was his conscious mind working.

2349
02:15:49,892 --> 02:15:52,394
But if no gun had been available,
he would have gone anyway.

2350
02:15:52,478 --> 02:15:55,939
How would a man look in the grip
of dissociative reaction?

2351
02:15:56,024 --> 02:16:00,277
He might appear to be deadly calm,
fiercely deliberate.

2352
02:16:00,361 --> 02:16:03,322
Mm-hmm. Would you describe
his behavior as being...

2353
02:16:03,406 --> 02:16:05,866
like a mailman delivering the mail?

2354
02:16:05,950 --> 02:16:10,162
That's not bad. Like a mailman, he would
have a job to do, and he would do it.

2355
02:16:11,497 --> 02:16:12,581
Your witness.

2356
02:16:12,665 --> 02:16:16,585
Doctor, did you find any psychosis
in Frederick Manion?

2357
02:16:16,669 --> 02:16:17,878
I did not.

2358
02:16:17,962 --> 02:16:20,964
- [Dancer] Any neuroses?
- I found no history of neuroses.

2359
02:16:21,049 --> 02:16:24,634
- [Dancer] Any history of, uh, delusion?
- None.

2360
02:16:24,719 --> 02:16:26,803
- Loss of memory?
- Not before this instance.

2361
02:16:26,888 --> 02:16:31,308
[Whispering]
Hey. Can you spot Mary Pilant?

2362
02:16:31,392 --> 02:16:33,477
She didn't come back after lunch.

2363
02:16:33,561 --> 02:16:36,313
I think you'd better give up on that one.

2364
02:16:36,397 --> 02:16:38,273
Doctor, you stated that the defendant...

2365
02:16:38,358 --> 02:16:40,318
might or might not have
been able to distinguish

2366
02:16:40,319 --> 02:16:42,277
the difference between
right and wrong...

2367
02:16:42,362 --> 02:16:43,987
but that it wouldn't have made
much difference.

2368
02:16:44,072 --> 02:16:46,448
- Am I right? Is that what you said?
- Approximately, yes.

2369
02:16:46,532 --> 02:16:48,450
Did you mean that at the time
of the shooting...

2370
02:16:48,534 --> 02:16:50,452
he could have known the difference
between right and wrong?

2371
02:16:50,536 --> 02:16:52,329
He might have, yes.

2372
02:16:52,413 --> 02:16:57,000
Dr. Smith, if the defendant
could have known what he was doing...

2373
02:16:57,085 --> 02:16:59,002
and could have known that it was wrong...

2374
02:16:59,087 --> 02:17:02,130
how can you come here and testify
that he was legally insane?

2375
02:17:02,215 --> 02:17:04,299
I'm not saying he was legally insane.

2376
02:17:04,384 --> 02:17:06,301
I'm saying that in his mental condition...

2377
02:17:06,386 --> 02:17:08,970
it would not have made any difference
whether he knew right from wrong.

2378
02:17:09,055 --> 02:17:11,056
He would still have shot Quill.

2379
02:17:12,100 --> 02:17:14,684
Dr. Smith, are you willing...

2380
02:17:14,769 --> 02:17:18,188
to rest your testimony
in this case on this opinion?

2381
02:17:18,272 --> 02:17:20,232
Yes, I am.

2382
02:17:21,442 --> 02:17:23,860
Your Honor, I'd like to
ask for a short recess.

2383
02:17:23,945 --> 02:17:25,862
The attorneys for the People
would like to meet...

2384
02:17:25,947 --> 02:17:27,094
with Mr. Biegler and
the court in chambers.

2385
02:17:27,095 --> 02:17:28,240
Mr. Biegler?

2386
02:17:28,825 --> 02:17:30,659
Glad to oblige, Your Honor.

2387
02:17:30,743 --> 02:17:33,745
Short recess. Jury will remain.

2388
02:17:45,299 --> 02:17:47,384
Someday I'm going to horrify tradition...

2389
02:17:47,468 --> 02:17:53,223
and lay a dense blue cloud of tobacco smoke
in that hallowed courtroom.

2390
02:17:53,307 --> 02:17:55,517
What's on your mind, Mr. Dancer?

2391
02:17:55,601 --> 02:17:57,519
Your Honor, in view of
Dr. Smith's testimony...

2392
02:17:57,603 --> 02:18:00,063
I thought perhaps the defense might like
to change their plea.

2393
02:18:00,148 --> 02:18:02,899
- Change it to what?
- Guilty, of course.

2394
02:18:02,984 --> 02:18:05,735
- No, we'll still go for broke.
- Hell, Polly.

2395
02:18:05,820 --> 02:18:08,071
You know a guy's not
considered legally nuts in Michigan...

2396
02:18:08,156 --> 02:18:10,073
unless he didn't know right from wrong.

2397
02:18:10,158 --> 02:18:12,347
Why don't you come on
and get this over with?

2398
02:18:12,348 --> 02:18:14,536
Your Honor, would
you turn to page 486?

2399
02:18:14,620 --> 02:18:16,246
[Lodwick] What's that?

2400
02:18:16,330 --> 02:18:18,999
Appears to be a law book, Mr. Lodwick.

2401
02:18:20,334 --> 02:18:22,252
[Chuckles]
Oh, I'm sorry, Your Honor.

2402
02:18:22,336 --> 02:18:25,422
I make those things
to help me think sometimes.

2403
02:18:25,506 --> 02:18:27,841
- For perch?
- No, that one's for frog.

2404
02:18:27,925 --> 02:18:29,885
What case is he citing, Judge?

2405
02:18:29,969 --> 02:18:31,950
We gig frogs down in
my part of the country.

2406
02:18:31,951 --> 02:18:33,930
Yeah, well, it's
the same up here.

2407
02:18:34,015 --> 02:18:36,766
I'm a trout man myself,
but this is a new wrinkle I'm gonna try.

2408
02:18:36,851 --> 02:18:39,060
They do it a lot
down in the bayous down south.

2409
02:18:39,145 --> 02:18:41,062
The idea...
they get a great big long pole...

2410
02:18:41,147 --> 02:18:45,650
and about a ten-pound line, just sort
of drift along a high bank in a boat.

2411
02:18:45,735 --> 02:18:48,612
Then you see that
great big old bullfrog in a crevice...

2412
02:18:48,696 --> 02:18:51,615
and you sort of float this along
in front of him.

2413
02:18:51,699 --> 02:18:53,159
Pop! That old tongue of
his snaps out and...

2414
02:18:53,160 --> 02:18:54,618
[Clicks Tongue]

2415
02:18:54,702 --> 02:18:57,287
- You've got frog's legs for supper.
- Well, I'll be darned.

2416
02:18:57,371 --> 02:19:01,625
- Why don't you keep it? Try it sometime.
- Thanks. I will.

2417
02:19:01,709 --> 02:19:03,835
486.

2418
02:19:05,087 --> 02:19:09,424
- What is it, Your Honor?
- People versus Durfee, 1886.

2419
02:19:10,051 --> 02:19:11,801
Looks like a precedent.

2420
02:19:11,886 --> 02:19:14,262
Would you like to read it, Mr. Dancer?

2421
02:19:15,223 --> 02:19:17,140
No, thank you, Your Honor.

2422
02:19:17,225 --> 02:19:19,351
I think I recall the case.

2423
02:19:19,894 --> 02:19:24,356
We're, uh, hooked... like the frog.

2424
02:19:26,901 --> 02:19:30,487
[Dancer] Dr. Harcourt, where did you
receive your university training?

2425
02:19:30,571 --> 02:19:32,489
Johns Hopkins, in Baltimore, Maryland.

2426
02:19:32,573 --> 02:19:34,783
And where do you practice now?

2427
02:19:34,867 --> 02:19:38,495
I'm the medical superintendent of the
Bonder State Hospital for the Insane.

2428
02:19:38,579 --> 02:19:43,667
It's been stated here that dissociative
reaction, or irresistible impulse...

2429
02:19:43,751 --> 02:19:46,670
is not uncommon among soldiers in combat.

2430
02:19:46,754 --> 02:19:49,339
- Do you agree with that statement?
- I do...

2431
02:19:49,423 --> 02:19:51,341
but not as it was put by Dr. Smith.

2432
02:19:51,425 --> 02:19:55,345
- Where would you depart from Dr. Smith?
- Well, dissociative reaction...

2433
02:19:55,429 --> 02:19:59,349
is not something that comes out of the blue
and disappears as quickly.

2434
02:19:59,433 --> 02:20:03,520
It can only occur...
even among soldiers in combat...

2435
02:20:03,604 --> 02:20:07,524
if the individual has a psychoneurotic
condition of long standing.

2436
02:20:07,608 --> 02:20:11,361
It's been testified here that a psychiatric
examination of the defendant...

2437
02:20:11,445 --> 02:20:14,030
showed no, um, evidence of neuroses...

2438
02:20:14,115 --> 02:20:16,533
and no history of dissociative reaction.

2439
02:20:16,617 --> 02:20:18,535
You've further heard it testified...

2440
02:20:18,619 --> 02:20:23,373
that the defendant's behavior on the night
of the shooting was cool and direct.

2441
02:20:23,457 --> 02:20:25,250
As an observer, do you
remember this testimony?

2442
02:20:25,251 --> 02:20:27,043
Yes.

2443
02:20:27,128 --> 02:20:29,045
From this, have you formed an opinion...

2444
02:20:29,130 --> 02:20:31,881
about the defendant's sanity
on the night of the shooting?

2445
02:20:31,966 --> 02:20:36,386
Yes. I'm of the opinion that he was in
sufficient possession of his faculties...

2446
02:20:36,470 --> 02:20:39,222
so that he was not dominated
by his unconscious mind.

2447
02:20:39,307 --> 02:20:42,892
In other words, he was not in the
grip of irresistible impulse?

2448
02:20:42,977 --> 02:20:44,311
In my opinion, he was not.

2449
02:20:44,312 --> 02:20:45,645
Thank you, Doctor.
Your witness, Mr. Biegler.

2450
02:20:45,730 --> 02:20:48,732
Dr. Harcourt, psychiatry
is an effort to probe...

2451
02:20:48,816 --> 02:20:51,568
into the dark, undiscovered
world of the mind.

2452
02:20:51,652 --> 02:20:55,071
And in there, the world might
be round, it could be square.

2453
02:20:55,156 --> 02:20:58,033
Your opinion could be wrong.
Dr. Smith's opinion could be right.

2454
02:20:58,117 --> 02:20:59,848
Isn't that true?

2455
02:20:59,849 --> 02:21:01,578
I'd be a poor doctor if I
didn't agree with that...

2456
02:21:01,662 --> 02:21:05,081
but I believe my opinion to be right.

2457
02:21:05,166 --> 02:21:07,459
Now, do you think you might have
changed your opinion...

2458
02:21:07,543 --> 02:21:10,462
if you had examined the defendant,
as Dr. Smith did?

2459
02:21:11,130 --> 02:21:12,714
I don't believe so.

2460
02:21:12,798 --> 02:21:15,884
But Dr. Smith's opinion was made under
better circumstances, wasn't it?

2461
02:21:15,968 --> 02:21:19,012
If you mean that he was able
to examine the man, yes.

2462
02:21:19,096 --> 02:21:20,930
Yeah. Well, thank you, Doctor.

2463
02:21:21,015 --> 02:21:24,267
That's all, Dr. Harcourt.
ls there more rebuttal?

2464
02:21:24,352 --> 02:21:26,603
We're over a barrel, Mitch.

2465
02:21:26,687 --> 02:21:28,813
We have to use him.

2466
02:21:29,357 --> 02:21:31,900
We call Duane Miller to the stand.

2467
02:21:31,984 --> 02:21:34,152
Will the sheriff please
bring in the witness?

2468
02:21:40,534 --> 02:21:42,494
What can he tell?

2469
02:21:43,204 --> 02:21:44,704
Nothing.

2470
02:21:45,706 --> 02:21:47,666
He can't tell anything.

2471
02:21:58,469 --> 02:22:00,095
Raise your right hand.
Do you solemnly swear

2472
02:22:00,096 --> 02:22:01,721
the testimony you shall
give in this cause...

2473
02:22:01,806 --> 02:22:05,350
shall be the truth, the whole truth
and nothing but the truth, so help you God?

2474
02:22:05,434 --> 02:22:07,018
I do.

2475
02:22:08,729 --> 02:22:11,648
- Would you state your name, please.
- Duane Miller.

2476
02:22:11,732 --> 02:22:13,525
Most folks call me Duke.

2477
02:22:13,526 --> 02:22:15,318
Where do you presently
reside, Mr. Miller?

2478
02:22:15,403 --> 02:22:17,320
Across the alley in the jail.

2479
02:22:17,405 --> 02:22:19,239
You know the defendant, Frederick Manion?

2480
02:22:19,323 --> 02:22:21,033
Yeah, I got to know him
in the past few weeks.

2481
02:22:21,034 --> 02:22:22,742
His cell's right next to mine.

2482
02:22:22,827 --> 02:22:25,245
When was the last conversation
you had with the lieutenant?

2483
02:22:25,329 --> 02:22:29,040
Except for "hello" this morning,
the last time was last night.

2484
02:22:29,125 --> 02:22:32,544
- Did you discuss his trial last night?
- Yeah, some.

2485
02:22:32,628 --> 02:22:35,880
Would you tell the court what Lieutenant
Manion had to say about the trial?

2486
02:22:35,965 --> 02:22:39,551
Well, I said, uh,
"Things looking up, Lieutenant?"

2487
02:22:39,635 --> 02:22:42,554
And he said, "I got it made, buster."

2488
02:22:42,638 --> 02:22:46,891
He said, "I fooled my lawyer.
I fooled that headshrinker.

2489
02:22:46,976 --> 02:22:49,686
I'm gonna fool that bunch
of corn cobbers on the jury."

2490
02:22:49,770 --> 02:22:52,689
You're a liar!
You're a lousy, stinkin' liar!

2491
02:22:52,773 --> 02:22:54,774
[Whispers] Come on. Come on.

2492
02:22:54,859 --> 02:22:56,401
Take it easy.

2493
02:22:57,361 --> 02:23:00,363
I apologize for my client, Your Honor.

2494
02:23:00,448 --> 02:23:02,365
Yet his outburst is almost excusable...

2495
02:23:02,450 --> 02:23:05,368
since the prosecution
has seen fit to put a felon on the stand...

2496
02:23:05,453 --> 02:23:07,746
to testify against an officer
in the United States Army.

2497
02:23:07,830 --> 02:23:12,459
Your Honor, I don't know who is
the worse offender, Manion or his lawyer.

2498
02:23:12,543 --> 02:23:14,544
We're close to the end.

2499
02:23:14,628 --> 02:23:20,258
In the name of heaven, let's have peace
and courtesy for these last few hours.

2500
02:23:20,342 --> 02:23:25,388
Mr. Dancer, you will continue
your interrogation without comment.

2501
02:23:25,473 --> 02:23:28,391
Mr. Biegler, you will not
sound off at every opportunity...

2502
02:23:28,476 --> 02:23:31,561
and the defendant will remain seated
in his chair and keep his mouth shut.

2503
02:23:31,645 --> 02:23:34,063
- Now go ahead.
- Mr. Miller...

2504
02:23:34,148 --> 02:23:36,733
are you certain that
Lieutenant Manion said...

2505
02:23:36,817 --> 02:23:40,236
- "I've got it made, buster"?
- That's what he said.

2506
02:23:40,321 --> 02:23:42,405
Mr. Miller,
did Lieutenant Manion say anything else?

2507
02:23:42,490 --> 02:23:44,574
Yes, sir. He said when he got out...

2508
02:23:44,658 --> 02:23:49,120
the first thing he was gonna do was to
kick that bitch from here to kingdom come.

2509
02:23:50,372 --> 02:23:53,166
- [Dancer] To whom was he referring?
- To his wife.

2510
02:23:54,126 --> 02:23:55,794
Your witness, Mr. Biegler.

2511
02:23:56,629 --> 02:23:58,421
What are you in jail for, Mr. Miller?

2512
02:23:58,506 --> 02:24:01,090
Arson. I copped out,
and I'm waiting for a sentence.

2513
02:24:01,175 --> 02:24:03,384
And how many other offenses
have you committed?

2514
02:24:03,469 --> 02:24:06,805
Well, I was in reform school when
I was a kid, but that's all.

2515
02:24:07,348 --> 02:24:09,933
Your Honor,
I'd like to see this man's criminal record.

2516
02:24:10,017 --> 02:24:12,060
Do you have his record, Mr. Lodwick?

2517
02:24:12,144 --> 02:24:13,645
Yes, sir.

2518
02:24:14,355 --> 02:24:16,314
Here it is.

2519
02:24:18,859 --> 02:24:20,777
Well, your record here
shows you've been in prison...

2520
02:24:20,861 --> 02:24:23,655
six times in three different states.

2521
02:24:24,365 --> 02:24:26,282
You were in three times for arson...

2522
02:24:26,367 --> 02:24:30,078
twice for assault with a deadly weapon,
once for larceny.

2523
02:24:30,871 --> 02:24:34,958
Yeah. Also shows you've done
short stretches in four city jails...

2524
02:24:35,042 --> 02:24:38,795
on charges of indecent exposure,
window peeping...

2525
02:24:38,879 --> 02:24:42,090
perjury and disorderly conduct.

2526
02:24:42,883 --> 02:24:44,926
Is this your true record?

2527
02:24:45,553 --> 02:24:47,637
Them things are never right.

2528
02:24:47,721 --> 02:24:50,974
How did you get the ear of the prosecution
in order to tell them...

2529
02:24:51,058 --> 02:24:53,476
about this conversation you had
with Lieutenant Manion?

2530
02:24:53,561 --> 02:24:56,521
- The D.A. was taking us to his office.
- Taking who to his office?

2531
02:24:56,605 --> 02:24:58,211
Us prisoners in the jail.

2532
02:24:58,212 --> 02:24:59,816
He take you all at
once, or one at a time?

2533
02:24:59,900 --> 02:25:01,818
One at a time.

2534
02:25:01,902 --> 02:25:04,153
Him and that other lawyer
took us to his office...

2535
02:25:04,238 --> 02:25:06,990
and asked us questions
about Lieutenant Manion.

2536
02:25:07,074 --> 02:25:09,409
Were you promised a lighter sentence
if you came over here...

2537
02:25:09,493 --> 02:25:12,120
- and went on the witness stand?
- [Dancer] Your Honor, the People object...

2538
02:25:12,204 --> 02:25:13,830
Overruled. Answer the question.

2539
02:25:13,914 --> 02:25:15,832
- I wasn't promised anything.
- Oh, you just thought...

2540
02:25:15,916 --> 02:25:19,502
it would help your own troubles if you
dreamed up this story to please the D.A.?

2541
02:25:19,587 --> 02:25:21,046
I didn't dream up nothin'.

2542
02:25:21,047 --> 02:25:22,505
You're sure that's what
Lieutenant Manion said?

2543
02:25:22,590 --> 02:25:24,216
Yeah, I'm sure.

2544
02:25:24,217 --> 02:25:25,842
Just as sure as you were
about your criminal record?

2545
02:25:25,926 --> 02:25:29,053
Well, I guess I kind of goofed on that one.

2546
02:25:30,931 --> 02:25:36,185
Your Honor, I don't feel I can dignify
this creature with any more questions.

2547
02:25:36,270 --> 02:25:38,313
Take the witness away.

2548
02:25:38,397 --> 02:25:40,857
Mr. Biegler, would you
like a conference with your client?

2549
02:25:40,941 --> 02:25:44,027
I can see how the last witness
was quite a surprise.

2550
02:25:44,111 --> 02:25:46,529
No, Your Honor.
We don't need a conference.

2551
02:25:46,614 --> 02:25:49,407
I'll recall Lieutenant Manion
to the stand right now.

2552
02:25:57,458 --> 02:26:00,919
Now you've heard the
testimony of this Miller.

2553
02:26:01,629 --> 02:26:03,379
Is any part of it true?

2554
02:26:03,464 --> 02:26:04,964
None.

2555
02:26:05,466 --> 02:26:09,969
Lieutenant, do you have any idea why he
might come here with a tale like that?

2556
02:26:10,054 --> 02:26:11,596
No, sir.

2557
02:26:13,307 --> 02:26:15,558
Have you ever talked with this man?

2558
02:26:15,643 --> 02:26:17,060
Yes.

2559
02:26:17,603 --> 02:26:19,354
And what did you talk about?

2560
02:26:21,315 --> 02:26:23,399
Nothing important.

2561
02:26:23,484 --> 02:26:25,381
Certainly nothing...

2562
02:26:25,382 --> 02:26:27,278
nothing about my personal
life or my feelings.

2563
02:26:27,988 --> 02:26:29,572
That's all I wanted to know.

2564
02:26:29,657 --> 02:26:31,324
Lieutenant Manion...

2565
02:26:32,326 --> 02:26:35,244
have you ever had any sort of...

2566
02:26:35,329 --> 02:26:37,789
trouble with, uh, Miller?

2567
02:26:38,749 --> 02:26:41,542
I don't know. What do you mean?
An argument? Something like that?

2568
02:26:41,627 --> 02:26:46,130
Well, did you ever, um, attack Miller...
physically attack him?

2569
02:26:46,757 --> 02:26:49,300
Your lawyer can't answer the
question for you, Lieutenant.

2570
02:26:49,385 --> 02:26:51,302
Did you ever physically attack Miller?

2571
02:26:51,387 --> 02:26:53,972
Well, I wouldn't call it an attack exactly.

2572
02:26:54,056 --> 02:26:55,599
I pushed his head
against the bars one day.

2573
02:26:55,600 --> 02:26:57,141
Why?

2574
02:26:57,226 --> 02:26:59,310
He said something ugly about my wife.

2575
02:26:59,395 --> 02:27:03,022
And do you remember, uh, pushing or
bumping his head against the bars?

2576
02:27:03,107 --> 02:27:05,274
Well, sure. I just told you.

2577
02:27:05,359 --> 02:27:07,652
Then this was not dissociative reaction?

2578
02:27:07,736 --> 02:27:09,112
The defendant isn't
qualified to answer that.

2579
02:27:09,113 --> 02:27:10,488
[Judge Weaver] Sustained.

2580
02:27:10,572 --> 02:27:14,325
Lieutenant Manion,
wasn't your action against Barney Quill...

2581
02:27:14,410 --> 02:27:16,327
much the same as your
action against Miller...

2582
02:27:16,412 --> 02:27:19,998
and against the lieutenant
that you struck at the cocktail party...

2583
02:27:20,082 --> 02:27:24,502
all in the heat of anger, with a willful,
conscious desire to hurt or kill?

2584
02:27:24,586 --> 02:27:27,171
I don't remember my action against Quill.

2585
02:27:28,257 --> 02:27:31,843
How long had you known your wife
was running around with Barney Quill?

2586
02:27:33,262 --> 02:27:35,263
I never knew anything like that.

2587
02:27:36,223 --> 02:27:37,849
I trust my wife.

2588
02:27:38,684 --> 02:27:41,519
I suppose you just beat her up occasionally
just for the fun of it.

2589
02:27:41,603 --> 02:27:45,023
Nothing has been established
to permit a question like that.

2590
02:27:45,107 --> 02:27:47,358
He keeps implying things
without ever getting to the point.

2591
02:27:47,443 --> 02:27:50,695
Let him ask the lieutenant,
did he ever beat his wife.

2592
02:27:50,779 --> 02:27:52,739
[Judge Weaver]
I'll sustain the objection.

2593
02:27:52,823 --> 02:27:55,700
Would you like to rephrase
your question, Mr. Dancer?

2594
02:27:56,952 --> 02:27:58,870
No, thank you, Your Honor.

2595
02:27:59,455 --> 02:28:01,372
I've finished.

2596
02:28:01,457 --> 02:28:05,460
Well, then I'll ask him. Did you,
Lieutenant Manion, ever beat your wife...

2597
02:28:05,544 --> 02:28:07,795
on the night of the shooting,
or at any other time?

2598
02:28:07,880 --> 02:28:09,881
- No, sir.
- Is there any doubt in your mind...

2599
02:28:09,965 --> 02:28:12,258
that Barney Quill raped Mrs. Manion?

2600
02:28:12,342 --> 02:28:13,801
- No, sir.
- That's all.

2601
02:28:13,886 --> 02:28:15,887
Step down, Lieutenant.

2602
02:28:22,061 --> 02:28:24,562
- Are we hurt?
- We're hurt bad.

2603
02:28:24,646 --> 02:28:26,564
[Whispering] Paul.

2604
02:28:26,648 --> 02:28:28,566
[Whispering]

2605
02:28:30,152 --> 02:28:32,111
Your Honor, I know time is very pressing.

2606
02:28:32,196 --> 02:28:34,113
I don't want to ask for a recess.

2607
02:28:34,198 --> 02:28:36,240
I would like to leave
the courtroom for a moment.

2608
02:28:36,325 --> 02:28:38,910
If it's important,
we can be at ease for a minute.

2609
02:28:38,994 --> 02:28:40,495
Thank you, sir.

2610
02:28:41,663 --> 02:28:43,915
This is highly irregular, Your Honor.

2611
02:28:43,999 --> 02:28:47,085
Well, there's no reason
to make a federal case out of it.

2612
02:28:57,971 --> 02:28:59,889
Thank you very much, Your Honor.

2613
02:28:59,973 --> 02:29:02,058
We now have another rebuttal witness.

2614
02:29:02,142 --> 02:29:04,227
The defense calls Mary Pilant to the stand.

2615
02:29:04,311 --> 02:29:06,395
Your Honor, we must protest
this whole affair.

2616
02:29:06,480 --> 02:29:09,398
The noble defense attorney
rushes out to a secret conference...

2617
02:29:09,483 --> 02:29:12,527
and now the last-minute witness is being
brought dramatically down the aisle.

2618
02:29:12,611 --> 02:29:15,863
The whole thing has obviously been rigged
to unduly excite the jury.

2619
02:29:15,948 --> 02:29:18,074
It's just another one
of Mr. Biegler's cornball tricks.

2620
02:29:18,158 --> 02:29:21,410
Your Honor, I don't blame
Mr. Dancer for feeling put upon.

2621
02:29:21,495 --> 02:29:24,413
I'm just a humble country lawyer
trying to do the best I can...

2622
02:29:24,498 --> 02:29:28,126
against this brilliant prosecutor
from the big city of Lansing.

2623
02:29:28,210 --> 02:29:29,961
Swear the witness.

2624
02:29:30,504 --> 02:29:32,421
Raise your right hand, please.

2625
02:29:32,506 --> 02:29:34,924
You do solemnly swear the testimony
you shall give in this cause...

2626
02:29:35,008 --> 02:29:38,427
shall be the truth, the whole truth
and nothing but the truth, so help you God?

2627
02:29:38,512 --> 02:29:40,471
- I do.
- Sit down, please.

2628
02:29:43,225 --> 02:29:44,934
Where do you live, Miss Pilant?

2629
02:29:45,018 --> 02:29:46,894
At the Thunder Bay Inn, in Thunder Bay.

2630
02:29:46,979 --> 02:29:50,106
- And how long have you lived there?
- For two years.

2631
02:29:50,190 --> 02:29:53,025
- And what's your profession?
- I manage the inn.

2632
02:29:53,110 --> 02:29:57,613
Now, Miss Pilant, how is the laundry
handled at Thunder Bay Inn?

2633
02:29:57,698 --> 02:29:59,615
It's chuted down to the laundry room.

2634
02:29:59,700 --> 02:30:02,451
Where is the location of that chute
on the second floor?

2635
02:30:02,536 --> 02:30:06,122
- Between room 42 and 43.
- Who lives in those rooms?

2636
02:30:06,206 --> 02:30:09,959
I live in 42. Mr. Quill lived in 43.

2637
02:30:10,043 --> 02:30:12,628
Now, would Mr. Quill,
coming up from the lobby...

2638
02:30:12,713 --> 02:30:16,757
have to pass by the mouth of that chute
on the way to his room?

2639
02:30:16,842 --> 02:30:17,508
Yes.

2640
02:30:17,593 --> 02:30:21,095
Would it be very easy for him to drop
something into that chute as he passed by?

2641
02:30:21,180 --> 02:30:22,138
Yes.

2642
02:30:22,222 --> 02:30:25,892
Have you ever had occasion to go down
into the laundry at any time?

2643
02:30:25,976 --> 02:30:29,520
Yes. Part of my job is to sort
various pieces of laundry...

2644
02:30:29,605 --> 02:30:31,981
as they come out of
the wash-and-dry machine.

2645
02:30:32,065 --> 02:30:33,983
Would you tell the court what you found...

2646
02:30:34,067 --> 02:30:37,486
among those pieces of laundry
on the day after Mr. Quill was killed?

2647
02:30:37,571 --> 02:30:39,822
I found a pair of women's panties.

2648
02:30:39,907 --> 02:30:43,201
- What did you do with them?
- I threw them in the rag bin.

2649
02:30:43,285 --> 02:30:46,662
When did you learn
the significance of those panties?

2650
02:30:46,747 --> 02:30:49,123
Here. This morning in the courtroom.

2651
02:30:49,208 --> 02:30:51,834
And then you went home
and got them out of the rag bin?

2652
02:30:51,919 --> 02:30:53,669
- Yes.
- Did you bring them with you?

2653
02:30:53,754 --> 02:30:55,254
Yes.

2654
02:30:57,257 --> 02:31:00,676
I offer this article of lingerie...

2655
02:31:00,761 --> 02:31:03,179
as exhibit number one for the defense.

2656
02:31:03,263 --> 02:31:06,891
They're white,
they have lace up the side...

2657
02:31:07,935 --> 02:31:09,852
and they're badly torn...

2658
02:31:09,937 --> 02:31:13,689
as if they'd been ripped apart
by powerful hands.

2659
02:31:13,774 --> 02:31:15,733
The label reads...

2660
02:31:16,944 --> 02:31:19,946
"Smart Shop, Phoenix, Arizona."

2661
02:31:20,030 --> 02:31:23,282
If there is no objection,
the exhibit will be received in evidence.

2662
02:31:23,367 --> 02:31:24,367
That's all, Miss Pilant.

2663
02:31:24,451 --> 02:31:26,119
Did you ever talk to Mr.
Lodwick, the prosecuting

2664
02:31:26,120 --> 02:31:27,787
attorney, about the
death of Barney Quill?

2665
02:31:27,871 --> 02:31:31,290
Yes. He came to the hotel several times
after Mr. Quill was killed.

2666
02:31:31,375 --> 02:31:34,710
Did you tell Mr. Lodwick that you didn't
believe Barney Quill had raped Mrs. Manion?

2667
02:31:34,795 --> 02:31:36,837
- Yes, I told him that.
- Now, Miss Pilant...

2668
02:31:36,922 --> 02:31:39,048
did you ever talk to Mr. Biegler,
the defense attorney?

2669
02:31:39,132 --> 02:31:39,840
Yes.

2670
02:31:39,925 --> 02:31:42,260
Was this also in connection with
the shooting of Quill? - Yes.

2671
02:31:42,344 --> 02:31:44,845
Did you tell him you didn't believe
Barney Quill had raped Mrs. Manion?

2672
02:31:44,930 --> 02:31:45,510
Yes.

2673
02:31:45,511 --> 02:31:46,889
How many times did you
talk to Mr. Biegler?

2674
02:31:46,974 --> 02:31:48,891
- Twice.
- When was the last time?

2675
02:31:48,976 --> 02:31:51,394
- Last night.
- And have you now changed your mind?

2676
02:31:51,478 --> 02:31:54,063
Do you now believe
Barney Quill raped Mrs. Manion?

2677
02:31:54,147 --> 02:31:56,732
I... I don't know now.
I think he might have.

2678
02:31:56,817 --> 02:31:58,734
When did you change your mind?
Last night?

2679
02:31:58,819 --> 02:32:00,736
No. No, it was here, this morning.

2680
02:32:00,821 --> 02:32:02,863
When were you given the panties?
Was that last night?

2681
02:32:02,948 --> 02:32:05,075
Now wait a minute!
Now just wait a minute.

2682
02:32:05,076 --> 02:32:07,201
Use the proper form of
objection, Mr. Biegler.

2683
02:32:07,286 --> 02:32:09,245
No, on second thought,
I don't object, Your Honor.

2684
02:32:09,329 --> 02:32:11,372
I'd like the jury to hear her answer.

2685
02:32:11,456 --> 02:32:13,749
- The witness may answer.
- No.

2686
02:32:13,834 --> 02:32:16,460
I was not given the panties,
last night or at any other time.

2687
02:32:16,545 --> 02:32:18,504
I found them exactly as I said.

2688
02:32:18,588 --> 02:32:21,590
Do you know for a fact that Barney Quill
dropped the panties down the chute...

2689
02:32:21,675 --> 02:32:23,592
- or did you just assume it?
- I assumed it.

2690
02:32:23,677 --> 02:32:26,304
Had you thought that perhaps someone
else might have put the panties there...

2691
02:32:26,388 --> 02:32:27,827
someone who wanted them
found in the laundry?

2692
02:32:27,828 --> 02:32:29,265
I hadn't thought of that.

2693
02:32:29,349 --> 02:32:33,769
Mm-hmm. And in the grip of what Mr. Biegler
might call irresistible impulse...

2694
02:32:33,854 --> 02:32:35,771
you rushed in here with the panties...

2695
02:32:35,856 --> 02:32:38,274
because you wanted to crucify the character
of the dead Barney Quill.

2696
02:32:38,358 --> 02:32:40,443
- Isn't that true?
- No. I thought it was my duty.

2697
02:32:40,527 --> 02:32:43,404
- Your pride was hurt, wasn't it?
- I don't know what you mean.

2698
02:32:43,488 --> 02:32:45,364
Your Honor, he's trying
to confuse the witness.

2699
02:32:45,449 --> 02:32:47,700
Let him ask her a question
she can understand.

2700
02:32:47,784 --> 02:32:51,662
Yes, Mr. Dancer, I myself
would like to know what you're driving at.

2701
02:32:51,747 --> 02:32:54,999
Miss Pilant, when you found the panties...

2702
02:32:55,083 --> 02:32:58,669
was your first thought that Barney Quill
might have raped Mrs. Manion...

2703
02:32:58,754 --> 02:33:02,590
or was it that he might
have been stepping out with Mrs. Manion?

2704
02:33:02,674 --> 02:33:04,717
What does he mean?
I don't know what he means.

2705
02:33:04,801 --> 02:33:06,844
Mr. Dancer, once again I must ask you...

2706
02:33:06,928 --> 02:33:09,680
to put straight questions to the witness.

2707
02:33:09,765 --> 02:33:12,099
Here is a straight question, Your Honor.

2708
02:33:12,934 --> 02:33:15,186
Miss Pilant, were you
Barney Quill's mistress?

2709
02:33:15,187 --> 02:33:17,438
No! No, I was not!

2710
02:33:17,522 --> 02:33:20,066
You know it's common knowledge
in Thunder Bay you were living with Quill?

2711
02:33:20,150 --> 02:33:21,984
That's not true! Barney Quill was...

2712
02:33:22,069 --> 02:33:24,362
Was what, Miss Pilant?

2713
02:33:24,446 --> 02:33:26,697
Barney Quill was what, Miss Pilant?

2714
02:33:28,617 --> 02:33:30,701
Barney Quill was my father.

2715
02:33:30,786 --> 02:33:32,703
[Spectators Murmuring]

2716
02:33:42,798 --> 02:33:44,715
No more questions, Your Honor.

2717
02:33:44,800 --> 02:33:46,884
That's all for me.

2718
02:33:47,761 --> 02:33:50,054
The witness may step down.

2719
02:33:50,138 --> 02:33:52,056
We will recess for 15 minutes...

2720
02:33:52,140 --> 02:33:55,226
after which we will hear
the closing arguments.

2721
02:33:55,310 --> 02:33:59,563
If possible, I would like
to charge the jury before nightfall.

2722
02:34:03,819 --> 02:34:05,736
## [Piano: Jazz]

2723
02:34:14,996 --> 02:34:17,415
Think they're gonna stay out all night?

2724
02:34:32,514 --> 02:34:35,141
Can't somebody say something?

2725
02:34:37,018 --> 02:34:39,437
What do you want me to say, Maida, darling?

2726
02:34:39,521 --> 02:34:41,605
Tell me we're gonna win.

2727
02:34:42,941 --> 02:34:46,777
I'm counting on getting
that promissory note from the lieutenant.

2728
02:34:46,862 --> 02:34:48,779
I hope we can borrow some money on it.

2729
02:34:48,864 --> 02:34:51,282
I need a new typewriter.

2730
02:34:51,366 --> 02:34:54,785
Half the time the "P" and the "F"
don't strike on mine.

2731
02:34:55,370 --> 02:34:59,999
"Party of the first part"
sometimes comes out "arty of the irst art."

2732
02:35:00,834 --> 02:35:03,544
Doesn't make sense.
It's embarrassing.

2733
02:35:03,628 --> 02:35:05,963
"Arty of the irst art"?

2734
02:35:06,047 --> 02:35:08,132
I kind of like that.

2735
02:35:08,216 --> 02:35:10,134
It has a ring to it.

2736
02:35:13,221 --> 02:35:16,307
Twelve people go off into a room.

2737
02:35:17,476 --> 02:35:21,645
Twelve different minds,
12 different hearts...

2738
02:35:21,730 --> 02:35:24,565
from 12 different walks of life.

2739
02:35:25,233 --> 02:35:28,986
Twelve sets of eyes,
ears, shapes and sizes.

2740
02:35:29,654 --> 02:35:31,989
And these 12 people...

2741
02:35:32,073 --> 02:35:35,159
are asked to judge another human being...

2742
02:35:35,243 --> 02:35:38,746
as different from them
as they are from each other.

2743
02:35:38,830 --> 02:35:43,834
And in their judgment they must become
of one mind... unanimous.

2744
02:35:45,545 --> 02:35:49,882
It's one of the miracles of man's
disorganized soul that they can do it.

2745
02:35:50,509 --> 02:35:53,010
And in most instances, do it right well.

2746
02:35:54,763 --> 02:35:57,723
God bless juries.

2747
02:35:58,975 --> 02:36:01,685
I don't know what I'd do
if I were on that jury.

2748
02:36:05,273 --> 02:36:07,816
I really don't know.

2749
02:36:08,693 --> 02:36:09,860
Do you?

2750
02:36:10,862 --> 02:36:12,821
[Chuckling]

2751
02:36:14,449 --> 02:36:16,534
I loved that, Polly.

2752
02:36:16,618 --> 02:36:19,745
I loved that "humble country lawyer" bit.

2753
02:36:19,829 --> 02:36:23,207
[Laughing]
You had Mr. Dancer dancing.

2754
02:36:23,959 --> 02:36:25,709
I'm afraid he got in the last dance.

2755
02:36:25,794 --> 02:36:28,254
That's the best summary
I've ever heard in a courtroom.

2756
02:36:28,338 --> 02:36:30,881
I liked yours much better, Polly.

2757
02:36:35,971 --> 02:36:37,888
Do you have to play that stuff?

2758
02:36:37,973 --> 02:36:41,225
Can't you play "Danny Boy,"
or "Sweet Isle of Innisfree"?

2759
02:36:41,309 --> 02:36:44,228
## ["Danny Boy" In Upbeat, Jazzy Style]

2760
02:36:48,650 --> 02:36:50,568
[Phone Ringing]

2761
02:36:55,323 --> 02:36:57,241
Paul Biegler's office.

2762
02:36:57,325 --> 02:36:59,410
Yes, sir. Right away.

2763
02:36:59,494 --> 02:37:01,412
- [Handset Settles In Cradle]
- They're ready.

2764
02:37:11,172 --> 02:37:13,090
[Laura] Hey, sweetie!

2765
02:37:14,342 --> 02:37:16,594
Go on, go on.

2766
02:37:16,678 --> 02:37:19,430
- The jury's coming in.
- Yeah, I heard.

2767
02:37:19,514 --> 02:37:22,600
You can tell my lovin' husband
I'll be waiting in the car.

2768
02:37:22,684 --> 02:37:25,102
- You're sure he's gonna come out?
- Oh, sure.

2769
02:37:25,186 --> 02:37:27,104
[Giggles] He's lucky.

2770
02:37:27,188 --> 02:37:29,440
Some people have all the luck.

2771
02:37:29,524 --> 02:37:33,777
You can tell him I'm waiting
to get kicked to kingdom come.

2772
02:37:33,862 --> 02:37:37,615
Oh. Hey, sweetie, I have
a souvenir for you.

2773
02:37:37,699 --> 02:37:39,783
[Chuckles]

2774
02:37:39,868 --> 02:37:43,621
Well, now, you better keep that.
You might need it again sometime.

2775
02:37:43,705 --> 02:37:46,957
- You never know.
- No, you don't, do you?

2776
02:37:47,042 --> 02:37:48,959
Oh, I like you, Polly.

2777
02:37:55,925 --> 02:37:59,720
I warn all those present
not to interrupt the taking of the verdict.

2778
02:37:59,804 --> 02:38:02,473
I will stop the proceedings
and clear the courtroom...

2779
02:38:02,557 --> 02:38:04,975
if there is any demonstration.

2780
02:38:13,735 --> 02:38:15,319
Proceed, Mr. Clerk.

2781
02:38:15,904 --> 02:38:20,074
Members of the jury, have you agreed upon a
verdict, and if so, who will speak for you?

2782
02:38:20,158 --> 02:38:22,076
We have. I'm the foreman.

2783
02:38:22,160 --> 02:38:23,994
[Judge Weaver]
The defendant will rise.

2784
02:38:26,414 --> 02:38:28,332
What is your verdict?

2785
02:38:28,416 --> 02:38:31,168
We find the defendant not guilty
by reason of insanity.

2786
02:38:31,252 --> 02:38:35,506
- [Spectators Cheering]
- [Gavel Rapping]

2787
02:38:37,425 --> 02:38:39,677
Maida gave you that promissory note,
didn't she?

2788
02:38:39,761 --> 02:38:43,347
Right here,
ready to be signed by our happy client.

2789
02:38:43,431 --> 02:38:47,351
You know, I used to think the world
looked better through a glass of whiskey.

2790
02:38:47,435 --> 02:38:49,520
It doesn't.

2791
02:38:49,604 --> 02:38:51,522
I think I'll keep it this way.

2792
02:38:51,606 --> 02:38:53,107
Looks nice.

2793
02:38:53,775 --> 02:38:56,527
Well, I got one good thing
out of this case...

2794
02:38:57,529 --> 02:39:00,823
a new law partner,
if it's all right with him.

2795
02:39:01,449 --> 02:39:05,202
He'd be mighty proud to have his name
on a shingle with yours.

2796
02:39:34,983 --> 02:39:37,234
I guess you're looking for Lieutenant
Manion, aren't you, Mr. Biegler?

2797
02:39:37,318 --> 02:39:39,903
- Yeah.
- He gave me this note for you.

2798
02:39:41,823 --> 02:39:45,325
Felt real sorry for Mrs. Manion.
She was crying.

2799
02:39:45,827 --> 02:39:47,745
Left a mess, didn't they?

2800
02:39:47,829 --> 02:39:49,747
Well, we'd better get busy here.

2801
02:39:49,831 --> 02:39:53,584
"Dear Mr. Biegler.
So sorry, but I had to leave suddenly.

2802
02:39:53,668 --> 02:39:58,255
I was seized by an irresistible impulse.
Frederick Manion."

2803
02:39:59,591 --> 02:40:02,259
Now, how in the world
are we gonna face Maida?

2804
02:40:03,344 --> 02:40:05,262
Gin.

2805
02:40:05,346 --> 02:40:07,765
I knew there was something
wrong with that guy.

2806
02:40:07,849 --> 02:40:10,601
Never saw a gin drinker
yet you could trust.

2807
02:40:11,686 --> 02:40:14,772
Well, partner, what do you say
we go and see our first client?

2808
02:40:14,856 --> 02:40:16,940
- Who might that be?
- Mary Pilant.

2809
02:40:17,025 --> 02:40:19,443
We're gonna administer
Barney Quill's estate.

2810
02:40:19,527 --> 02:40:23,113
Now that's what I call
poetic justice for everybody.

2811
02:40:24,866 --> 02:40:26,366
Yeah.